<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--SharkAttack     03-10 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Shark Attack,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surfer Dies After Shark Drags Him From Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surfer was killed after a shark
dragged him from his board while bathers watched in horror at a
popular South Australia beach, police said today.
   Police said the injured surfer died as his friend towed him 200
yards to the beach. The attack came while the two men surfed off
Waitpinga Beach, 50 miles south of Adelaide, just before dusk
Thursday.
   Police said the victim, 27-year-old Matthew Foale, was dangling
his leg in the water when the shark grabbed it and dragged him
underwater.
   An autopsy was to be held later today to determine cause of
death, which may be drowning or loss of blood from a severed artery,
officials said.
   South Australian waters are notorious for shark attacks. In
October, a shark dragged a teen-ager from his surfboard but the boy
escaped by punching the shark on the snout. He needed more than 110
stitches for wounds to his leg.
</TEXT>
