<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Libraries     03-10 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Libraries,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Poles, Libraries Are Window On The West</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One U.S. Embassy librarian remembers
handing a copy of Billboard magazine through an iron gate, past a
militiaman, to a young Pole interested in keeping up with the
Western pop music scene.
   It was a time of martial law and authorities frowned on such
things.
   During that bitter winter of 1981-82, and for years before and
after, the library at the U.S. Embassy and ones run by British and
French institutes have been virtually the only source of Western
news, books and magazines for Poles.
   The official information lock has eased some.
   Authorities no longer bother to check luggage at airports, video
stores are opening in Warsaw, the jamming of foreign broadcasts has
ended, satellite dishes bring a world full of signals into the
country, an underground press publishes vigorously, and the official
media provide a broader range of views.
   But still no Western newspapers are on sale regularly in Warsaw,
and Newsweek magazine circulates a few hundred copies for a country
of nearly 38 million.
   At the U.S. Embassy library, however, anyone can come in for
English-language fiction, magazines ranging from House &amp; Garden to
Fortune, college catalogues, reference works or even American
telephone books.
   ``This library is very famous because books are here that you
cannot get anywhere else,'' said a woman researching her doctoral
thesis on Martin Luther King Jr.
   The U.S. Information Agency pays for embassy libraries worldwide,
spending about $15,000 annually to stock the Warsaw branch.
   In Poland, the agency also supports smaller reading rooms at U.S.
Consulates in Krakow and Poznan and a scholarly study center at
Warsaw University.
   The embassy library has about 8,000 volumes of fiction and
non-fiction and 136 magazines, covering ``wide spectrum of political
thought ... from National Review to New Republic,'' said Alice
Lemaistre, the U.S. cultural officer.
   She describes the library as a way of ``filling in the gaps'' in
Poles' understanding of the United States.
   She said it is important, for example, that Poles considering
emigrating to the United States understand how much housing costs.
   The British Institute, which operates independently of the
British Embassy, runs a 28,000-volume library in Warsaw and branches
in four cities.
   Planes carrying books were among the first to arrive in the
post-World War II relief operation, said the institute's director,
Richard Alford.
   ``It was a much more risky proposition for Poles to come here
during the (Stalinist) 1950s,'' said Alford. ``Now, nobody thinks
twice about it.''
   One patron during the relatively relaxed 1970s recalls the
American library as the ``in'' place to be seen for high school
students studying English.
   The British library has a computer link to a Western database for
research that had been running for only a few days in 1981 before
martial law was declared and communications links cut.
   The re-established system serves Polish scholars whose libraries
do not have the money to buy specialized books and journals from the
West.
   Militia officers posted outside the U.S. Embassy discouraged
library use during martial-law, and the government press reported,
falsely, that it was closed.
   Still, Poles came. Testimony to their determination is the worn
copy of Herman Wouk's ``The Caine Mutiny'' with the library card
recording a due date of Jan. 4, 1982, three weeks after martial law
was imposed.
   Now, about 4,300 people have library cards at the U.S. libary and
up to 150 people pass through the embassy metal detector to use it
daily.
   Newsweek, Time and the International Herald Tribune, which is
published in Paris, are ``read to death,'' said Ms. Lamaistre.
   One day recently, a Polish music writer was catching up on
Rolling Stone magazine, and a student was checking out ``Trouble
Spots of English Grammar.''
   Art, theater and film _ both libraries show movies in English _
are favorite topics and computer magazines are newly popular.
   Also well-thumbed are copies of such decorating magazines as
Metropolitan Home and do-it-yourself guides, a result of the
improvisation that takes over when the store shelves are empty.
   ``There is a voracious appetite for anything in the way of
Western literature,'' said Runnall Davis, head of the British
Council Library where about 90 percent of the 7,000 fiction titles
are on loan at any time.
   ``We are a window to the West,'' he said. ``This is one place
where Poles can come and see things from a different point of view.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
