<DOCNO> AP890310-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SlappingSuspension     03-10 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slapping Suspension,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nigerian Student Suspended over Child Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nigerian medical student charged with
child abuse who says he was only disciplining his daughter in a way
acceptable in his culture has been suspended by the University of
Florida for one year.
   The decision by Art Sandeen, vice president for student affairs,
means Fons Amaye-Obu is suspended from classes until after the
spring semester of 1990, the student's attorney, Horace Moore, said
Wednesday.
   Moore is appealing the decision to university Provost Bob Bryan,
who is to become acting president later this month.
   Amaye-Obu, 34, faces criminal charges of aggravated child abuse
since his 15-year-old daughter accused him of beating her in August
at their campus apartment.
   Amaye-Obu, saying the university has no right to intervene in
family affairs, appealed his case to Sandeen after the Student
Conduct Committee recommended expulsion.
   Under the suspension, Amaye-Obu could graduate after returning in
the summer of next year. A fourth-year student, he lacks only two
months of school and a medical internship before completing his
medical education.
   Amaye-Obu, separated from the girl's mother, said he struck his
daughter after she shouted at him when he asked her to put dinner on
the table. The police report says the girl's eyelids and lips were
swollen and she had a bruised nose, which Amaye-Obu denies.
   Moore said he showed Sandeen that the daughter had good grades
when she was living with her father, but has not done as well in
school since moving out last fall.
   ``It appears as though we've totally disregarded his daughter's
welfare and need for strong parental guidance,'' Moore said.
</TEXT>
