<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TowerDownfall Bjt   03-10 1018</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Downfall, Bjt,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>John Tower: The Bitterest Wine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His adversaries, even a few subordinates, used
to call him the Littlest Caesar in Washington, a nickname as
prophetic as it was derisive. In the end, just shy of the ides of
March, John Tower was done in by his fellow patricians in the Senate.
   He wanted so badly to crown his public career as secretary of
defense he even swore abstinence, sort of, from the nectar of grape
and grain. A Texas friend, George Bush, continued to swear by him.
But those oaths were not enough to win Tower the oath of office.
   The Senate's 53-47 vote late Thursday sealed the first rejection
in history of a Cabinet nominee of a newly elected president. More
astonishing to some is that the Senate turned against one of its
own, a four-termer who once headed the very committee, Armed
Services, that dealt the cruelest blow by declaring him, on a
largely party-line vote, unfit.
   Tower, 63, surely is among the least surprised that knives were
drawn by his former colleagues in the once-fabled, self-protective
society of the Senate, which never before had rejected a former
senator for an executive post.
   Twenty-two years ago, Tower waged a lonely battle against the
censure of Democratic Sen. Thomas Dodd, the late father of current
Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut. He recalled then that Sen.
Prescott Bush, another Connecticut senator and the late father of
the president, had once been asked by a young woman if senators
really were courteous and deferential to each other, regardless of
political belief.
   ``He replied: `Yes, young lady, it is true ... but when one of us
breaks a leg, we eat him.'''
   Broken leg or not, Tower may have been particularly vulnerable to
those carnivorous instincts. He left the Senate in 1985 with an
especially low reservoir of good will for a departing committee
chairman.
   He had monumental confrontations with leaders of his own party,
much less the Democrats who watched him ram Ronald Reagan's massive
defense budgets through the Senate. He waged jurisdictional wars
with other Republican chairmen, and few members were spared his acid
tongue in floor debates.
   Indeed, the only Senate club that John Tower seemed to care about
was the one he figuratively carried on his shoulder. Compromise was
not his cup of tea. He once refused, even, to shake hands with the
Democratic congressman, Robert Krueger, who dared run against him in
1978.
   ``John Tower is a former member of the Senate, but it is probably
also the case that he doesn't have a lot of intimate friends here or
any aura of popularity or good will,'' said Republican Sen. Richard
Luger of Indiana. ``He is not necessarily a person who ingratiates
himself with anybody.''
   Still, he fared well with the electorate of Texas, which put him
into the Senate in 1961 when the Republican Party could have held
its state conventions in a phone booth. He won three more terms
before retiring from the Senate in 1985.
   He didn't lack for cockiness. At a 1979 costume party in Dallas,
the 5-foot-6 Tower turned up in a Superman suit, a rare departure
from his tailored pinstriped suits and Saville Row cotton shirts.
``I was born to play Superman,'' he said. ``I'm a man who stands for
truth, justice and the American way.''
   To him that meant bashing liberal Democrats for ``creeping
socialism,'' supporting a greater war effort in Vietnam _ he still
believes the United States should have won _ and striving for
military superiority, not just parity, against the Soviet Union.
   Twice divorced, he was long the subject of rumors about his
personal life. His second wife, Lilla, divorced him in 1987 after
charging him with ``marital misconduct.'' Last week, he acknowledged
only that he had broken his wedding vows.
   But stories about his drinking were the most damaging. Tower at
first denied that he'd had a problem with alcohol. Later he admitted
that he was ``a pretty good scotch drinker'' in the 1970s but said
he drank only moderately in recent years, mainly wine.
   Others didn't see it that way. The FBI, according to Sen. Ernest
F. Hollings, D-S.C., turned up ``corroborated facts _ with words
`crocked,' `bombed,' `excessive drinking,' `sloshing,' `stoned,'
`comatose' ...''
   Many of those accounts came from sources with little or no
credibility. But several came from Americans with no apparent ax to
grind with Tower, even former aides and defense industry executives.
   Though his confirmation hearings opened with a tide of good will,
many senators became disturbed by Tower's dodginess and pattern of
denial over the alcohol issue. He admitted to ``excessive
drinking,'' but steadfastly asserted he had not ``abused'' alcohol.
He claimed his switch from scotch to wine was evidence of
moderation, a refrain often heard from problem drinkers who fail to
acknowledge that average servings of wine, beer or liquor all have
the same alcoholic content. He took a pledge of abstinence, but
conditioned it on confirmation _ he continued to drink wine, he
said, in the meantime. To some, that too smacked of the problem
drinker's claim that he or she can quit any time _ but not just now.
   Then too, there were concerns about Tower's coziness with the
defense industry, especially in light of his million-dollar-plus
earnings as a consultant for the likes of Martin Marietta, LTV,
Rockwell and Textron. Between those jobs, he took on two key
assignments from Reagan, first as a strategic arms negotiator, then
as head of the presidential panel that investigated the Iran-Contra
scandal.
   Even his severest critics gave him high marks for his Iran-Contra
report, but the reviews were mixed about his stint in Geneva, where
Tower apparently was bored as a negotiator with the Soviets. More
troubling, according to Democrats, was Tower's own testimony that he
later counseled defense contractors on their sales prospects in
light of his perception of the likely outcome of those confidential
talks. Tower denied that he shared any secrets or that any conflict
of interest was involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
