<DOCNO> AP890310-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland Bjt   03-10 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says Free National Elections Only First Step</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders praised a government
agreement to create a new national legislature with freely elected
members, but they say open elections on the local level must be the
next step toward true democracy.
   Government and opposition negotiators, in a breakthrough that
could give Poland the first democratic national elections in the
communist bloc, agreed Thursday to add a second chamber of
parliament open to all candidates.
   The agreement also calls for 35 percent of the seats in the
existing parliament, the Seijm, to be open to opposition candidates.
   Additionally, the sides agreed in principle to establish a post
of president who would be elected by a majority of both chambers of
Parliament, which would form the National Assembly.
   Opposition figures cautioned that the tentaive reforms only are a
first step toward substantive democratic reform.
   ``If the process of the democratization is to work, it must
include solutions of such problems as local governments which would
be elected in completely free elections,'' said Bronislaw Geremek,
head of the opposition group negotiating with the government on
political reform.
   He also called for opposition access to mass media and freedom to
create associations.
   ``Such reform cannot begin and end at the top authorities,''
opposition negotiator Zbigniew Bujak told state television late
Thursday. ``It must also be made from the bottom.''
   Authorities have insisted on elections in June, leaving the
independents little time to mount effective campaigns.
   Candidates for the new parliamentary chamber, provisionally
called the ``senate,'' can be nominated by an existing group or
gather 5,000 signatures to run, said Janusz Reykowski, a government
negotiator.
   Reykowski is the leader of the government side on the working
group dealing with political reforms, part of the broader talks
between opposition and the government on Poland's future.
   Opposition negotiators said the number of members in the future
sentate still remained to be negotiated.
   They also said the agreement on free elections to the senate was
part of a trade-off for conceding that Poland would have a strong
presidency, which likely would remain in Communist Party control.
   The powers of the president still are to be debated, but the idea
is to combine in the presidency powers now held by the Council of
State, such as appointing the head of the army and names
ambassadors. The president also would be able to dissolve parliament
and call new elections.
   There has been wide speculation that if a presidency is
established, the post would be filled by communist party First
Secretary Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   Reykowski said the proposed new election law would be submitted
to the Sejm as early as next week. The communist party now has an
absolute majority in the Sejm and any laws proposed by the party are
assured passage.
   The electoral changes are part of a package of political and
economic reforms being negotiated since Feb. 6 at the talks between
the authorities and opposition.
   The talks also have resulted in tentative agreement to restore
the banned trade union Solidarity, the farmers' union rural
Solidarity and the Independent Students' Association.
   Solidarity, under the leadership of Lech Walesa, had refused to
come to the negotiating table until the communist party agreed in
principle to restore its legal status, stripped away after the
December 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   Both sides must agree to the entire package for the reforms to
take effect. After a meeting with government officials on Tuesday,
Walesa said the two sides hope to complete work and sign a new
national accord April 3.
   Geremek said entering free elections poses risks for both sides.
   The communist authorities for the first time face ``a test of the
basis of the ruling coaliton.'' But the opposition is at risk
because it is ``completely unprepared'' for competition at the polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0510EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BushFallout Bjt   03-10 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Fallout, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Asserts Itself, Quickly, in Tower Episode</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's defeat on the nomination of
John Tower demonstrates that a Congress dominated by Democrats is
not afraid of him and stands ready to trade blows with the White
House in other tests of power.
   For Bush, the best thing about the long and messy ordeal over
Tower was that it finally came to an end. After a bitter six-day
debate, the Senate killed Tower's hopes of running the Pentagon on a
53-47 vote.
   For weeks, the struggle over Tower had sapped the energy of
Bush's new White House, requiring countless telephone calls and
trips to Capitol Hill by chief of staff John Sununu.
   Allegations against Tower of excessive drinking, womanizing and
conflict of interest with defense contractors diverted attention
from subjects Bush wanted to highlight, and the whole episode
provoked charges of White House bungling.
   Even though Bush insisted the allegations against Tower were
groundless, the nomination reinforced the notion that Bush sometimes
has a blind spot when it comes to picking the right people.
   The White House version of events made it sound as if Tower's
defeat wasn't such a bad thing, after all.
   ``Out of this struggle has come a good unity with the Republican
Party,'' said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater. ``We
brought the administration team together and we feel that it's been
a tempering affair that should serve us well as we move forward.''
   Bush did show that even though the odds were against him, he
didn't back down and yank Tower's nomination. He made a stand for
loyalty and the right of a president to pick his own men.
   But the bottom line, of course, was that Bush was defeated in his
first showdown with Congress.
   In the first three months to six months, a new president develops
an image that becomes a stereotype. ``This is beginning to shape
that image in the wrong way for Bush,'' said Norm Ornstein, a
specialist in the presidency at the American Enterprise Institute.
``It's not fully formed yet but a few more things like this and
he'll have a very bad image he'll have to overcome.''
   Moreover, Ornstein said, ``The degree of respect and fear that
every president wants in his relationship with Congress is not going
to be there as much'' after Tower's defeat.
   For world leaders, Bush's loss could be a source of uneasiness.
   ``It tells them they're dealing with a weaker president than
Ronald Reagan,'' said William Schneider, a political analyst at AEI.
``If you reach a deal with this man, will it stick? Can he sell it
to Congress?''
   Richard Brody, a Stanford University political science professor,
said Tower's defeat may make Bush more cautious on other
nominations, particularly in choosing Supreme Court candidates if
vacancies arise.
   ``With the Democrats _ cutting across ideological lines _ willing
to hang together on this one, it may signal that Supreme Court
nominees are not going to get a free ride,'' Brody said.
   Mindful that the Democrats run Congress and that he'll have to
deal with them again, Bush carefully refrained from doing anything
that would drive a wedge between the White House and Congress.
   He held back on some weapons that are available to the president.
For instance, there were no televised addresses from the Oval Office
on Tower's behalf, no direct challenge to any of Tower's critics.
   Bush seems eager to close the book on the whole affair. ``We owe
it to the American people to come together and move forward,'' Bush
said after the vote.
   Senate Democrats said they, too, did not want the Tower fight to
ruin relations with Bush. Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman
Sam Nunn and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell made a hurried
telephone call to Bush after the vote, pledging to work in a
cooperative and productive spirit.
   ``This doesn't represent an effort to be harmful to the
president,'' Mitchell told reporters. ``I hope and believe we can
work together on important matters. The tension of this issue will
have no long-lasting effect on the relationship.''
   No one suggests that Tower's defeat has crippled Bush. The public
didn't seem much interested, and Bush's popularity remains high in
public opinion polls.
   Raymond Wolfinger, a political scientist at the University of
California at Berkeley, said Tower may have been merely ``teething
troubles'' for Bush. ``Lots of presidents learn from mistakes early
in their administration.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terence Hunt has covered the White House since
1981 and is the AP's chief White House correspondent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
