<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     03-10 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Opera Presents Enjoyable `Onegin'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tchaikovsky's ``Eugene Onegin'' _ not heard at
the Metropolitan Opera since the 1984-85 season _ returned with a
cast that assures a satisfying evening.
   All the principals were announced as singing their roles for the
first time at the Met, but soprano Mirella Freni had the flu so
Tatyana was sung by Makvala Kasrashvili, a native of the Soviet
Union who made her Met debut as Tatyana in 1979.
   Her voice is splendidly suited to the part. Her soft notes and
high notes are especially lovely.
   Sandra Walker of Richmond, as her sister Olga, has a
mezzo-soprano so rich she sounds more matronly than girlish, but yet
it's a beautiful voice.
   Both acted well. Miss Kasrashvili conveyed a young woman, not
sought out by men, who suddenly awakens into love with the
well-dressed stranger, Onegin. Miss Walker's acting also was
effective. In the Act 2 party when Onegin dances with Olga because
he's bored, she's a bit excited about flirting with him.
   Jorma Hynninen of Finland sang Onegin pleasingly and Jerry Hadley
of Princeton, Ill., was excellent as Olga's jealous fiance. Hadley's
singing sounded Italian sometimes in the first act but he was clear,
forthright and ringing in Act 2, which ends with him shot by Onegin
in a duel.
   Other notable singers who added to the evening's enjoyment were
bass Nicolai Ghiaurov of Bulgaria, who appears in Act 3 as Tatyana's
husband, Gweneth Bean of Battle Creek, Mich., as Tatyana's nurse in
Act 1 and Michel Senechal of Paris who has one aria, in French, as
Tatyana's tutor.
   Andrew Litton of New York, principal conductor of the
Bournemouth, England, Symphony, was making his Met debut. Instead of
trying for the rousing, he drew out and savored orchestral
interludes. He held the orchestra quiet while singers held final
notes as long as they wished. He conducted some of the arias so
slowly one wondered whether the singers had difficulty.
   The scenery for ``Eugene Onegin'' dates back to 1957. The
production was revised in 1977 with new staging, costumes and
choreography for six couples at Act 2 and 3 parties. The revised
production changed the language of presentation from English to the
original Russian.
</TEXT>
