<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0504EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TowerFallout Bjt   03-10 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Fallout, Bjt,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0430 to make slug conform to PM-News Digest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Asserts Itself, Quickly, in Tower Episode</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's defeat on the nomination of
John Tower demonstrates that a Congress dominated by Democrats is
not afraid of him and stands ready to trade blows with the White
House in other tests of power.
   For Bush, the best thing about the long and messy ordeal over
Tower was that it finally came to an end. After a bitter six-day
debate, the Senate killed Tower's hopes of running the Pentagon on a
53-47 vote.
   For weeks, the struggle over Tower had sapped the energy of
Bush's new White House, requiring countless telephone calls and
trips to Capitol Hill by chief of staff John Sununu.
   Allegations against Tower of excessive drinking, womanizing and
conflict of interest with defense contractors diverted attention
from subjects Bush wanted to highlight, and the whole episode
provoked charges of White House bungling.
   Even though Bush insisted the allegations against Tower were
groundless, the nomination reinforced the notion that Bush sometimes
has a blind spot when it comes to picking the right people.
   The White House version of events made it sound as if Tower's
defeat wasn't such a bad thing, after all.
   ``Out of this struggle has come a good unity with the Republican
Party,'' said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater. ``We
brought the administration team together and we feel that it's been
a tempering affair that should serve us well as we move forward.''
   Bush did show that even though the odds were against him, he
didn't back down and yank Tower's nomination. He made a stand for
loyalty and the right of a president to pick his own men.
   But the bottom line, of course, was that Bush was defeated in his
first showdown with Congress.
   In the first three months to six months, a new president develops
an image that becomes a stereotype. ``This is beginning to shape
that image in the wrong way for Bush,'' said Norm Ornstein, a
specialist in the presidency at the American Enterprise Institute.
``It's not fully formed yet but a few more things like this and
he'll have a very bad image he'll have to overcome.''
   Moreover, Ornstein said, ``The degree of respect and fear that
every president wants in his relationship with Congress is not going
to be thee as much'' after Tower's defeat.
   For world leaders, Bush's loss could be a source of uneasiness.
   ``It tells them they're dealing with a weaker president than
Ronald Reagan,'' said William Schneider, a political analyst at AEI.
``If you reach a deal with this man, will it stick? Can he sell it
to Congress?''
   Richard Brody, a Stanford University political science professor,
said Tower's defeat may make Bush more cautious on other
nominations, particularly in choosing Supreme Court candidates if
vacancies arise.
   ``With the Democrats _ cutting across ideological lines _ willing
to hang together on this one, it may signal that Supreme Court
nominees are not going to get a free ride,'' Brody said.
   Mindful that the Democrats run Congress and that he'll have to
deal with them again, Bush carefully refrained from doing anything
that would drive a wedge between the White House and Congress.
   He held back on some weapons that are available to the president.
For instance, there were no televised addresses from the Oval Office
on Tower's behalf, no direct challenge to any of Tower's critics.
   Bush seems eager to close the book on the whole affair. ``We owe
it to the American people to come together and move forward,'' Bush
said after the vote.
   Senate Democrats said they, too, did not want the Tower fight to
ruin relations with Bush. Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman
Sam Nunn and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell made a hurried
telephone call to Bush after the vote, pledging to work in a
cooperative and productive spirit.
   ``This doesn't represent an effort to be harmful to the
president,'' Mitchell told reporters. ``I hope and believe we can
work together on important matters. The tension of this issue will
have no long-lasting effect on the relationship.''
   No one suggests that Tower's defeat has crippled Bush. The public
didn't seem much interested, and Bush's popularity remains high in
public opinion polls.
   Raymond Wolfinger, a political scientist at the University of
California at Berkeley, said Tower may have been merely ``teething
troubles'' for Bush. ``Lots of presidents learn from mistakes early
in their administration.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terence Hunt has covered the White House since
1981 and is the AP's chief White House correspondent.
</TEXT>
