<FIRST>r w PM-BetterSchools     03-10 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Better Schools,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools Can be Improved with Little Spending, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An influential education group is trying to
convince President Bush that he can bring about dramatic school
improvements with little or no extra spending if he adopts its
prescriptions for change.
   ``First, go for quality. Second, reward success in producing
quality. Third ... let the people on the firing line figure out how
to get the job done and get rid of as much of the bureacracy ... as
possible,'' says the blueprint released Thursday by the National
Center on Education and the Economy.
   The report calls on Bush to set ambitious national math and
science performance goals that match or exceed those of students
anywhere in the world.
   It also recommends letting some school districts use federal
money more freely, waiving the usual red tape and regulations in
favor of innovative local plans for as long as students continue to
progress. The successful projects would serve as models to reform
basic federal programs later on.
   New emphasis and cooperation among all levels of government in
the areas of day care, early childhood education and workforce
literacy are also envisioned in the report, called ``To Secure Our
Future: The Federal Role in Education.''
   Apple Computer Chairman John Sculley, chairman of the center
board, said the report has been presented to Bush, White House chief
of staff John Sununu and education secretary Lauro Cavazos.
   Speaking by telephone hookup to a news conference, Sculley said
he did not know whether any of the proposals would be included in an
omnibus education bill now being drafted at the White House.
   But Sculley said Bush was ``extremely interested in what we had
to say'' when he was given a draft last December. ``We do believe we
have the president's ear in terms of how important it is for him to
come out early in his term for massive education reform.''
   The report comes three years after the center, then known as the
Carnegie Forum on Education and Economy, released a highly respected
plan to upgrade the teaching profession. Among the members of its
high-powered board are former North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt, former
labor secretary Ray Marshall and pollster Lou Harris. The honorary
chairman is New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   The two major teacher unions responded positively to the group's
latest effort.
   ``While respecting the need for certain regulations, the report
suggests we unhandcuff the system for greater creativity,'' said
Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers.
   Mary Futrell, president of the National Education Association,
said the report correctly stresses the need for federal
encouragement of restructuring.
   ``We also agree that proposed changes in distribution of federal
monies and programs must first be thoroughly tested, on an
experimental pilot basis, before existing regulatory and legislative
processes are modified,'' she said.
   The cornerstone of the report is its proposal to let school
districts design initiatives to improve student performance, ease
the transition from school to work for potential dropouts, and
coordinate social services for disadvantaged students. The money
would come from existing programs in the Labor, Education, Justice
and Health and Human Services departments.
   Local communities, if their proposals were approved by the state
and federal governments, ``would be free to combine the available
state and federal funds as they wish. ... They would continue to be
free of the prevailing rules and regulations as long as they were
meeting the (performance) targets they had set.''
   The other major recommendations:
   _Bush should ``identify the best (math and science) performance
anywhere in the world and resolve as a nation to meet it or beat
it,'' said center president Marc Tucker. The report suggests several
strategies, including a revamped curriculum and a national center to
teach teachers technology.
   _State, federal and local agencies should combine resources for
high-quality full-time day care, preschool child development centers
and before and after school care programs. Poor kids should not be
permitted to enter kindergarten ``as damaged goods, already marked
for failure.''
   _The country must stop treating adult illiteracy as a personal
misfortune ``rather than the threat to the nation's standard of
living that it really is.'' The problem can't be solved by
volunteers, nor can employers be expected to foot the whole bill.
</TEXT>
