<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     03-10 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Timetable on S&amp;Ls Slipping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 45-day deadline that President Bush gave
Congress for enacting his $90 billion savings and loan rescue
package is slipping _ and by months rather than days.
   Despite losses mounting at an estimated $33 million a day, it has
been more than a month since Bush asked for action by April 1 and
none of the appropriate congressional committees has even begun
writing a bill.
   While the administration outlined the basic aspects of Bush's
proposals just prior to his budget address Feb. 9, the details were
not delivered to Congress until two weeks later.
   Both the House and Senate banking committees, which have the
primary jurisdiction, are not scheduled to begin drafting
legislation until after Congress returns April 3 from an Easter
recess.
   But because Bush's package calls for taxpayers to pick up $50
billion of the tab _ at an estimated cost four to six times that
amount over the next 30 years since the money will be borrowed _ at
least half a dozen other committees are demanding a say once the
banking panels are through.
   The tax-writing House Ways and Means and Senate Finance
committees are both claiming jurisdiction and the right to amend
whatever the banking committees do, as are the appropriations and
budget committees on both sides of Capitol Hill.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., a member of the Senate Banking
Committee, said Thursday that a bill ready for final action by
Congress will not be ready until June at the earliest.
   Asked if August might be a more reachable target, Cranston said,
``My hope is that it will be before then but you never know.''
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Don Riegle, D-Mich., wants to have
a draft bill ready by March 23 when Congress recesses for Easter so
that members can review it over the holiday.
   He recalled that it took Congress a full year to write
legislation for the $1.5 billion in federal loan guarantees to bail
out the Chrysler Corp. in 1980. He added that the financial
complexities of the Chrysler package were far fewer than those in
Bush's far bigger S&amp;L plan.
   Unlike Chrysler, which repaid all the money once it became
profitable again, no one expects the government to ever regain the
billions of dollars Bush is asking taxpayers to shell out for
depositors who sought federally guaranteed high interest rates at
deregulated and now insolvent S&amp;Ls.
   Riegle and other Democrats have criticized Bush's proposed
creation of a new government corporation to issue 30-year bonds for
financing the taxpayer portion of the bailout as a way of preventing
the costs from showing up in the federal deficit.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated Thursday that the
fiscal 1990 budget deficit will be $40 billion higher than the $91.1
billion predicted by the administration, attributing $22 billion of
the difference to the cost of the S&amp;L rescues.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the tax-writing Ways
and Means Committee, said Thursday he expects whatever legislation
is written by the House Banking Committee to be referred to his
panel for amendment.
   ``I do not intend to delay or otherwise hamper the passage of
this important legislation,'' he said, adding that his committee
will only delve into the revenue and federal debt aspects of the
package.
   ``Only in this way can the Congress be assured that the American
taxpayer will have a full understanding of the total costs of the
savings and loan assistance program,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. took control of
another 45 failed savings and loans with $13.6 billion in assets in
eight states Thursday.
   That brings to 118 in 24 states the total number of institutions
that the agency has taken control of since Bush announced his S&amp;L
rescue package in early February.
   Bush instructed the FDIC, which regulates commercial banks, to
take over the sickest S&amp;Ls with the idea of minimizing their losses
while the institutions await rescue or closure. The agency plans to
take control of about another 100 institutions within the next month.
</TEXT>
