<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Fashion     03-10 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Fashion,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armani Shows Stole, Steals Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sunny, mild winter with no rain has
inspired Italian designers to rethink their cold-weather wardrobes.
   For the fall-winter ready to wear collections, which ended here
Thursday, there are practically none of the usual rainccats, heavy
shearlings and sumptuous furs that usually mark the coming of winter
Italian style.
   Instead, designers played heavily on lighter wool coats, capes,
shawls and every possible shape of jacket from the blazer to the
blouson.
   Fake furs, and fur look-a-like fabrics served the double purpose
of placating conservationists, and offering cheaper, cooler
alternatives to the traditional wraps.
   The biggest champion for the ecological cause was Milan's
``numero uno'' Giorgio Armani, who showed stoles, jackets and even
floor length coats in synthetic substitutes of leopard, tiger,
panther among others. As the fake furs were paraded down the runway
a voice speaking for the animal world announced, ``thank you Armani
for saving our skins.''
   Fendi, famous for their extravagant furs also nodded in the
direction of the conservationists with a collection of inside out
furs. The leather side of pelts from sable to skunk is in fact
treated to look like polished cotton, so that the coat stripped of
its lining is reversible.
   The new Milanese coat is very big, soft and cozy with ample
dropped sleeve, and wide shawl collar. Sometimes it is belted at the
waist, at others it flows freely to the ankle.
   After several seasons where the skirt dominated the fashion scene
from the daring 1980's minis skirt, to the feminine mid calf-length
alternative, pants are firmly back on the Milan runway. Often
man-tailored and cuffed, they also come super-wide especially for
evening, or as skin-fitting as tights.
   At the beginning of a new decade the Milanese designers have
opted to to let women make their own fashion decisions in color and
style. Thus there is not one strong message for next season but a
lot of fashionable suggestions, from Gianfranco Ferre's dramatic
silhouette, of stiff-collared, gold cuff-linked white silk blouse
draped with a lavish fox scarf, and worn over simple gray flannel
pants, to Giorgio Armani's tailored art student look, to Byblos'
leisurely weekend collection.
   As to the color scheme there were the usual staple black and
white, and Milan smog shades. Fall shades were also popular, with
aubergine or eggplant and mustard the newest hues. For those who
want a more cheerful winter the designers also offered lots of
bright blue, yellow and tangerine, along with festive red.
   Hairstyles for next winter are generally longer than in recent
seasons, with some designers calling for a return to the wild and
wooly looks of the 1960's.
   There is, however, one point on which all the Milanese designers
insist. High heels even for evening are no longer chic. Instead
fashionable women will warm their winter feet in elf-like suede
booties.
</TEXT>
