<FIRST>r w PM-Kassebaum     03-10 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kassebaum,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kassebaum Only GOP Senator to Break Ranks on Tower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the moment came, Nancy Landon Kassebaum
sat alone at her desk on the crowded, silent floor of the United
States Senate.
   When her name was called, she rose, alone among her Republican
colleagues, and said what none of them had said or would say about
the nomination of John Tower to be secretary of defense.
   ``No,'' said Kassebaum, with nearly all of the 100 senators
sitting quietly in their armchairs, listening as she became the only
Republican senator to join Democrats in defeating Tower's nomination.
   It was the latest display of independence by the junior senator
from Kansas, who serves her state with Bob Dole, the senior senator,
Republican leader and prime fighter on behalf of Tower.
   Kassebaum is independent, yet loyal.
   Had her vote been needed, she said, she would have swallowed her
objections to Tower and voted for his confirmation. As she later
explained to reporters: ``I would not have wanted to be the
defeating vote ... if it was that important to the president.''
   Twice before in recent years the 56-year-old Kassebaum has broken
ranks with her party on hot, highly-partisan issues.
   ``It's very tough when you go against the president of your own
party and against my senior senator, who is the Republican leader.
But I really didn't have a lot of arm-twisting,'' she said.
   ``I think people, whether they were disappointed or not, and I'm
sure some were, respected the independent judgment that you bring to
bear on these issues,'' Kassebaum added.
   Such was the case twice in 1986 _ in the summer when she voted
against the nomination of Dan Manion to be a federal judge, and in
the fall when she voted with Democrats to override President
Reagan's veto of limited economic sanctions against South Africa.
   In the Manion case, she also showed party loyalty while
dissenting. Told during the roll call that a fellow Republican who
wanted to vote in favor of Manion couldn't be located, she agreed to
``pair'' her vote with the missing senator, in effect canceling out
each other's vote.
   Kassebaum, who served as head of a congressional Military Reform
Caucus, said her chief concerns about Tower involved his work for
defense contractors.
   ``The next secretary of defense is going to have to counter the
debilitating impact that the defense procurement scandal has had on
public confidence in our defense establishment,'' she said.
   She said did not believe that Tower could ``provide the
leadership that is necessary to forge a consensus on the critical
national security issues confronting us today.''
   One of only two women serving in the Senate _ Democrat Barbara
Mikulski of Maryland is the other _ Kassebaum also took note of
Tower's alleged attitudes about and treatment of women.
   She noted a Pentagon study that found harassment and promotion
problems facing women in the military and said ``I am not confident
that Senator Tower would give these issues the priority they demand
or would demonstrate the necessary sensitivity to their
seriousness.''
   But Kassebaum made no mention of Tower's drinking habits, subject
of much of the week's debate.
   ``It was not immaterial,'' she said. But ``it's hard to judge
someone on moral standards.''
   Kassebaum, daughter of Alf Landon, the 1936 GOP presidential
nominee who was buried by a Roosevelt election landslide, said she
thought of her late father during the Tower debate.
   ``I couldn't help but think of my dad, who I'm sure would have
said, `Nancy, you should vote with the president.' He would have
felt strongly that way. But as with most who have an appreciation of
government, he would have respected the judgment I brought to bear.''
   The senator faces another judgment call in the not-too-distant
future.
   She came to the Senate in 1978, promising if elected to serve no
more than two terms. Her current one expires in 1990, and she is
under GOP pressure to run for another six-year term.
   At a meeting in Dole's office recently, President Bush posed for
pictures with Kassebaum. The president wore a campaign button
saying, ``Run, Nancy, Run!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
