<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis says she would have preferred to keep
her personal crisis and drinking problem private, but she now wants
to help others.
   ``My hope is that by being public, I might encourage others to
seek help through programs like the one I entered at Edgehill
Newport and the extraordinary fellowship of AA,'' she said Thursday,
adding that she is eager to go through the Alcoholics Anonymous
program.
   The wife of Gov. Michael Dukakis also said she had a drinking
problem long before encountering the stresses of her husband's
public life. ``I don't blame the (presidential) campaign for my
being an alcoholic,'' she said.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, spoke at a news conference two days after
completing a monthlong rehabilitation program in Rhode Island.
   She said her drinking became a serious problem in the three
``terribly painful and lonely'' months after her husband's defeat.
   ``Any crisis could have led to the drinking,'' she said. ``The
campaign was a very positive experience. The only problem is that we
lost.''
   Accompanying Mrs. Dukakis were her husband and her father, Harry
Ellis Dickson, retired associate conductor of the Boston Pops.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jake Garn, who flew aboard the space
shuttle in 1985, has used the spacecraft as grist for his first
novel, ``Night Launch.''
   The plot involves a terrorist hijacking of a space shuttle
flight. The book, co-written with Stephen Paul Cohen and published
by William Morrow in New York City, is set for release April 24.
   Garn, a Utah Republican, declined to be interviewed about the
novel until his publisher begins a publicity drive.
   He flew as a congressional observer on the Discovery in April
1985. At the time, he was chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee overseeing NASA's budget.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Barbadians cheered
Britain's Queen Elizabeth II, who addressed the Senate in a ceremony
marking the 350th anniversary of this eastern Caribbean island's
parliament.
   ``Any nation which can boast of the continuous existence of their
parliament for 350 years has sure grounds for pride,'' she said
Thursday at a joint session of the House of Assembly and Senate.
   Crowds gathered in Bridgetown's Trafalgar Square, adjacent to the
parliament buildings, and applauded Elizabeth and her husband,
Prince Philip, as they stepped out of their limousine and entered
the Senate.
   She said that the ``small band of expatriate Englishmen'' who
established Barbados' House of Assembly in 1639 ``believed that a a
self-governing system formed according to the principles of
individual liberty would bring more order and comfort to their lives
in an unfamiliar environment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columnist and TV commentator George F. Will
has resigned as a University of Maryland regent under pressure, but
Gov. William Donald Schaefer said he isn't ready to accept Will's
departure.
   Schaefer said he will decide whether to ask Will to remain on the
Board of Regents after he talks to board Chairman Peter O'Malley.
   The Evening Sun of Baltimore has reported that Will attended none
of the seven regents' meetings since he was appointed last July and
has not attended subcommittee meetings.
   ``I think he thought he was under pressure from the press and
others as to why he didn't attend,'' the governor said.
   But he said Will made it clear when he agreed to accept the
appointment last summer that he would miss many meetings because of
his busy schedule. Will writes a syndicated newspaper column and is
a comentator for ABC-TV.
   Will resigned March 2, saying the demands of his profession were
``incompatible'' with service on the board. But Schaefer said he is
nonetheless a valuable addition to the Board of Regents because of
his prestige.
   ``He knows everybody,'' the governor said. ``He interviews with
the greatest. To me he was just a good person to have as a member of
the Board of Regents even though he couldn't come to all the
meetings. I put him on with that understanding.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu is
running for the Harvard Board of Overseers to push for the
university's total divestment from companies doing business in his
homeland.
   ``Harvard is a great leader in world education. The time has come
for Harvard to become a moral leader as well in the worldwide
struggle against apartheid,'' Tutu said Thursday in a prepared
statement.
   ``With her help, and the help of men and women of good will
throughout the world, we shall one day soon transform my beautiful
and troubled land into a genuinely democratic, non-racial society,''
Tutu said.
   The archbishop's candidacy was announced at the University of the
Western Cape in Cape Town, South Africa, said his spokesman John
Allen. News conferences also were held in Harvard and in Bogota.
   The Harvard Alumni Association has announced 10 candidates for
the five positions open, making a total of 15 candidates. Results of
the election, voted on by the 160,000 alumni worldwide, will be
announced June 8.
