<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     03-10 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Expected to Cause Boost in Worldwide Oilseed Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New estimates by the Agriculture Department
suggest that American soybean farmers will continue to hear the
approaching samba sound of Brazilian footsteps in the world oilseed
market.
   Not that South American production is taking over the soybean
lead enjoyed by the United States for many years, but world trade _
and domestic prices _ are sensitive to the slightest movement in
production and demand.
   The USDA said Thursday that improved prospects for soybeans in
Brazil have helped boost the forecast slightly for 1988-89 global
oilseed production to 198.6 million metric tons.
   Officials said the total increased less than 1 percent from
indications last month and still was 4 percent below last year's
record.
   Soybeans, forecast at 93.4 million tons, accounted for most of
the increase from February. The U.S. share of world output was 41.9
million tons.
   In 1987-88, when world soybean output was 103.2 million tons, the
U.S. harvest was 52.3 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of soybeans or wheat, or 39.7 bushels of corn.
   ``Brazil's crop estimate was raised by 1 million tons to 21
million tons, reflecting larger area indications and highly
favorable growing conditions over the past month,'' the report said.
   At 21 million tons, the crop would be a record for Brazil and
about 11 percent more than the harvest of 18 million tons in 1987-88.
   Brazil and Argentina are the leading foreign competitors of U.S.
farmers in the world soybean market. Along with other Southern
Hemisphere countries, they are watched closely for signs of changes
in soybean and grain production patterns.
   For example, the improved outlook for Brazil's soybeans has been
an important factor this week in commodity futures trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade, along with weather conditions that could
affect spring planting kin the United States.
   ``Argentina's soybean prospects deteriorated further in February,
although the improvement in moisture and temperature trends late in
the month probably aided soybeans,'' the report said.
   The forecast for Argentina soybeans was reduced by 500,000 tons
to 8.5 million tons in 1988-89, compared with 9.9 million tons last
season.
   Looking at grain, the report said global prospects for 1988-89
``are little changed from last month. Argentina's new corn crop
continued to deteriorate, but South Africa's crop showed further
improvement.''
   World grain trade for 1988-89 was forecast to be up slightly from
February indications, with larger imports expected for China and the
Soviet Union. The U.S. grain supply and use estimates were largely
unchanged.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has scrapped a plan
which would have held farmers and others in the marketing chain
financially accountable for selling livestock found to contain
illegally high traces of drugs at time of slaughter.
   The ``bill-back'' proposal was announced May 24, 1988, and was
subjected to public review during formal rulemaking procedure.
Nearly 300 comments were received.
   B.H. ``Bill'' Jones, administrator of the department's Packers
and Stockyards Administration, said Thursday the bill-back plan was
designed to shift economic responsibility for violative drug
residues from the meat packer to the person causing the violation.
   The proposal involved illegally high residues of sulfa and
antibiotic drugs found in carcasses of young calves, culled dairy
cows and swine.
   Jones said 87 percent of the comments opposed the concept of
bill-back, with most questioning the ability to trace and accurately
identify the source of the illegal drug residues.
   Although the proposal has been withdrawn, Jones said that would
not preclude anyone suffering financial hardship because of an
illegal drug residue from seeking restitution.
   Buyers are entitled to know the identity of the seller, including
a consignor, when an animal carcass is condemned as a result of a
drug violation, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's orange harvest for the 1988-89
crop season is estimated by the Agriculture Department at 210.9
million boxes, down 2 percent from last month's forecast but 5
percent more than produced last season.
   Florida production, based on March 1 indications, was estimated
Thursday at 146 million boxes, down 3 percent from the February
forecast but 6 percent more than in 1987-88.
   The California harvest was estimated at 61 million boxes,
unchanged from last month and 4 percent more than last season. The
Arizona estimate, which was carried forward from earlier, was put at
2 million boxes, up 10 percent from last season.
   Texas orange production was forecast at 1.9 million boxes, up 3
percent from February indications and up 33 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
