<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     03-10 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Darman's Private Stance on Taxes Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget talks between the White House and
Congress are off to a less-than-smooth start, as early political
squabbling dampened otherwise optimistic talk.
   President Bush's budget director, Richard Darman, and Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady met with the Democratic chairmen and senior
Republicans from the House and Senate budget committees Thursday
afternoon to launch an initial two-week search for agreement.
   The participants said they hoped to draw a map on how to reach
compromise on a fiscal 1990 budget, although they might not reach
that destination themselves.
   Their goal, they said, is a general plan to balance competing
interests of defense and domestic programs, taxes, and reducing the
deficit, but without the detail of a congressional budget resolution.
   Darman characterized the first meeting as deciding on a
``framework for analysis,'' and the talks broke off until next
Tuesday so that budget technicians could put things in order for
``getting down to the hard part.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said the discussions would not necessarily be limited to
fiscal 1990. Bush has proposed a $1.16 trillion spending plan for
the year beginning Oct. 1.
   The chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, Jim Sasser, D-Tenn.,
told reporters before Thursday's meeting that he saw the White House
agenda as adopting ``a minimalist approach'' this year and then
opening the door to tax increases later.
   Sasser, who repeatedly has said that a tax boost was needed to
reduce the deficit, told reporters that Darman was privately
agreeing with him.
   Darman, however, denied he had strayed even privately from
President Bush's promise of no new taxes, and said he hoped the
talks would produce a strong deficit-reduction plan.
   ``I can't imagine he would have said that,'' Darman said. Asked
whether he was more favorable to a tax increase than his public
statements have indicated, Darman said, ``Maybe that's what he would
like to believe.''
   The White House contends enacting its budget would reduce the
deficit below the $100 billion target of the Gramm-Rudman law.
   A report by the Congressional Budget Office, released Thursday,
estimated the deficit at $131 billion, $40 billion higher than the
administration projection. Most of the difference was due to an
accounting difference over Bush's plan to bail out the savings and
loan industry.
</TEXT>
