<FIRST>r i PM-People-VanAllen     03-10 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Van Allen,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discoverer of Van Allen Belts Wins Swedish Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore cycle designator, fix category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Van Allen, the U.S. space
researcher who discovered the Earth's high-energy radiation belts
named for him, has won the $252,000 Crafoord prize of Sweden's Royal
Academy of Sciences.
   The academy, which also awards the Nobel prizes, cited work by
Van Allen which gave the United States the edge at the start of the
space race with the Soviet Union.
   Van Allen, 74, developed new rockets and space instruments used
in launching the first U.S. satellites, the academy said Thursday.
   ``He played an important role in the space race,'' said academy
member Rolf Bostrom. ``He has been kind of a father for experimental
physics in space research.''
   Van Allen, however, never advocated sending men into space,
believing instead that greater scientific benefit could be drawn
from unmanned flights through their instruments.
   The prestigious Crafoord prize, worth $252,000, has been awarded
since 1982. It will be given to Van Allen at a ceremony in September
by Sweden's King Carl XVI Gustaf.
</TEXT>
