<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett     03-10 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Urge Drug Czar to Resist Congressional Hearings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug policy director William J. Bennett needs
to ``just say no'' to overeager lawmakers who might make him
squander time in endless hearings, senators said after confirming
the former education secretary in his new post.
   ``I have pledged to Dr. Bennett that the Judiciary Committee will
not call him up to testify in the next six months, as long as he
follows the statute's requirement,'' Judiciary Chairman Joseph
Biden, D-Del., said Thursday as the Senate voted 97-2 for
confirmation.
   Biden urged other lawmakers to do the same, saying the last thing
Bennett needs as the nation's new ``drug czar'' is to shuttle back
and forth to Capitol Hill to field questions.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said congressional procedures must be
streamlined to remove the temptation to summon Bennett for
``seven-camera hearings'' on the drug issue, always a convenient way
to seize the limelight.
   Bennett's confirmation was smooth, even though sparks at times
flew over his strongly worded views as President Reagan's secretary
of education.
   Only Sens. Paul Simon, D-Ill., and Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., voted
against the nominee while Sen. John Warner, R-Va., did not vote.
   Simon, a longtime ally of teacher groups, said he feared that
Bennett would produce ``a blizzard of press releases but not much
action.''
   He was the lone dissenter hours earlier when the Judiciary
Committee voted 13-1 to send the nomination to the floor. He said
Bennett had sought a cut in the Education Department's drug
education budget and ``was not strong'' as an administrator.
   Bennett's new post gives him 180 days to draft a strategy for
fighting the drug war and requires him to study the spending plans
of Cabinet officers and prod them to increase outlays for narcotics
control if he deems it necessary. The president becomes the referee
if the two officials cannot agree.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said Thursday that Bennett ``has a
difficult job (but) it shouldn't be considered mission impossible.''
   Biden told lawmakers the real issue was ``whether President Bush
has a strategy, whether he is going to enunciate that strategy and
whether he is going to put that strategy into effect.''
   Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, the top Republican on the
committee, replied there was no question that Bush was focusing hard
on the drug problem.
   ``I have been in the White House several times recently and I
assure you that he is vitally interested,'' Thurmond said.
   Biden said he believed Bush was interested but it remained to be
seen if that would be ``matched by overwhelming commitment of
resources and action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
