<DOCNO> AP890310-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GrainTrade     03-10 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grain Trade,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quality Control Lacking in US Grain Exports, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American system of handling grain exports
has so many problems with quality control that the United States
could lose its leading role in the world market, says a report
requested by Congress.
   The report, released Thursday by the Office of Technology
Assessment, said U.S. policy on grain lacks even have one definition
of quality.
   ``In grain, the word quality has a variety of meanings _ being
free of foreign material, not cracked or spoiled or having the
proper characteristic for a particular use,'' the report said.
   The problems with American grain have led to an increase in
foreign complaints, the report said.
   ``In the 1970s, one-third of the world's countries supplied grain
to two-thirds of the world; today the reverse is true,'' the report
said. ``This highly competitive environment has made foreign buyers
increasingly sensitive about the quality of grain they import.''
   The report was prepared at the request of the House Committee on
Agriculture and the Joint Economic Committee.
   At a news conference on the report, Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D.,
said he did not agree with everything it in, but that it was
important in determining how the United States can improve its
competitive edge.
   ``It's a starting point for further debate,'' he said.
   Both he, and Sens. Thomas Daschle, D-N.D., and Charles Grassley,
R-Iowa, mentioned that they were troubled by reports of cement chips
in U.S. grain that had been shipped to foreign ports.
   ``My farmers tell me their grain is clean when it is brought to
the elevator,'' said Daschle.
   Conrad said the Secretary of Agriculture has been asked to
investigate further.
   Michael Phillips, who headed the OTA study, said the problem is
with the whole system of marketing grain to foreign countries.
   Compared with other grain-exporting countries, the U.S. system is
more complex, Phillips said.
   He said other countries address the quality problems as part of
an integrated agricultural policy, with more controls at the first
point of sale.
   Most other exporters clean grain at the first point of receipt,
while no economic incentive to do so exists in the United States, he
said.
   He also said foreign buyers complain about the way the United
States blends a wide range of different quality grains in an attempt
to create a uniform product, but this causes differences in
shipments.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., said enhancing grain quality must
begin with the design of commodity programs, research at
universities and seed breeders on new grain varieties, and the
standardization of testing procedures.
   Phillips said, however, the United States still has many
advantages over its biggest competitors: Argentina, Brazil, Canada
and Australia.
   ``We can meet almost any demand,'' he said. ``We can produce any
type of grain a buyer wants. We can supply it at any time of the
year and we can move it from terminal to overseas buyer faster thany
anyone else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ArmySpy     03-10 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Army Spy,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Warrant Officer Given 40 Years for Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army officer who made up to $200,000 spying
for East Germany and the Soviet Union did it mainly for the money, a
psychiatrist testified before the officer was sentenced to 40 years
in prison and fined $50,000.
   Warrant Officer James W. Hall III, 30, of Sharon Springs, N.Y.,
was sentenced Thursday night in a military courtroom at Fort McNair
in southwest Washington. Three days earlier he had pleaded guilty to
10 counts of espionage, attempted espionage and violating Army
regulations.
   Col. Howard C. Eggers, the military judge who presided at the
court-martial, also gave Hall a dishonorable discharge and ordered
him to forfeit all future pay and allowances.
   Hall, who will be eligible for parole after serving a minimum of
10 years, was facing the prospect of a death sentence before he
entered into a pre-trial agreement with the government that set his
maximum punishment at 45 years confinment.
   Eggers was not allowed to see the punishment agreement before
passing sentence.
   Army prosecutors and defense lawyers agreed during the
court-martial that Hall had received payments totaling $100,000 to
$200,000 between 1983 and 1988, when he admitted passing classified
information to representatives of East Germany and the Soviet Union.
The annual $30,000 retainer from East Germany was in effect part of
that five-year period.
   Col. David Armitage, chief of the Army's forensic psychiatry
division at Walter Reed Army Hospital, testified Thursday that his
examinations of Hall suggested that Hall was motivated primarily by
money.
   Most of the government's case against Hall, including the details
of his espionage activities, was outlined for Eggers during closed
sessions of the court-martial that were conducted in a secured
courtroom.
   Hall, an intelligence analyst with a top-secret security
clearance, was arrested Dec. 21 near Savannah, Ga., and accused of
delivering film and documents dealing with communications
intelligence and war plans to Warsaw Pact nations.
   At the time of his arrest, Hall was assigned to the 24th Infantry
Division and worked as an intelligence analyst at the Army's G-2
intelligence section. He joined the Army in 1976 and spent most of
his career in Europe working as an analyst of intercepted radio and
telephone traffic and coded messages.
   Before leaving Europe to return to the United States in 1987,
according to testimony, Hall received a medal and a $5,000 bonus
from the East German government.
   After his arrest, Hall began cooperating with military
authorities. The pre-trial agreement required that he submit to
``unlimited debriefings'' and polygraph examinations about his spy
activities.
   He also agreed to testify, if called, against Huseyin Yildirim, a
Turkish-born naturalized citizen to whom Hall allegedly passed the
intelligence information.
   Yildirim, 60, was arrested at his home is Belleair Beach, Fla.,
last December and charged with conspiracy to commit espionage. If
convicted, he could be sentenced to life in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
