<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-10 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Loses Ground, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo on Friday, while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange after losing ground earlier in the day.
   The dollar closed at 128.88 yen, down 0.35 yen from Thursday's
129.23-yen finish. The currency opened at 128.85 yen and was traded
in a range between 128.82 yen and 129.08 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
181.21 points the previous day, recouped 45.33 points, or 0.14
percent, to finish trading at 31,701.78.
   The market's main index recovered from its 116.33 point-decline
in the morning session and gained ground in the afternoon.
   Exchange dealers said the market has been bearish since the end
of February because of unwillingness by fund managers to risk their
portfolios as the end of the accounting period for their mutual and
trust funds approaches. Japan's fiscal year ends March 31.
   ``Most fund managers appear to have won reasonable profits,
thanks to the bullish market throughout the year,'' said Keiichi
Nishida, a dealer at Kidder Peabody Securities in Tokyo. ``But most
of them have already cashed in and the market doesn't seem to have
much incentive for buying at this point.''
   He said the trend is likely to continue until the end of the
month.
   ``But market environment is not so bad, either,'' Nishida added.
``So, if share prices go down even further, investors may turn to
buying again.''
   The Nikkei, Tokyo's main economic barometer, has plunged more
than 700 points since Monday.
   In currency dealings, dealers said the dollar's weakness was
prompted by comments from U.S. Budget Director Richard Darman on
Thursday in which he discounted a tax increase. His statement
contradicted that of Michael Boskin, chairman of the Council of
Economic Advisers, who said Wednesday that taxes may rise.
   Market anxiety over the U.S. unemployment figure for February, to
be released Friday in Washington, sidelined many players, added a
dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The report will provide one of the first indications of how the
American economy has responded to rising interest rates. The U.S.
Federal Reserve Board has been pursuing a restrictive monetary
policy to help slow growth and relieve inflationary pressures on the
economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
