<FIRST>u a PM-Eastern-Unions Bjt   03-10 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Unions, Bjt,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Unions Vow To Fight On, But Some Workers Set To Look For
Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern's union leaders vow to keep battling Texas
Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo through bankruptcy reorganization,
but some rank-and-file workers say they can't wait that long.
   ``Starting tomorrow, I'll be looking for another job after 12
years here,'' said Cynthia Carrasco, an office service worker and
single mother of two daughters. ``But I'll still be right out here
picketing and protesting. I want my paycheck. I've got rent, food,
clothing to buy.''
   Betsie Romano, a 20-year flight attendant, was on the picket line
Thursday pushing her 2-year-old daughter Beige in a stroller as news
of the Chapter 11 reorganization circulated. ``I was mentally
prepared, but financially, no,'' Ms. Romano said. ``My husband is
unemployed. My family's busted.''
   Yurbano Mayorquin, a 21-year electronics technician, said he'll
be looking for a new job at age 55. ``I'm going to try to start over
again,'' Mayorquin said.
   The Machinists union urged all workers to file for unemployment
compensation, though it was doubtful strikers would qualify.
Striking members also were urged to seek financial counseling and
loans from the Eastern employees credit union.
   The company indicated that this week's paychecks were frozen like
other Eastern liabilities because of the Chapter 11 filing. Union
attorneys are likely to ask the bankruptcy court to order the checks
released.
   Wally Haber, a Machinists district general chairman, said $100
weekly strike-fund payments won't begin for two more weeks under
union rules.
   The pilots' national union will make emergency payments to
Eastern pilots if no resolution occurs by March 15, when the pilots'
next check is due, union leaders said. Flight attendants were
uncertain whether they could obtain any such special benefits.
   Earlier Thursday, workers jammed around television sets in the
Machinists union hall, shouting at Lorenzo and Eastern President
Phil Bakes as they announced the bankruptcy filing in New York. They
cheered for the live telecast that followed of Machinists District
100 President Charles Bryan's news conference in Miami.
   ``It certainly is a sad day for Eastern,'' said Bryan, the
combative union leader who heads 8,500 mechanics, baggage handlers
and other ground workers who struck the airline Saturday after talks
broke down in their 17-month contract dispute.
   The strike virtually shut down Eastern when pilots and flight
attendants refused to cross Machinists' picket lines.
   Bryan said his union will fight Lorenzo in bankruptcy court and
in Washington and will picket everything touched by Texas Air,
including a fuel tanker in Corpus Christi, Texas, and Eastern'
sister airline, Continental, where Lorenzo got labor contracts
abrogated in 1983 bankruptcy reorganization.
   The pilots, whose action was blamed by Lorenzo for forcing the
bankruptcy reorganization, also pledged to continue fighting any
sales of assets and to do battle in bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``Chapter 11 means there's still a patient and it's undergoing
surgery and it's coming back,'' said John Bavis, head of the Eastern
pilots. ``That's better than the continued slow dismantling of
Eastern under Texas Air.''
   Bavis said Lorenzo's statement blaming the pilots was
``amazing,'' and that the chairman had sought the strike so ``he can
break the unions and get rid of us once and for all.''
   Bryan said poor management, not Eastern's unions, was to blame
for the strike, and he repeated charges he's made for three years
that Lorenzo intended from the start to try to break the unions and
carve up Eastern.
   The union is urging a nationwide boycott of Continental, which
Bryan says is Lorenzo's ``war machine'' to take advantage of
Eastern's shutdown by expanding its low-cost services on Eastern
routes.
</TEXT>
