<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Glasnost     03-10 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Glasnost,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glasnost Takes On Anti-American Tilt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relations between the superpowers may seem as warm
as a McDonald's hamburger in Moscow, but a new flood of
anti-American attacks is showing the flip side of glasnost.
   While Soviets themselves are reading more good things about the
United States, their government is providing foreigners with
anti-U.S. material that harkens back to the Cold War.
   Many of the assertions have been heard before from the Soviets:
the FBI murdered the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., the CIA massacred
Jim Jones and 900 of his People's Temple followers in Guyana.
   But now, they are part of ``glasnost,'' President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of greater openness, according to an editor at
the Soviet press agency Novosti.
   Hundreds of such anti-American charges are contained in booklets
published recently by Novosti, whose motto is ``Information for
Peace and International Friendship.''
   The deputy editor-in-chief of Novosti's North American
department, Yevgeny A. Posdnyakov, says the slick publications are
not just recycled Cold War propaganda but part of the campaign for
greater frankness.
   ``There is a need to write about everything so people will make
up their own mind and understand things,'' Posdnyakov said. ``The
demand that some zones be free from inquiry by journalists would be
an attack on glasnost.''
   The view from Washington is far different: at least one of the
Novosti books, ``Once Again About the CIA,'' is full of falsehoods
and innuendo designed to smear the reputation of the United States,
U.S. officials charge.
   ``We have discussed this book with the Soviets as a particularly
egregious example of what we call `disinformation,''' said U.S.
Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert.
   Nevertheless, ``Once Again About the CIA,'' whose cover shows
bloody corpses imposed on the Central Intelligence Agency's seal, is
being distributed in special waiting rooms of Moscow airports
reserved for foreigners. According to Posdnyakov, 10,000 copies were
printed in English.
   Novosti publications also are available in Intourist hotels,
whose clientele is largely foreign; from Aeroflot, the Soviet
airline; and from Soviet embassies and other institutions abroad.
   Paradoxically, the publication of the books, largely intended for
foreign markets, comes as official media whose audience is mostly
Soviet are finding much about the United States to praise.
   Ogonyok magazine recently asked whether a U.S.-style jury system
could be instituted, and on Thursday the Communist Party daily
Pravda lauded the taste of hamburgers from McDonald's, which has a
franchise in Moscow.
   The Novosti books strike a far different note. Among recent
releases:
   _ ``Silent Terror,'' billed as ``the book U.S. censors don't want
Americans to read.'' Written by former U.S. cancer researcher Arnold
Lockshin and his wife, Lauren, who obtained political asylum in the
Soviet Union in 1986, the book recounts ``the silent campaign of
harassment and terror which the FBI (the U.S. political police)
organized to force them to conform politically _ or be sorry.''
   The former Houston couple _ members of the Communist Party U.S.A.
who came to Moscow with their three children _ accuse the FBI of
waging an intimidation campaign that included the bugging of their
home.
   The Lockshins also say it was an ``inescapable conclusion ...
that the FBI murdered King,'' the late civil rights leader.
   Their book was printed in 10,000 copies in English, Posdnyakov
said.
   _ ``Once Again About the CIA,'' in 117 pages, accuses the U.S.
intelligence service of committing the ``monstrous crime'' of
killing the Rev. Jim Jones and more than 900 of his followers at
Jonestown, Guyana, in 1978 and of assassinating foreign leaders like
Panama's Omar Torrijos and the Congo's Patrice Lumumba.
   The booklet suggests that CIA made an unsuccessful attempt on the
pope's life in 1981, which an Italian state prosecutor linked
instead to the secret service of Bulgaria, a Soviet ally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
