<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     03-10 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Boycott Deepens Rifts in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A growing political feud between two
of Yugoslavia's republics has prompted many Serbians to mount an
unprecedented boycott of Slovenian goods, according to news reports.
   Belgrade newspapers said Thursday that many businesses and
shoppers in Serbia, the largest of six republics, are shunning
products from Slovenia to protest support there for ethnic Albanians
who went on strike last month in the southern Serbian province of
Kosovo.
   On Feb. 27, prominent Slovenian intellectuals and politicians
came together in the republic's capital of Ljubljana to express
support for about 1,300 striking miners at the Trepca lead-zinc mine
in Kosovo.
   The federal government sent troop and tank reinforcements into
the province, but three provincial leaders viewed as pro-Serbian
resigned and the striking Kosovo miners ended their eight-day sit-in.
   Tensions between Serbs and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have led to
mass protests through much of the past year.
   New reports of labor unrest in the province were still emerging.
The official Tanjug news agency said about 400 ethnic Albanian
miners at a nearby mine went on strike Thursday.
   Tanjug said the miners at the Goles magnesite mine, about 140
miles south of Belgrade, rallied at the company's head office and
demanded to talk to Kosovo officials.
   The reasons for strike were not immediately clear. But it
appeared to be ``politically motivated,'' said a journalist in the
provincial capital of Pristina.
   A day after the earlier strike ended, more than 500,000 angry
Serbs, claiming insult to their national pride, protested in
Belgrade against Slovenia.
   They also called for ending political pluralism in Slovenia, the
country's most liberal and industrial republic. Several independent
political groups have been established there in recent months.
   After the rally, hundreds of Serbians ran on the Belgrade branch
of the Slovenian Bank of Ljubljana, closing their accounts and
transferring the equivalent of at least $1.5 million to Serbian
banks, the Belgrade daily newspaper Borba said Thursday.
   Several Serbian businesses have threatened to break off business
with Slovenian firms if the companies refuse to condemn Slovenian
leadership for ``its support for Albanian separatists in Kosovo,''
the newspaper said.
   The Vulkan rubber plant in southern Serbia, a subsidiary of a
Slovenian tire manufacturer, served notice that it was severing its
ties with its mother company, the report said.
   It also said workers at a pig farm near Belgrade refused to allow
hogs that had already been paid for to be loaded on trucks for
transport to Slovenia.
   Shoppers throughout Serbia, meanwhile, have been boycotting
Slovenian goods, which are generally considered superior to local
products, the Vecernje Novosti newspaper reported Thursday.
   ``It is true that our customers are choosing Slovenian goods less
and less frequently,'' Milos Slijepcevic, chairman of Yugoslavia's
largest department store chain, Beograd, was quoted as saying.
   ``Shoppers are now disgusted ... and often loudly complain when
they see such goods on display,'' Slijepcevic was quoted as saying.
   Serbia has been trying to impose more central control on Kosovo,
which is administratively part of the republic but enjoys wide
autonomy under the present Yugoslav constitution.
   Serbian leaders claim that the minority Slav population is being
harassed by the Albanian majority there.
</TEXT>
