<FIRST>u i PM-IslamicIsrael     03-10 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Islamic Israel,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Run Israeli City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UMM EL-FAHM, Israel (AP) _ Moslem fundamentalists who won control
of this city say bad roads and big debts, not an Islamic revolution,
helped propel them to power.
   Nevertheless, some Israeli Jews say they are worried by the
outcome of the election in this northern town of 27,000 people.
   Government officials, scholars and editorial writers have warned
of a fundamentalist trend and some even suggest Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, the Iranian patriarch, has become a revolutionary model
for Israeli Moslems.
   Israel has 810,000 Arab citizens, 18 percent of the population,
and 80 percent of them are Moslems.
   Sheik Raed Salah Mahajneh, a Moslem preacher and new mayor of Umm
el-Fahm, said his party won because the town is in disrepair and has
a debt of $3.9 million. He blamed that on skimpy government funding
and a poor job by the previous local administration, which the
communists supported.
   ``We are short of drainage, roads and schoolrooms,'' said the
30-year-old mayor, a policeman's son. ``Anywhere you put your
finger, there is something to be done. We are not in Iran, we are
here. We have been here since before the Iranian revolution.''
   Alex Bligh, a government adviser on Arab affairs, said complaints
of discrimination against Israeli Arabs were ``not totally
baseless.'' Despite improvements, he said, the ratio of government
funds devoted to Jewish and Arab towns is 4-1.
   Mahajneh has the full beard of a Moslem fundamentalist but he
greeted reporters this week in a stylish sweater, slacks and loafers.
   The Islamic Movement's use of mosque donations to build roads and
kindergartens in Arab areas is cited by many observers as a major
reason for its election success.
   A combination mosque, clinic and social center now being built in
Umm el-Fahm was financed with local donations and $45,000 from Cat
Stevens _ the American folk singer who changed his name to Yusef
Islam after becoming a Moslem, Mahajneh said.
   The five-story complex sits on a hill overlooking the town 35
miles northeast of Tel Aviv.
   Such efforts by the party have not arrested decades of neglect,
however. Open sewage drains and rutted, dirt roads are common in
Arab towns and villages.
   The Islamic Movement, which is challenging Communist domination
among Israeli Arabs, won leadership in Umm el-Fahm and two large
villages, and could win three more villages in run-off elections.
Six of the 19 council posts in the biblical city of Nazareth went to
Islamic candidates.
   Bligh, who spoke at a government forum on the elections, called
the victories ``a very disturbing development'' that could have
national implications if the Islamic Movement runs for parliament,
where Arabs occupy a half-dozen of the 120 seats.
   Rafi Israel, an expert on Islamic affairs at Hebrew University,
tied growing fundamentalism among Israel's Moslems to the Islamic
fervor of Khomeini and Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi. ``I can see
very alarming signs that things might get out of hand,'' he said.
   He noted that the concept of Islam as a system of government and
society as well as a religion were incompatible with the idea of a
Jewish state, and declared it ``nonsense'' to believe Arabs were
loyal citizens of Israel.
   Leaders of the Islamic Movement and newly elected Moslem
officials insist such fears are unfounded.
   ``We will not do anything outside the law,'' Mahajneh said. ``The
law will be here as it is in Tel Aviv.''
</TEXT>
