<FIRST>u a PM-CommonCold Bjt   03-10 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Common Cold, Bjt,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Best Way To Attack The Common Cold May Be To Fool It, Scientists
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists reported today that the next best thing
to a cure for the common cold _ a way to prevent it _ may have
become possible at last by using a kind of cellular illusion to
trick the relentless virus.
   Two teams, working separately, have deciphered the chemical
hitching post that about half of all cold viruses use when they
latch onto cells in the nose and infect them.
   This seemingly arcane discovery may be an important key to
defeating one of humanity's most universal miseries.
   ``It is clearly feasible to develop a treatment based on what we
have learned,'' said Dr. Timothy A. Springer of the Center for Blood
Research in Boston.
   Their anti-cold strategy is simple: Fool the virus.
   The scientists have developed a detailed picture of the
rhinovirus receptor on the cells that make up the lining of the
nose. A cold occurs when a virus attaches itself to one these
receptors and infiltrates the cell.
   Researchers have isolated the gene responsible for making the
receptor, and as a result, they can produce it in limitless
quantities.
   They believe they can keep people healthy by flooding their noses
with copies of the receptor. If a cold virus wanders by, it will
harmlessly attack a dummy receptor and never find a susceptible nose
cell.
   No one knows for sure whether this ploy will work, although it
looks promising in a test tube. A similar scheme is being tested
against AIDS.
   ``If it works, it would be very exciting,'' commented Dr. Richard
Crowell, a virus researcher at Hahnemann University School of
Medicine in Philadelphia.
   Even if the scientific hunch is right, it will be several years
before such treatment is available. There will also be drawbacks.
The therapy will only work against rhinoviruses, which causes about
half of all colds, but it will be powerless against other cold
germs. And it probably will not stop colds once they start.
   ``This is not a cure. It is a scientific step,'' said Dr. Michael
E. Kamarck of Molecular Therapeutics in West Haven, Conn.
   Reports on the two teams' conclusions were published in the
journal Cell. One study was conducted at the Center for Blood
Research, the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston and Boehringer
Ingelheim Pharmaceuticals in Ridgefield, Conn., and the other at
Molecular Therapeutics, part of Miles Inc., a pharmaceutical firm.
   Springer said his group has already produced a soluble form of
the virus receptor, but they are attempting to develop a version
that will be even more effective as a virus-fooling drug.
   Experts predicted that such a treatment would probably be used as
a nose spray or drops. Since it would be impractical _ and probably
expensive _ to use the drops daily, people might take the medicine
when they are especially worried about getting colds.
   For instance, parents might take the treatment to protect
themselves when their child brings home a cold. Or an athlete might
use it to keep from catching a cold before an important game.
   Scientists said the discovery resulted from combining two lines
of separate research.
   Springer has worked for several years on a structure on the
surface of cells called intercellular adhesion molecule-1, or
ICAM-1. This protein is the receptor that white blood cells use to
hook themselves onto the body's tissues _one step in coordinating
the response to infection and triggering inflammation.
   Meanwhile, Dr. Richard Colonno of the drug firm Merk, Sharp &amp;
Dohme discovered three years ago that 90 percent of all rhinoviruses
attach themselves to just one receptor when they attack the body.
   In the latest work, the scientists found that ICAM-1 is the
portal for both blood cells and cold viruses.
   ``The big thing has been the identification of the two proteins
that we worked on separately being one and the same,'' Colonno said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0618EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Birds&amp;Bees     03-10 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Birds &amp; Bees,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Birds, Tribesmen Whistle While They Work in Search of Honey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wild African bird that leads the way to
hidden beehives cuts by nearly two-thirds the time tribesmen must
spend beating around the bush for honey, according to research
proving a unique form of cooperation between species.
   In a study published today in the journal Science, scientists
from Kenya and West Germany say they repeatedly observed a bird
called the greater honeyguide direct people from the Boran tribe in
Africa to the hidden hives of wild honey bees.
   The cooperation between human and honeyguide is the only known
instance in which non-domesticated animals willfully and freely work
with humans to find food in the wild, said Frank Gill, a bird expert
in Philadelphia who was not part of the research.
   The people gather the honey and the birds feed on larvae and wax
left behind, the report says.
   Such a bird had been the subject of myth, part of which calls for
punishment for honey gatherers who refuse to share with the birds.
When that happens, the bird leads the people to a lion or leopard
the next time.
   H. A. Isack of the National Museum of Kenya and H. U. Reyer of
Max Planck Institute in West Germany reported in the article that
they spent three years watching the bird guide people to 186 honey
bee nests.
   The mutual hunt begins, they report, when members of the Boran
tribe create a whistle by blowing through clasped fists or through
hollow shells or nuts.
   Attracted by the whistle, the bird flies to where the people wait.
   ``The greater honeyguide draws the attention of a human by flying
close to him, moving restlessly between perches around him and
emitting a double-noted, persistent call, which sounds like
`tirr-tirr-tirr-tirr,' '' the study says.
   Moments later, the bird will fly away for a minute or more, an
event called the ``first disappearance.''
   When the bird returns, it perches near the humans and gives a
call. When approached to within 15 feet, the bird flies a short
distance away, displaying white tail feathers, and continues to call
to the people.
   ``As the Borans follow, they whistle, bang on wood, and talk
loudly to the bird to keep it interested in the guiding,'' the
report said. ``This pattern of leading and following is repeated
until the bee colony is reached.''
   Isack and Reyer said they proved that the bird's actions were no
accident by repeatedly allowing birds to lead them back to an
untouched beehive.
   ``From different compass points, the bird led us via different,
but again fairly direct, routes,'' the authors reported.
   The study said Borans claim that the birds' actions are based on
the distance to the hive. Those actions included the length of the
``first disappearance,'' the distance between perches as the bird
guides, and the height of the tree limbs the bird picks as perches
during the guiding.
   ``We found all three Boran statements to be true,'' the authors
said.
   Upon arrival at the bee's hive, Isack and Reyer said the
honeyguide bird perches close to the nest and sings a new song, one
that differs from the guiding call. The bird may also fly around the
hive to indicate its location.
   The authors said they staked out some previously-discovered bee
hives and learned that the honeyguide bird would regularly visit
untouched bee nests, sometimes even flying to the hive's entrance
and peering into it.
   ``The information gathered during such visits enables the bird to
engage in its goal-oriented guiding behavior,'' the authors said.
   Borans, who rely on honey as an important part of their diet,
also hunt for honey when no greater honeyguides are around.
   The authors said that in an unfamiliar area the Borans need about
8.9 hours to find a honey hive, but only 3.2 hours when guided by
the bird.
   Science is the journal of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
