<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Infants Have Less Health Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a third of all poor children have no
health insurance and nearly 30 percent of children in low-income
families are uninsured, according to a Children's Defense Fund
report.
   The report by the private organization said 32.4 percent of all
poor children and 28.7 percent of children in families with incomes
between 100 percent and 200 percent of the poverty line had no
health insurance in 1986.
   The report warned many children not covered by private,
employer-based health insurance programs are also not getting
adequate coverage under the federal-state Medicaid program and other
health assistance programs.
   ``When the savings and loan industry has a crisis, political
leaders find at least $60 billion to bail them out,'' said
Children's Defense Fund President Marian Wright Edelman. ``When our
children are dying and being disabled from preventable causes, our
political leaders offer fiscal Band-Aids and say we cannot afford
the few billion to build a health floor to keep our babies alive and
healthy,'' said Edelman in releasing the report during the group's
three-day annual conference this week.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumer Debt Grows By $4.4 Billion in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revised government figures show Americans
borrowed $4.4 billion more than they repaid in January, edging the
annual rate of consumer debt to 7.9 percent.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Thursday the January increase
followed a revised increase of $4.3 billion in December and a gain
of $4.7 billion in November.
   January's increase in the seasonally adjusted rate of credit
growth was up slightly from a 7.8 percent in December but well below
the 8.5 percent rate in November.
   The Fed said a slower growth in auto loans and the category of
debt that includes credit cards helped keep the increase from being
greater , while loans for mobile homes increased after falling
sharply in December.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>$75 Million Program to Aid Waiting Addicts Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is infusing efforts to
rid America's streets of drug addicts and reduce the spread of AIDS
through expanded drug treatment services with $75 million in grants.
   Frederick K. Goodwin, head of the Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental
Health Administration said the money would be targeted for public
and private nonprofit organizations that are providing out-patient
or residential drug treatment services.
   The agency was most concerned with helping reduce and eliminate
the waiting lists of programs where applicants have been waiting
more than a month to be admitted. Goodwin said in some cities the
current wait to enter programs can be six months and longer.
   ``Given the fact that approximately one-third of all new AIDS
cases are contracted through use of contaminated intravenous
needles, it is especially critical that the nation's ability to
provide treatment to drug abusers be expanded,'' Goodwin said
Thursday as he announced the program.
   In addition to the new grant program, Frederick's agency, part of
the Department of Health and Human Services, is providing $518
million this fiscal year in block grants to states for substance
abuse treatment and prevention programs, a spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
