<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Massacre     03-10 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Massacre,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historian Says Soviets Were Guilty for Executing Polish Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish historian studying a World War II
massacre of more than 4,000 Polish army officers said he is
convinced the Soviets are to blame for the executions.
   Historian and parliament deputy Jarema Maciszewski made the
remarks in an interview Thursday in the official Communist Party
newspaper Trybuna Ludu. He serves as chairman of the Polish side of
a joint Polish-Soviet commission studying what are called historical
``blank spots.''
   The historian was quoted as saying he believes a tentative
conclusion blaming the Soviet Union for the killings at Katyn Forest
will stand.
   ``The expertise unequivocally indicates that all goes to show the
NKVD bodies (Soviet secret police) committed the crimes,'' he was
quoted as saying.
   The Soviet side on the commission, however, ``drew attention to
the fact that the data presented by us ... does not contain, because
it cannot contain, direct evidence of guilt,'' he said in the
interview.
   Maciszewski's interview followed similar remarks Tuesday by
government spokesman Jerzy Urban at his weekly news conference. He
announced two weeks ago that a Warsaw monument to the Katyn victims,
calling them victims of ``Hitler's fascism,'' will be changed.
   The Polish officers were shot through the back of the head and
buried in mass graves uncovered by the Germans at Katyn, near the
Soviet city of Smolensk, in 1943. The victims later were identified
as having been imprisoned in the Soviet Union shortly after the
September 1939 outbreak of World War II.
   The Nazis invaded Poland from the west and the Soviets followed
with an attack from the east when the war began. Germany and the
Soviet Union then signed a non-aggression pact which Hitler broke in
1941, sending invasion forces into the Soviet Union.
   Since assuming power at the end of World War II, communist
authorities in Poland had supported the Soviet version of the
massacre, asserting that the crime was committed by the Nazis in
1941 after their invasion of the Soviet Union.
   Most Poles and historians in the West had long ago concluded that
the killings were carried out on the orders of Stalin in 1940, when
Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union were still allied.
   The Katyn episode has come to constitute one of the most
emotional issues in Polish-Soviet relations. For many Poles, it is a
symbol of a long series of Soviet crimes against their country.
   In 1987, Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev agreed to appoint the joint commission to study
Katyn and other painful ``blank spots'' in history.
   Last month, after a parliament deputy complained that the Soviet
side was dragging its feet, Maciszewski unveiled a wartime Polish
Red Cross document found in British archives. He said it gave
incontrovertible evidence that the killings took place in 1940,
before the Nazis occupied the Katyn area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0055 </DOCNO>
