<FIRST>r i PM-China-Corruption     03-10 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Corruption,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desire to Go Abroad Leads to Corruption, Official Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The desire to leave China was the major cause of
the most serious corruption cases in Shanghai, an official daily
said today.
   The China Youth News said in six of 15 cases now before Shanghai
courts, young people either embezzled money or took bribes in order
to finance a life abroad.
   One 26-year-old accountant in a Shanghai embezzeled nearly
$19,000 so he could study in Australia. A businessman in a textile
company obtained $13,500 by embezzlement and bribery after he got a
passport and visa.
   An 23-year-old accountant in a bank embezzled $5,670 by making
false receipts to pay for her way out of China.
   The report said next most common were cases of people taking
bribes in connection with construction contracts.
   One deputy general manager of a construction company received
more than $27,000 in bribes for subcontracting work for a Chinese
Academy of Sciences building.
   Another man, named a ``construction hero'' for his good deeds for
Shanghai, was charged with taking $35,100 in bribes.
   China is now waging a nationwide campaign against corruption,
which has become increasingly serious in recent years because of
shortages of commodity goods and raw materials, rough edges in the
new market economy, and price discrepancies between
government-controlled items and those selling on free markets.
</TEXT>
