<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Eastern-Chapter11     03-10 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Chapter 11,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Chapter 11 Means For Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a rundown on how Eastern Airlines' Chapter 11 bankruptcy
filing will affect the carrier's operations:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GENERAL OPERATIONS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Under federal bankruptcy law, Eastern can continue flying and
reorganize its finances while protected from creditors. Any
reorganization plan is subject to approval by the bankruptcy court
and creditors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EMPLOYEES:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern may have a difficult time imposing lower wages on
striking employees since federal law requires bankrupt companies to
negotiate with unions and prove economic necessity before abrogating
their contracts.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said the carrier is prepared to hire
non-union pilots if pilots honoring the Machinists' strike do not
return to work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PASSENGERS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The bankruptcy court must approve ticket refunds, said Eastern
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak, adding that she did not know how the
process would work. In the eyes of the court, ticketholders are
considered unsecured creditors, trailing secured creditors in
priority.
   But passengers who bought tickets with a major credit card
probably won't have to stand in line at the courthouse since federal
law protects consumers who make credit card purchases but fail to
receive goods or services. At Visa U.S.A. Inc., for example,
requests for credit must be submitted no more than 120 days after
the flight date, said spokesman David Brancoli.
   Eastern, meanwhile, will try to get as many planes back in the
air as possible in order to make ``old tickets good,'' Bakes said.
   The company also plans to renegotiate agreements with other
carriers to honor Eastern tickets. Passengers have had mixed success
trying to swap Eastern tickets for seats on other carriers.
Continental Airlines is accepting Eastern tickets, but other
airlines have different policies.
   Chances remained good that if the passenger's destination were a
popular one, another carrier would honor the ticket, although
possibly at a higher price.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ROUTES:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Currently operating shuttle flights linking Boston, New York and
Washington as well as scaled-back service to Latin America, Eastern
plans to restore unspecified routes as its financial situation
improves. Bakes said, however, that the carrier's ``immediate
emphasis'' will be on the shuttle and Latin American routes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TAKEOVER BIDS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern's bankruptcy filing would not prevent takeover bids,
though an acquisition might be cumbersome since creditor and
bankruptcy court approval is required. Bakes said he would not
speculate on ``any future transactions,'' an apparent reference to
Trans World Airlines Chairman and takeover strategist Carl Icahn,
who has said he is willing to discuss a bid for the airline.
   Bakes said Eastern will consider selling assets to restore
liquidity, like the planned $365 million sale of the shuttle to New
York developer Donald Trump. Assets sales also require court
approval.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>INVESTORS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bakes said ``all creditors will be fully paid'' and shareholders
can expect fair value for their stock. But Standard and Poor's
Corp., a major credit-rating agency, either downgraded or expressed
concern about $277.2 million of Eastern debt.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOUTH FLORIDA'S ECONOMY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The state Commerce Department estimated Eastern's payroll in Dade
County, which includes Miami, has added $500 million a year to the
economy, plus $150 million in indirect income based on employee
purchases.
   Tom Ferguson, president of the county's Beacon Council economic
development group, estimated the Miami-based carrier has a $1
billion to $1.5 billion impact in a $50 billion local economy.
   ``Miami was hurting even before the strike,'' said J. Antonio
Villamil, chief economist with Southeast Bank. ``Because of what has
happened, our economy will be flat at best in 1989.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
