<FIRST>u i PM-ComicRelief Bjt   03-10 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comic Relief, Bjt,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITING a0475 to make slug conform to PM-News Digest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Veddy Funny: Millions Of Britons Don Red Noses</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON-6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's stiff upper lip broke into a big grin
today as millions of people put on red plastic noses, wallowed in
baked beans, donned gnome suits and pretty much turned the day into
a big laughing matter.
   Despite the outbreak of mass silliness, organizers of some worthy
causes will be laughing all the way to the bank if today's ``Red
Nose Day 2'' is as successful as last year's inaugural charity
drive, which raised $27 million.
   The idea behind the fund-raising effort, which was organized by a
group of British comedians and run by a coalition of groups called
Comic Relief, is to get Britons to loosen their pursestrings while
they laugh.
   Two-thirds of this year's cash will go to Third World projects
and to Princess Anne's Save the Children Fund, and the rest to
programs in Britain to help young people and the elderly.
   Britain has been gearing up for today all week. Cars, trucks and
taxis have been sporting big red plastic noses on their hoods and
radiators.
   On Thursday, Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke and two government
colleagues wore red plastic noses and posed for press photographers,
and soldiers paraded with guns and red noses at the Yeomanry
Barracks in York in northern England.
   Most Britons, however, saved their red noses for today. The goofy
89 cent props are purchased from the sponsoring charities, a
national store chain and in many pubs. A chain of gas stations is
selling the car schnozzes for $1.72.
   All proceeds go to Comic Relief.
   As of Thursday night, more than 4.5 million red noses for people
and 2 million for autos had been sold, with a big surge in sales
expected today.
   Rowan Atkinson, Billy Connolly and other top British comedians
predicted that 7 million Britons would don red noses today.
   Tied in with ``Red Nose Day 2'' are 50,000 fund-raising stunts
registered with Comic Relief.
   The stunts range from Ian Hunt's 10-hour wallow in a bathtub full
of cold baked beans at the Sutton Arms pub in London _ for which his
supporters have pledged $1,720 dollars _ to customers at a pub near
Swansea who will hold a candlelit supper atop eight tons of cow dung.
   Several of the staff at the historic Tower of London, one of the
capital's top tourist attractions, planned to spend their working
day clanking round in suits of armor.
   Officers at Leytonstone police station in east London will direct
evening traffic dressed as garden gnomes.
   As last year, the British Broadcasting Corp. plans a seven-hour
comedy extravaganza on television to mark Red Nose Day 2, starring
Comic Relief stalwart Lenny Henry, Atkinson, Rhys Jones, Phil
Collins and more than 100 other show business personalities.
   The French nobleman the Duc de Sully said 359 years ago that the
English take their pleasures sadly. Even today, not everyone is
enamored with red noses.
   ``There is a lot to be said for having no sense of humor... Life
is a vale of tears...'' Columnist Geoffrey Wheatcroft wrote today in
the London newspaper The Daily Telegraph on Friday:
   ``What is more objectionable about today's stunt than its
childishness is its forced merriment... Our own post-Christian
Christmas is bad enough, with its relentless mandatory mirth; it is
not hard to understand why the week around Dec. 25 has the highest
suicide rate of the year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
