<FIRST>r a PM-MissingClimbers     03-10 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Climbers,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>McKinley Rescue Teams Await Weather Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALKEETNA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Park Service ranger says he
remains optimistic about the fate of three missing Japanese climbers
who have been on Mount McKinley for two weeks.
   The men were described as experienced climbers with excellent
gear and a radio, although contact has not been made.
   ``The ingredients (for survival) are there if they can put it
together,'' Ranger Bob Seibert said Thursday. ``It's been a long
time, though. It sure has.''
   Hurricane-force wind around North America's largest peak
prevented rugged Army helicopters from joining the search Thursday.
An Air Force plane sent up to check wind conditions around the peak
65 miles from Talkeetna reached the 14,000-foot level and
encountered turbulence.
   Crews planned to try again today.
   The climbers were seen by an Austrian team on Feb. 22. The
Austrians were descending and the apanese, who set out Feb. 16, were
ascending the 20,320-foot peak.
   ``It took the Austrians a few days to get down. Nobody has heard
from the Japanese since,'' said John Quinley, a park service
spokesman.
   The climbers' rations probably ran out days ago, but the Park
Service has a cache of food and water at 17,200 feet, Quinley said.
   Members of the Japanese party are leader Noboru Yamada, 39, Teruo
Saegusa, 31, and Kozo Komatsu, 34, all of Tokyo.

</TEXT>
