<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArmyBoxing     03-10 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Army Boxing,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boxing Causing Dozens of Military Hospitalizations Yearly, Study
Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors today delivered a haymaker to the U.S.
military's boxing program, saying the sport used to maintain fitness
for decades has killed at least one soldier and hospitalized 401
others over a six-year period.
   Army soldiers spent 2,056 days in the hospital and logged 3,581
sick days because of boxing injuries from 1980 through 1985,
military doctors said in today's issue of the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
   ``Head injuries accounted for 68 percent of all boxing-related
hospitalizations and 81 percent of (boxing-related) injuries to U.S.
Military Academy cadets,'' said the doctors, led by Maj. Robert W.
Enzenauer, an eye doctor at Fitzsimons Army Medical Center in
Aurora, Colo.
   But a former military boxing coach disagreed with the study,
saying the sport provides excellent mental and physical training and
probably produces fewer serious injuries than college football or
wrestling.
   ``In football, you have the kids that are paralyzed, the kids
that die,'' said Emerson Smith, head boxing coach at the U.S. Naval
Academy for 27 years and chairman of the U.S.A. Amateur Boxing
Federation's Safety Committee.
   ``I don't believe there's any high school or college ... where
you have contact sports where you'll eliminate all serious injury,''
he said.
   Instructional boxing is mandatory at U.S. service academies.
Military graduates known for their boxing prowess as undergraduates
include former Navy Secretary James Webb and retired Marine Col.
Oliver North.
   Enzenauer, who boxed when he attended the U.S. Military Academy,
said sports like the martial arts or fencing would provide the same
benefits without the risks of injury to the central nervous system.
   ``It's inconsistent to train a soldier, to spend money on him, to
teach him how to fly a helicopter, to repair a jeep, to drive a
tank, and then (to have him) participate in a sport that could
conceivably make him unfit for duty,'' Enzenauer said in a telephone
interview Thursday.
   ``There is other military training ... that can teach a soldier
how to deal with fear, how to improve his self-confidence, his
self-esteem, without offering such a risk,'' he said.
   Unlike football or wrestling, the objective in boxing is to
achieve a knockout, which by definition is an injury to the brain,
Enzenauer said.
   The study found that 401 soldiers had been hospitalized in the
six-year period, and one died after complications from bleeding
inside the skull caused by boxing. Another was blinded in one eye.
   ``Evidence that boxing produces irreversible brain damage is now
as indisputable as the link between cigarette smoking and lung
cancer,'' the doctors wrote.
   Concussions, bruising of brain tissue, bleeding inside the skull,
broken facial bones and eye injuries were among the types of head
trauma recorded.
   The study did not examine the price tag for hospital care and
lost productivity due to boxing but said the cost ``is certainly
considerable.''
   Military boxing has served as a springboard to some spectacular
careers. Leon Spinks, a Marine when he won a gold medal at the 1976
Montreal Olympics, eventually defeated Muhammad Ali for the world
heavyweight title.
   Three gold medalists at the 1988 Olympics were U.S. Army boxers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salinas     03-10 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salinas,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salinas Stronger With Dramatic Moves In First 100 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari today marks the
100th day of his presidency as a more powerful leader whose
political skills have earned respect even from critics.
   The bald, mustachioed 40-year-old economist won the slimmest
victory in the history of his party, which has controlled Mexican
politics for most of this century. He then struggled through rocky
early days when his opponents claimed the election was rigged.
   Since then, however, he has widened his support with measures
aimed at restoring economic confidence and political stability in
advance of vital negotiations over Mexico's foreign debt.
   ``He has gained credibility,'' said Pablo Emilio Madero, former
presidential candidate and a leader of the conservative National
Action Party. The party is the country's second largest behind the
government's Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   Salinas took office after a fraud-marred election in which he
polled barely more than 50 percent. The governing party ended up
with a 260-240 margin in Congress, its lowest ever, and a vocal
leftist coalition that predicted Salinas wouldn't last.
   But infighting has weakened the leftist coalition put together by
Salinas' main opponent in the election, said opposition leader
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
   And on the right, Salinas undercut conservatives by moving to
weed out corruption, install a freer economy, and improve government
relations with the Roman Catholic church.
   ``Salinas has more political strength now than he did at the
start of his administration,'' said Jorge Arrambide, director of an
association of business groups in the northern state of Nuevo Leon.
``He has struck some spectacular blows with the purpose of getting
massive popular support he did not have in the elections.''
   In January, Salinas' popularity soared when he cracked down on
corrupt oil union leaders once considered invulnerable. He showed an
even hand by also jailing top businessmen accused of shady dealings
during the 1987 stock market crash.
   Salinas appeased the left by firing a hard-line police official
and releasing political prisoners, acknowledging their existence for
the first time.
   He also pledged to wean his party from its chronic use of state
resources in election campaigns and of vote-rigging _ pledges still
questioned by the opposition.
   ``He is making decisions,'' said Jesus Cantu, director of the
independent newspaper El Porvenir. ``The question is whether the
decisions will result in something good or turn out to be just a
little makeup.''
   The government's most immediate problem is the foreign debt,
estimated by the World Bank at $107.4 billion. Salinas wants to cut
in half annual payments, which totaled $14 billion last year, to
free funds for economic growth.
   The economy has been stagnant for six years, and Salinas is under
pressure from a growing population whose standard of living has
dropped steadily. An estimated 1 million new jobs are needed a year.
   Political parties and business groups have rallied to Salinas'
efforts to stem the cash flow resulting from the debt. Nationwide
riots last week in Venezuela also may help Salinas' cause by
alarming creditors.
   Some say the toughness Salinas displayed against the oil union
could just as easily be turned on creditors.
   ``Creditors need to believe that Mexico will resort to a
suspension of payments,'' said Jonathan Heath, chief economic
analyst for the Macro Asesoria consulting firm. ``Salinas has proven
he could provide a credible threat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
