<FIRST>r a PM-Cavazos     03-10 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cavazos,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Visits South Bronx Catholic School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<UNK>AP Education Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parochial schools may have a friend in new U.S.
Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, but he has made it clear that
probably won't sway him into recommending federal tuition tax breaks.
   Cavazos on Thursday visited St. Augustine School of the Arts, the
Roman Catholic grade school proclaimed as an educational oasis in
economically depressed South Bronx on CBS's ``60 minutes'' last
December.
   The school has been praised for its highly unusual curriculum
blending fine arts, especially music, with academic basics. But fame
has not brought fortune, and finances are so tight that ``at times
teachers have been asked not to cash their paychecks,'' said Father
Robert Jeffers, pastor of St. Augustine's.
   St. Augustine's, the only parochial school in the New York
archdiocese specializing in fine arts, admits all comers regardless
of potential talent, unlike most such schools.
   The school's 320 children in kindergarten through eighth grade
are required to study piano through at least fourth grade, and at
least another musical instrument thereafter.
   Cavazos lavished praise on St. Augustine and its mostly black
children. But he stopped short of holding out any promise of
financial relief.
   ``I think that any school that is well run, that is orderly, that
is free of drugs, all schools should be like that,'' Cavazos said.
   But, he said, ``I'm not really pushing for tuition tax credits or
vouchers.''
   ``I still am very optimistic,'' said principal Tom Pilecki. ``I'm
hopeful his visit here will help him see the strength of Catholic
schools. ... We don't have any money at all. We don't have a cent.''
   Tuition at St. Augustine's is only $1,100 a year. Teacher
salaries average just $17,000, half what New York City public school
teachers earn, Pilecki said. The 11 professional musicians and
artists who teach the school's special arts program average $13,000.
   The arts program is supported by about $350,000 a year in
foundation and corporate grants.
   William J. Bennett, Cavazos' predecessor, championed the cause of
parochial education. He pressed often, though unsuccessfully, for
federal tax breaks for parents paying private school tuition. And he
argued repeatedly that urban public schools could learn a lesson or
two from Catholic educators in preserving orderly schools.
   From the 1970s through 1984, enrollment at St. Augustine dropped
from about 500 to fewer than 200. The New York archdiocese was
considering shutting down St. Augustine's.
   But the school saved itself by devising an unusual curriculum
built around fine arts in the fall of 1984. Enrollment has since
rebounded to 320.
   The arts program has paid off, Father Jeffers said, because ``it
gives children a constant sense of accomplishment.''
   ``I would hope Cavazos would see some model here that could be
duplicated in other urban situations,'' said Jeffers.
   Cavazos also visited the Brooklyn campus of Long Island
University to help that school launch a new National Institute for
Hispanic Leadership. The institute's goal is to help Hispanic
youngsters gain leadership positions in the education field, and
eventually in other fields as well.
   ``Universities around this country must, I repeat must, recruit
more minority students,'' he said, and provide more scholarships for
such students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
