<FIRST>r a PM-MissionFromLockerbie     03-10 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mission From Lockerbie,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scottish Authorities in United States to Meet Families of Lockerbie
Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senior Scottish police officials are visiting
some families of the 259 victims of the Lockerbie plane disaster to
clear up what they consider a misunderstanding about victims'
belongings.
   The officers from the Dumfries and Galloway police forces will
visit several U.S. cities and talk to relatives who have complained
that the police have been slow in releasing the personal effects of
those who died in the December terrorist bomb blast aboard the Pan
Am jet.
   ``I lost a 16-year-old daughter and she had four suitcases with
her, almost everything she owned,'' said Paul Hudson, an Albany,
N.Y., lawyer who formed the 300-member relatives support group,
Victims of Pan Am 103. ``She had her Christmas presents with her.
Many of our memories of her were with her on that plane.''
   Only five or six relatives of the victims have received any
possessions, Hudson said.
   ``It's the last thing they have to remember their sons and
daughters,'' said North Adams Mayor Jim Barrett, who represented
several western Massachusetts families after the crash. ``Rings,
bracelets, it would mean so much to them to get them back.''
   The British policemen arrived in Boston Wednesday night and flew
to Washington Thursday to meet with U.S. State Department officials.
   ``We feel that to try to ease the frustrations of the relatives
here we should come personally and explain to various groups of
relatives exactly what the position is,'' Assistant Chief Constable
Paul Newell told British television before he left for the United
States.
   A letter of concern from the families that was sent to Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher last month may have resulted in the
officers' visit, said Hudson.
   ``It's a very emotional time,'' said Joe Horgan, whose
brother-in-law was on Flight 103. ``The additional trauma of not
having things returned means that the healing process cannot hit
full stride.''
   But Horgan, a member of the relatives group in charge of property
return, said the families are not angry with Scottish officials.
Horgan, who has visited police in Lockerbie, said Scottish law
differs from American law and authorities there did not want to
release what they consider evidence into a criminal investigation.
   He said the families became upset after receiving a letter from a
U.S. State Department official last month that hinted that some of
the victims' luggage and clothing might be destroyed.
   Horgan said ``all sorts of rumors and innuendo started after
that'' but it was found later to be false. Scottish authorities
``have been very sensitive to our needs,'' he said.
   The Scottish police met with State Department officials Thursday
to work out details of the visits, said department spokeswoman
Frances Jones.
   ``We will be accompanying them and making ourselves available to
family members for any questions they might have of us,'' she said.
   The Scottish policemen will meet with families in New York on
Saturday and in Boston on Sunday, travel to Detroit on Monday and
see families in Canton, Ohio, Tuesday.
   Police recovered more than 11,000 items of property scattered
over an area of 845 square miles.
</TEXT>
