<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     03-10 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Conference Proposes Refugee Solutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates from 30 nations have
drafted a plan asking Vietnam to curtail the exodus of boat people
from its shores, officials at the international conference said.
   However, the group, which ended a three-day meeting Thursday,
ruled out forcibly repatriating asylum-seekers who cannot show they
are fleeing political persecution, officials said.
   The delegates laid out the measures in a draft plan for
consideration at the International Conference on Indochinese
Refugees in Geneva in June.
   Chairman Majid Mohamed told a news conference the plan would help
``provide durable solutions to the Indochinese refugee problem.''
   The draft plan suggests Vietnam launch a campaign stressing the
risks and hardships of fleeing by boat and work to end illegal
departures by boat people. It also calls on Vietnam to make legal
departures easier.
   Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and other
countries in the region have agreed to provide only temporary asylum
for refugees. Western nations were urged to take in refugees left in
camps in Southeast Asia.
   Officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the conference
voted not to recommend a deadline by which those seeking asylum
would be screened to decide whether they qualified for resettlement
in the West.
   Officials said Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Australia, and some other Southeast Asian countries had
asked the conference to recommend forcible repatriation of boat
people and others fleeing their countries for reasons other than
political persecution.
   Vietnam, the United States, Sweden, the U.N. high commissioner
for refugees were among nations opposed tyo forced repatriation on
humanitarian grounds, said the officials.
   ``The rules are very clear ... whenever refugees are repatriated,
it has to be on a voluntary basis,'' said Jean Pierre Hocke, the
U.N. high commissioner for refugees.
   The officials said the Vietnamese delegation, led by Deputy
Foreign Minister Vu Khoan, had agreed at the conference to take back
anyone who wanted to return voluntarily.
   Western delegations present said they might take in additional
refugees and step up financial aid to help implement the plan.
   So far, 150,000 people have emigrated legally from Vietnam under
its Orderly Departure Program.
   There are about 300,000 Indochinese refugees in Southeast Asia.
About 1.5 million have been resettled since the outflow began 10
years ago, more than 800,000 of them in the United States, officials
said.
   Majid said the plan would be sent to U.N. Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar in New York for the Geneva conference June
13-14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
