<HEAD>Bomb Blast Damages French-Owned Bank ^Eds: UPDATES throughout with
details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through the offices of
the Athens branch of the Banque Nationale de Paris early today,
causing extensive damage but no injuries, police reported.
   The 4 a.m. explosion sparked fires at shops adjacent to the
French-owned bank in the fashionable Kolonaki district of the
capital, police said.
   It took firefighters two hours to bring the flames under control
in the seven-story building where the bank is located. Windows in
nearby stores were shattered and at least four cars parked nearby
were damaged.
   Police said no organization immediately claimed responsibility
for the blast.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it
was one of the most powerful bomb blasts in recent times. ``I
presume (it) was set off by some Greek terrorist group,'' he said.
   Authorities said the blast was caused by a time bomb.
   Police said officials were surprised the bombers had specifically
singled out a French-owned bank for attack. However, leftist Greek
terrorist groups have bombed banks in the past.
