<FIRST>r i PM-Uganda-Kenya     03-10 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uganda-Kenya,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uganda Denies Bombing Kenyan Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uganda has denied Kenyan charges that one
of its airplanes bombed a Kenyan border village. Ugandan newspapers
today accused Kenyan soldiers of raiding a village across the border.
   The Ugandan Ministry of Foreign Affairs said on Thursday it had
sent no aircraft near the Kenyan border town of Lokichogio, where
Kenya said an Ugandan aircraft attacked on Tuesday. Kenya's Ministry
of Foreign Affairs sent Uganda a protest note Wednesday accusing
Uganda of the attack, which Kenya said killed five people and
injured four.
   The two sides also traded charges of cross-border cattle raids.
Tribal warriors on both sides of the border have traditionally
raided each other.
   The New Vision newspaper, quoting unidentified Ugandan officials,
said Kenya troop movements had been observed near the twin border
towns of Busia. The state-owned newspaper said troops dug trenches
around the airstrip there.
   ``Some Kenyan attackers wearing army uniforms and armed with guns
raided Bukwa in Kapchorwa district and stole cattle from residents
early this week,'' the independent Guide weekly newspaper reported.
   Kenyan and Ugandan security personnel in December 1987 traded
gunshots at Busia, 210 miles west of Kenya's capital, Nairobi. Kenya
admitted no loses on its side but claimed to have killed 20 Ugandans.
   Land-locked Uganda, which depends on Kenya for land transport to
the Indian Ocean, said three of its soldiers were killed in the
conflict.
</TEXT>
