<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Executions     03-10 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Executions,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Executes 81 Drug Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran reportedly hanged 81 drug smugglers
today, the highest daily toll since it began cracking down on
illegal drugs in January.
   The smugglers were convicted of possessing and selling heroin,
opium, hashish and other narcotics and were executed in Tehran and
26 other cities, Tehran radio said in a report monitored in Nicosia.
   Some also were convicted of theft, illegal possesion of arms,
kidnapping, and ``indecent acts in contravention to Islamic law,''
the radio said.
   The executions are part of a continuing crackdown on drug
addiction in Iran. Today's hangings bring to 356 the number of
executions reported by Iran since a new anti-drugs law went into
effect Jan 21.
   The previous high toll for one day was 70 executions on Feb. 14.
The new law carries the death sentence for possession of even small
quantities of drugs and gives addicts six months to kick the habit
or face jail terms.
   Earlier this week, the radio quoted an unidentified source at the
country's main law enforcement agency, the Komiteh, who said the
six-month grace period granted to addicts will expire July 23, after
which they will be prosecuted.
   The source said more than 50 tons of illegal drugs were seized
during a 12-month period ending March 21, the radio reported.
</TEXT>
