<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-NewYork     03-10 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-New York,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says `Hunting Season' On Cops Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tough-talking President Bush brought his
anti-drug message to New York, a city where ``the war on drugs is no
metaphor.''
   Bush flew to New York Thursday to pay tribute to law enforcement
officers killed in the line of duty and met with the widow of a Drug
Enforcement Administration agent killed last week.
   Later in the day, Bush used an address to the United Negro
College Fund to repeat his anti-drug theme.
   ``My friends, drug abuse is America's 20th Century version of
human slavery,'' Bush said. ``It chains the spirit and imperils the
ability to learn.''
   He vowed to wage ``unconditional war'' against drug abuse and
said, ``We must fight on every front: education, treatment,
interdiction, enforcement.''
   In his speech at the DEA offices in Manhattan, the president
cited legislation passed by Congress last year providing the death
penalty for drug kingpins who commit murder while trafficking in
drugs.
   ``Just as the penalty for cop killers helps even the odds,
stripping our enemies of their ill-gotten gains turns the table in a
dramatic and highly effective way,'' he said.
   ``I have some bad news for the bad guys: Hunting season is over.
The rules on our side have changed too. It's about time.
   ``Here in New York City, as in other cities across the country,
the war on drugs is no metaphor,'' he said. ``Before we could bury
(DEA Agent) Everett Hatcher last week, another officer was gunned
down, felled by a single shot fired pointblank beneath his
bulletproof vest.''
   Bush, who headed a drug interdiction task force as vice
president, met with Hatcher's widow, Mary Jane Hatcher, just before
his speech.
   Bush, who has opposed strict gun controls and who has defended
the right of sportsmen and hunters to have semiautomatic rifles, did
say in his speech that he has asked William Bennett, his drug policy
coordinator, to ``look into what can be done to prevent fully
automatic assault weapons from falling into the hands of the
criminals you face.''
   On Feb. 9, Bush asked Congress for $5.5 billion for the war on
drugs, with the bulk of that going to law enforcement efforts,
including intensified border interdiction.
   At the same time, he is trying to put pressure on law enforcement
officials and leaders in other countries to staunch the flow of
drugs to the United States. Bush noted that he will soon receive a
report from Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on his just-completed
trip to Bolivia, Colombia and Peru.
</TEXT>
