<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Berlin 1stLd-Writethru a0516 03-10 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Party Joins Social Democrats In West Berlin Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with business threatening to leave
city because of environmentalists. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist party today agreed to join the Social
Democrats in forming a coalition government in West Berlin, a move
that businesses said could cause them to leave the divided city.
   The coalition of the left-leaning Social Democrats and the far
left Alternative List, the West Berlin equivalent of the anti-NATO
Greens Party, also has prompted Conservative West German politicians
from Chancellor Helmut Kohl on down to warn of dire consequences for
the city.
   Businessmen have opposed the Alternative List's insistence on
tighter environmental controls and claim the leftist group creates a
bad climate for investment. Some businessmen warned they may leave
the city, which had been dominated by Kohl's Christian Democratic
Union.
   The Social Democrats and the Christian Democrats won 55 seats
each in the West Berlin legislature in the Jan. 29 elections.
   The Alternative List won 17 seats and the far-right Republican
Party stunned many West Germans by winning 11 seats.
   After weeks of sometimes tense talks, negotiators for the two
leftist parties announced agreement on the details of the government
early today. The agreement was expected to win easy formal approval
from the full membership of both parties within days.
   The agreement outlined to the news media gives the Alternative
List three senators, who are the equivalent of Cabinet ministers in
other West German state systems. As a result, the far-leftists will
be in charge of programs for the environment, city development,
education, sports, families and youth.
   The Alternative List also has advocated more curbs on the police,
limits on motor vehicle use and more government-subsidized housing.
   Under the leftist coalition government, Social Democrat Walter
Momper will become the new mayor of West Berlin. He will replace
Eberhard Diepgen, whose Christian Democrats suffered severe setbacks
in elections on Jan. 29.
   The Christian Democrats had been actively promoting business
development in West Berlin to help end the isolation of the city 90
miles inside communist East German territory.
   The United States has promoted greater airline access to West
Berlin and has suggested that the city could be the site of U.N.
meetings as well as world conferences on human rights, arms control
and other issues.
   The far-right Republican Partym which has called for the ouster
of foreign workers and asylum seekers from West Berlin, is excluded
from the governing coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
