<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Libya     03-10 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian, Libyan Woman Appointed To Libyan Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya has announced changes in the government's
Cabinet that include the appointment of an Egyptian and the first
female minister.
   Libyan television and the official Libyan news agency JANA
Thursday reported the changes in the General People's Committee.
   The Cabinet spots are bureaucratic posts with little power. Col.
Moammar Gadhafi and a small group of close advisers run the country.
   Cabinet changes are announced each year at the annual meeting of
the General People's Congress, which consists of representatives of
the local grass-roots committees that make up the Libyan government.
   Jadallah Azzuz Al-Talhi will remain foreign minister, according
to the news reports, monitored in Rome.
   Umar Mustafa Al-Muntasir will remain prime minister _ or
secretary of the General People's Committee _ a post that does not
carry the influence it does in other countries.
   Libyan television said the Congress appointed an Egyptian, Amin
Halimi Uthman Kamil, as secretary of the General People's Committee
for Light Industries. The official Libyan news agency JANA said the
appointment demonstrated that Libya ``is the land for all Arabs.''
   Kamil was minister of light industry in Egypt under the late
President Gamal Abdul Nasser and since 1986 has worked as a
consultant to the Libyan Ministry of Industry, JANA said.
   The agency said Fatimah Abd Al-Hafiz Mukhtar became the first
woman appointed to a Cabinet post when she was named secretary of
the General People's Committee for Education.
   ``Such a step, the promotion of a woman to this popular position,
comes within the context of ... enabling woman to impose her will
and occupy her position in the people's administration,'' JANA said.
</TEXT>
