<SECOND>PM-Coma Woman,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comatose Woman Transferred To New Jersey Rehabilitation Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A comatose New York woman who received an
abortion after an emotional legal battle started an evaluation and
therapy program today at a rehabilitation center in this central New
Jersey community.
   ``We're committed to long-term care. ... We're talking months,
not weeks,'' said Dr. Keith D. Cicerone, clinical director of trauma
rehabilitation at John F. Kennedy Medical Center's Robert Wood
Johnson Jr. Rehabilitation Institute.
   Doctors will evaluate Nancy Klein and make an initial prognosis
on her condition in four to six weeks, Cicerone said. He declined to
give her condition or specific details of treatment, citing a
request by the family.
   Mrs. Klein has been comatose since suffering severe brain
injuries in a Dec. 13 automobile accident near her Long Island home.
She had been at North Shore Hospital on Long Island before being
transferred to the institute Thursday.
   Her husband, Martin Klein, went to court last month and won
guardianship of his wife so he could authorize the abortion. She was
17 weeks pregnant.
   Anti-abortion activists challenged the guardianship and appealed
to the U.S. Supreme Court, which declined to hear the case.
   In a lower court, doctors for both sides disagreed about whether
having an abortion could help Mrs. Klein recover.
   She could spend up to two years at the center, and then
additional years receiving out-patient treatment, Cicerone said. The
family was not present.
   Klein said in an interview that he told his wife not to be
scared, although he's not sure she understands. ``I told her we had
worked hard to get her into a place that will get her home faster,''
he said.
   Mrs. Klein's relatives said they have been encouraged by signs of
progress since the abortion on Feb. 11.
   Anne Zusselman, of Delray Beach, Fla., has said her daughter can
move her head to both sides, open her mouth and lift her left arm on
command.
   Doctors at North Shore continue to offer little hope for her
recovery.
   ``Doctors have seen a slight neurological improvement in Mrs.
Klein,'' said North Shore spokesman Daniel Rosette. ``They won't
predict her long-term prognosis, despite the slight signs of
improvement.''
</TEXT>
