<HEAD>Students, Workers Observe Labor Day With Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students demanding better pay
and rights for workers battled police today in Seoul as thousands of
workers observed Korean Labor Day with nationwide rallies calling
for free union activity.
   Riot police fired tear gas to block 200 students from marching
off Joong-Ang University in southern Seoul.
   The students pelted police with rocks and lobbed firebombs at
them in fighting that lasted about 40 minutes. There were no
injuries or arrests.
   At peaceful rallies in Seoul and at least four other cities,
workers accused the government of siding with company owners and of
suppressing free union activity.
   About 10,000 workers affiliated with the Federation of Korea
Trade Unions gathered at a gymnasium in Seoul to urge the government
to ensure labor rights and better pay and working conditions.
   Labor unrest has plagued hudreds of companies this year, and
government officials predict more and longer labor disputes in April
and May.
   In the southeastern port of Ulsan, Hundai Heavy Industries Co.,
South Korea's largest shipyard, remained shut because of a bitter
labor dispute that began Dec. 12.
