<HEAD>Subway Train Rams Work Train; 36 People Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subway train carrying about 150 subway
passengers rammed into a work train today on Manhattan's upper West
Side, injuring 36 people and disrupting the rush hour for thousands
of commuters, authorities said.
   Though many of the passengers were hurled from their seats, none
of the injuries was considered life-threatening, said Transit
Authority spokesman Bob Previdi. Three people were taken to
hospitals and 33 were treated at the scene after the 5 a.m. accident.
   The accident happened when a southbound West Side local rammed a
revenue train that was stopped at the 103rd Street station. Previdi
said the revenue train travels from station to station collecting
money from the token booths. He estimated about 150 passengers were
aboard the local train and five or six Transit Authority workers on
the revenue train.
   He could not immediately say how fast the local train was
traveling at the time of the accident. The cause was under
investigation.
   Commuters faced extensive delays through the morning as a result
of the accident.
