<FIRST>r a PM-ArtWindfall     03-10 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art Windfall,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bargain Painting Worth Thousands, Couple Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Miller couldn't believe his eyes when he
saw a painting of the Millersburg Ferry on the Susquehanna River
near his former home in Pennsylvania.
   A volunteer for Goodwill Industries, he bought the painting for
$12 as soon as the charitable organization began its annual art sale
last year. He was prepared to pay up to $100.
   But he and his wife, Ruth, couldn't believe their ears when they
found out how much the painting was worth _ $35,000 to $50,000.
   ``At first I just laughed about it,'' Mrs. Miller said Wednesday
as she and her husband helped set up this year's sale at the Arizona
State Fairgrounds. ``I thought it was funny. It took a little while
for it to set in.''
   The painting, signed by Ned Smith, a wildlife artist who died in
1985, features a stern-wheel ferry that has operated on the
Susquehanna for more than 150 years, with the central Pennsylvania
community of Millersburg in the background.
   ``I recognized it right away. It's about 20 miles from where we
were born and raised'' in Juniata County, said Miller, a retired
police officer.
   Last summer, an appraiser and the Pennsylvania Historical Society
for Fine Arts told the Millers what the painting was worth.
   Even though he knows he can get up to $50,000 for the painting,
Miller doesn't intend to sell it.
   ``Why sell it and have to give half the money to Uncle Sam?'' he
asked.
   Instead, he plans to loan the painting to the Pennsylvania
Historical Society for Fine Arts on a long-term basis.
</TEXT>
