<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Poison Gas, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Egypt Reportedly Plans To Build Chemical Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Swiss company reaction. Stands for
PM-Switzerland-Poison Gas on Digest update. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss engineering company today said
it has cut its business links with a military-industrial complex in
Egypt that reportedly plans to build a plant to produce poison gas.
   The company said it believed the parts it shipped to Egypt would
be used to produce pharmaceuticals but that it severed its business
relationship with the Egyptian complex on the advice of the Swiss
government.
   The comment by Krebs A.G. followed a news report in The New York
Times today saying that U.S. officials believe Egypt is assembling
Swiss-made parts that could be used to create a chemical weapons
plant.
   The report, quoting Swiss and U.S. officials, said the Bush
administration hasn't decided how to respond to the reported
Egyptian plan.
   The Times said Krebs delivered to Egypt parts that will be
installed in a plant at Abu Zaabal, north of Cairo.
   But Mohammed Wahby, a spokesman for Egypt's Embassy in
Washington, denied Egypt plans to build a chemical-weapons plant.
``We are not involved in the manufacture of chemical weapons,'' the
Times quoted him as saying.
   The plant is part of a military-industrial complex that is also
scheduled to include someday a joint Egyptian-American plant for
assembling the M-1 tank, the newspaper said.
   An unidentified U.S. official told the Times the Bush
administration's efforts to stop the proliferation of chemical
weapons applies to all countries and not just those which have had
hostile relations with the United States.
   The administration official was quoted as saying the United
States has not decided how it will respond to the information about
Egypt, a nation that could play a key role in U.S. efforts to bring
a peace settlement to the Middle East.
   But the Times quoted another U.S. official as saying the United
States had recently told Egypt it was concerned about the project.
   The paper quoted a Swiss Foreign Ministry official as saying his
government had ``reason to believe'' the plant was intended to make
poison gas. It also quoted him as saying he would not provide
details because he had to protect intelligence sources.
   Kreb's president, Hans Rudolf Weber, told The Associated Press
today that the company cut ties to the military-industrial complex
in Egypt on the advice of the Swiss government. He would not
elaborate.
   Weber said Egyptian authorities told his company that the Abu
Zaabal plant would be controlled by the Health Ministry and would
produce pharmaceuticals. He said Krebs A.G. has supplied the plant
with parts since 1976 but has now halted all deliveries and also was
no longer sending any experts to Egypt.
   The state secretary in the Swiss Foreign Office, Klaus Jacobi,
sent a letter to Krebs last week demanding that the company sever
its relationship with the project, the Foreign Ministry official
said.
</TEXT>
