<FIRST>r a PM-People-Ray     03-10 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Ray,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Date of Guilty Plea Just Another Day to James Earl Ray</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   March 10 has double significance for
James Earl Ray: it was 20 years ago today that he pleaded guilty to
killing the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and it's also his 61st
birthday.
   But no celebrations were planned by Ray, now a Brushy Mountain
State Prison inmate. He spent another day working in the prison's
laundry and continued to pass time on his 99-year prison term.
   ``This is a big holiday for prosecutors, judges and the media to
celebrate,'' Ray said in a telephone interview from the prison.
``Not me.''
   Former Shelby County District Attorney General Phil Canale and
his assistant, now Court of Criminal Appeals Judge Robert Dwyer,
don't have any parties planned either. Dwyer said he has only one
regret about that day.
   ``I was actually disappointed in the guilty plea, '' Dwyer said.
``There was no question that we would have been able to prove him
guilty if we had gone through a trial.''
</TEXT>
