<FIRST>r i PM-Venezuela     03-10 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reverses Itself On Restoring Civil Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has reversed a decision
to restore full constitutional rights, which were suspended March 2
amid nationwide rioting and looting over austerity measures.
   Government spokesmen had promised that full civil rights would be
restored on Thursday. But the decision was revised to include only
freedom of speech, Interior Minister Alejandro Izaguirre said on
television Thursday night.
   ``The government considers it prudent to maintain the suspension
of some of the measures,'' Izaguirre said without elaborating.
   Under the suspension, authorities can continue to arrest people
without charges, enter homes at will, prohibit demonstrations and
public meetings and restrict freedom of movement.
   The military will continue to patrol the streets, Izaguirre said.
   University students protesting the latest austerity measure,
higher bus fares, began the week of violence Feb. 27. Authorities
say 256 people were killed and thousands injured in the rioting.
   Some observers say authorities fear there could be renewed
rioting when university classes resume Monday.
</TEXT>
