<FIRST>r a PM-People-Peck     03-10 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Peck,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fellows Stars Praise American Film Institute Award Recipient Gregory
Peck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gregory Peck, who joked that he's
``entirely too young'' for the honor, was saluted by fellow Oscar
winner Jane Fonda and others as he received the American Film
Institute's Lifetime Achievement Award.
   Peck, 72, was honored at a tribute Thursday attended by scores of
Hollywood stars. The program will be telecast on NBC on March 21.
   ``You can never really go as far or go as deep as you would like
to,'' Peck told the audience. ``So there's always something else to
try for _ there's always a new challenge.''
   Peck's latest movie isn't even out yet _ ``Old Gringo,''
co-starring Miss Fonda and Jimmy Smits of ``LA Law.''
   ``I may not be his first leading lady or his last, but I
certainly got him at his ripest,'' Miss Fonda said.
   Audrey Hepburn, who co-starred with Peck in ``Roman Holiday,''
said, ``I've waited 37 years to say with all my heart and all my
love, `Thank you, Gregory Peck.'''
   Miss Hepburn was host of the event, which attracted such stars as
Lauren Bacall, Virginia Mayo, Dorothy McGuire, Liza Minnelli,
Jennifer Jones, Charlton Heston, Dinah Shore and Frank Sinatra.
   Mary Badham, who played Peck's daughter in the 1962 film ``To
Kill a Mockingbird,'' recalled that he immediately befriended her
when she arrived in Hollywood. She called him ``one of the kindest,
most gentle human beings in the world.''
   ``Mockingbird'' brought Peck an Academy Award as best actor for
his role as a Southern lawyer who defends a black man accused of
rape.
   ``It was his greatest role because he was so much like Atticus
Finch,'' Miss Badham said.
   Miss Bacall, who starred with Peck in the 1957 movie ``Designing
Woman,'' said she first met him when he was 17 years old.
   ``I thought he was the most gorgeous creature I had ever seen in
my life,'' she said. ``But it was 15 years before I made a picture
with him.''
   Angie Dickinson said she ran into one major problem when she was
asked to co-star in the 1963 film ``Captain Newman, M.D.''
   ``Universal Pictures told me I had to agree to a long-term
contract,'' she said. ``But they told me my co-star would be Gregory
Peck. I said, `What the hell? What's seven years?'''
   About 1,000 people attended the black-tie tribute at the Beverly
Hilton Hotel. Past recipients of the award include Orson Welles,
Bette Davis, James Cagney, Henry Fonda, Alfred Hitchcock, Jack
Lemmon and Barbara Stanwyck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
