<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0532 03-10 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0532,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Army Changing Strategy in Refugee Camps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with troop movements today. Pickup
4th graf pvs, ``The total...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army withdrew troops today from crowded
areas of two of the largest refugee camps in the occupied Gaza Strip
in a plan that will put more paramilitary police and mobile units in
the volatile camps.
   Troops today began moving out of some posts in the Jabaliya camp,
which has 52,000 residents, and on Thursday began leaving the Shati
camp, where 42,000 Palestinians live, Palestinian witnesses and
Israel radio said.
   Israel radio said the soldiers would be replaced by mobile units,
deployed in less crowded areas, which could move quickly in case of
violence.
   Army officials said without eleaborating that the redeployment
was aimed at reducing casualties in the 15-month Palestinian
uprising.
   The total number of soldiers in the occupied Gaza Strip will not
be cut, but many combat soldiers will be replaced by border police
trained in riot control, an army spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   The military moves came as Foreign Minister Moshe Arens left for
the United States on a 10-day visit. He is to meet with President
Bush and Secretary of State James Baker.
   Arens is expected to seek U.S. support for peace efforts that
focus on an interim solution for the occupied territories. U.S.
officials are expected to urge Israel to reduce the violence used in
suppressing the 15-month Palestinian uprising.
   At least 393 Arabs and 17 Israelis have died since the
Palestinian rebellion against Israeli occupation began in December
1987. The Israelis seized the lands from Arab neighbors in the 1967
Middle East War.
   The lastest death came Thursday when a 16-year-old Palestinian
was shot to death and 10 Arabs were wounded in clashes with Israeli
troops.
   Military officials believe removing permanently stationed units
from the camps will lower tension.
   ``The policy is now to reduce the hold, to reduce the friction
between Israeli forces and the local population,'' Southern
Commander Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai was quoted as saying in
independent Haaretz newspaper.
   He added, however, that the new mobile army units will be ready
to move ``to every place and at every moment to disperse
disturbances.''
   The army plan also calls for border police to relieve infantry
units in densely populated Gaza City and the refugee camps of
Nusserat and Bureij.
   Army spokesman Maj. Moshe Fogel said the deployment of
highly-trained border police will reduce the high number of
casualties in demonstrations.
   Elsewhere in Gaza today, the army destroyed rooms in the homes of
three Palestinians from the Khan Yunis refugee camp who were
suspected of throwing firebombs at Arab collaborators, an army
spokesman said.
   Palestinians shuttered their stores and transportation halted
around the strip on the second day of commercial strikes.
   A Palestinian human rights activist was freed from military
detention in Israel one day before Amnesty International USA named
him a ``prisoner of conscience.''
   Zahi Jaradat of Saaer, a village in the West Bank, was released
Wednesday after a year in administrative detention, said an official
at Al Haq-Law in the Service of Man, a human rights group.
</TEXT>
