<FIRST>u w PM-HijackingTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0461 03-10 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younis Trial Goes to Jury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs with judge's instructions, picking up at 9th graf
pvs, Carter, in; deletes last two grafs to conform and trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in Fawaz Younis' hijacking trial
today gave the jury stern instructions that seemed to undercut the
defendant's argument that he was justified in taking over an
airliner in Beirut in 1985 because he was under orders from a
Lebanese militia.
   ``Orders to hijack a plane ... are illegal orders,'' U.S.
District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. told the jury of seven women
and five men. ``Obedience to illegal orders is no defense.''
   The judge said Younis should be acquitted only if he did not know
that hijacking was illegal.
   Younis has testified that he knew that hijacking was illegal in
peacetime, and that the Amal militia to which he belonged was not at
war with Royal Jordanian Airlines, the government of Jordan, the two
Americans aboard the aircraft or any of the other 70 passengers and
crew members.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent in the case, which is a test of
a 1984 statute asserting ``long-arm'' U.S. jurisdiction in cases
involving American hostages taken overseas.
   Federal prosecutors sought to convince jurors that Younis knew he
was committing an illegal act against innocent civilians by seizing
control of Royal Jordanian Flight 402 on June 11, 1985.
   In his closing argument Thursday, defense attorney Francis D.
Carter urged the jurors to put aside their preconceptions of
hijacking as they decide the fate of Younis, a member of Lebanon's
Amal militia, a Shiite Moslem group.
   ``It's not the bogyman that you thought _ the word hijacking,''
Carter said.
   If convicted of the six counts against him, Younis could face
life in prison plus more than $410,000 in fines, which he does not
have money to pay. He has been held in isolation since his arrest
September 1987 and is represented by court-appointed counsel.
   Carter, in his final presentation, recounted the civil war that
has engulfed Lebanon since 1975 and tried to convince the jury that
Younis felt compelled to obey the orders from Amal, virtually the
only authority in West Beirut where the lived.
   ``The difficulty that you have is to take American law ... and
put that on top of the facts in Lebanon,'' Carter said. ``You have
to understand what this man had been through,'' Carter said.
   Federal prosecutors J. Ramsey Johnson and Karen Morrissette, in
their closing arguments, reminded they jury of testimony by Younis
that Amal was not at war with the American, Jordanian and Lebanese
passengers aboard the aircraft, nor against the government of
Jordan, which owns the airline.
   Hijacking, said Morrissette, ``is a violation of international
law.''
   ``The defendant cannot hijack an airplane, then come into a
courtroom in this country and say, `Well, someone told me to do it,'
and it's all right,'' she said.
   The prosecution also reminded the jury of testimony from five
eyewitnesses who identified Younis in the court room and recounted
how the hijackers stormed aboard the plane armed with AK-47 assault
rifles and hand grenades and tortured nine Jordanian sky marshals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
