<FIRST>r i PM-Antigua-Election     03-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antigua-Election,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Returned To Power in Antigua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Vere Bird won a fourth
straight term in office, but the opposition broke the governing
party's virtual monopoly of the 17-seat Parliament by winning two
seats, officials said today.
   Bird's Antigua Labor Party captured 15 seats in Thursday's vote,
losing one seat from Antigua to the opposition United National
Democratic Party.
   The seat allotted to the sister island of Barbuda, previously
held by Eric Burton, an independent allied with the governing party,
was won by the opposition Barbuda People's Movement.
   Members of the governing party drove around this tiny eastern
Caribbean country this morning with loudspeakers thanking their
supporters for returning them to office.
   ``The people of Antigua and Barbuda today celebrated in the glory
of our democratic process and must be congratulated for their
efforts,'' said Lester Bird, son of the prime minister and chairman
of the Labor Party.
   Bird, 78, first came to power in 1976. He owes his popularity
largely to the country's booming tourism industry, low unemployment
and one of the most prosperous economies in the region.
   Thursday's vote was the second since Antigua became independent
from Britain in 1981. The country had been semi-independent since
1967.
   The Antigua Election Office released the results early today. It
did not disclose the number of votes cast or the turnout. There were
36,504 eligible voters, from a total population of 100,000.
   Opposition parties had accused the government of corruption and
blamed it for running up a $250 million foreign debt.
   Bird said the debt was necessary to improve roads and ports to
stimulate tourism, which earned the island $189 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
