<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Waste     03-10 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Waste,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Propose Legislation to Limit Exports of Hazardous Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today announced he will propose
legislation to halt exports of hazardous waste unless there is an
agreement that the receiving country will handle the material in an
approved, safe manner.
   The president's proposal would involve waste that U.S. industry
ships for disposal in other countries. Concerns have been raised by
environmentalists that some countries, particularly in the
developing world, do not regulate disposal and handling of such
wastes in an environmentally safe manner.
   Bush, in remarks at the swearing-in cermony for Health and Human
Services Secretary Louis Sullivan, said he would send legislation to
Congress to empower the United States to block exports by U.S.
companies unless safety can be ensured through a bilateral pact.
   The legislation ``will give the U.S. government the authority to
ban all exports of hazardous waste except where we have an agreement
with the receivng country providing for the safe handling and
management of those wastes,'' he said.
   ``We're determined to work with other concerned governments to
exercise wide stewardship over our environment, particularly where
matters of health are concerned,'' Bush said.
   The legislation Bush proposes would affect any U.S. companies
that export hazardous waste rather than dispose of it in the
approved domestic sites, said Linda Fisher, assistant Environemental
Protection Agency director for policy.
   She said most U.S. exports go to Canda and Mexico, where other
companies that deal in waste receive it. In Mexico, some handlers
use the waste in recycling efforts, she said.
   Most of the countries that have caused concern are third world
nations, she said.
   ``Under current law, the United States has to notify another
country that hazardous waste is being shipped to them. We don't have
any mechanism to make sure it is being handled properly in other
country,'' she said.
   Bush's proposed bill would ensure that companies only ship to
countries that have a bilateral agreement with the United States to
make sure it is handled in a manner that does not endanger health
and the environment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Sullivan-SwearingIn     03-10 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan-Swearing In,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Secretary Promises Department With `Gentle Touch'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan said today that under his
tenure, the Department of Health and Human Services will have a
``human face ... a gentle touch.''
   At his formal swearing-in ceremony attended by President Bush,
the new HHS secretary pledged to find better ways to serve the
nation's poor, continue research towards a cure for AIDS, help rid
the nation of drug abuse, develop preventive health strategies and
maintain the Social Security and Medicare programs.
   ``Health and Human Services is the hub of a vast wheel whose
spokes radiate out to touch all Americans,'' Sullivan said. ``During
my tenure, the offices of the department will have a human face, the
regulations promulgated will carry a gentle touch.''
   Sullivan is a personal friend of Bush and his wife, Barbara, who
also attended the ceremony. Mrs. Bush is on the board of trustees of
the Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta, which Sullivan founded
and served as president. While at HHS, Sullivan, a blood specialist,
is on an unpaid leave from the school as a professor of medicine.
   Bush said Sullivan has his ``complete confidence and my full
support'' at the helm of the department that spends the largest
portion of the federal budget and ``affects the lives of every
American.''
   Sullivan was sworn in right after he was confirmed by the Senate
last week. Today, he took the oath again in a formal ceremony before
several hundred supporters, department employees, members of
Congress and administration officials.
   Sullivan was joined on the podium by his wife, Ginger, and two
sons and daughter. His son, Halsted, a senior at the University of
Virginia, sang ``The Star Spangled Banner.''
</TEXT>
