<FIRST>r a AM-OwlProwl     03-10 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Prowl,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's NYC's Newest Who-o-o-o-o's Who: Barn Owls to Form Park Rat Patrol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They descend at night, death on the wing for the
skittering rats who populate city parks.
   Who?
   Barn owls, that's who _ the city's latest weapon in its endless
battle against the unwanted denizens of the parks.
   The Parks and Recreation Department said Thursday it would start
putting ``owl boxes'' in four parks to encourage more rat-devouring
birds to take up residence.
   It's called ``Operation Owl Prowl,'' and it's considered a
potential alternative to rat poison, which is becoming less toxic to
new generations of rodents and often kills animals other than their
intended targets.
   ``We're getting some recruits in the war against rats,'' said
Parks Commissioner Henry Stern, who calls the park rodents ``very
visible and increasingly bold.''
   Officials hope the plywood honeymoon cottages will encourage the
hundreds of owls that already live in the city to reproduce faster.
   An owl box ``imitates the natural habitat,'' said Marc Matsil,
director of the department's Natural Resources Group. ``They
actually prefer boxes to trees, because they're larger, more
symmetrical, better protected.''
   Similar programs have worked in Mount Rainier National Park in
Washington and Mesa Verde National Park in Colorado, Matsil said.
   Actually, barn owls don't give a hoot _ they make a loud hiss,
and sometimes a clicking sound. When frightened, the snap their
bills. They're medium-size, as owls go, with a white, heart-shaped
face ringed with tan and a tan breast.
   A barn owl can kill three rats in a night's work, Matsil said.
And not just for food _ they'll do it for fun, those feathery
fiends. If a pair of owls is raising owlets, usually four to six per
brood, they'll kill even more.
   ``The nightly labor of these owls will more than justify the
modest expense of the housing we are providing,'' Stern said.
   The program will start in the coming weeks with 25 owl boxes
scattered through four parks, including Central Park. They cost $3
to $7 apiece.
   In a couple of years, the park folks will know if it's working.
In the meantime, the city will keep using pesticides, Stern said,
while trying to keep the poison away from owl habitats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
