<FIRST>r a PM-GovernorSamaritan     03-10 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governor Samaritan,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Stops to Help Man Wedged on Bench</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drunken man wedged between a bench and
a building was saved by Gov. Edward D. DiPrite, who stopped his
police-chauffeured car and waited nearly 30 minutes while a rescue
squad freed the man.
   DiPrete was driving through a neighborhood northwest of the
Statehouse on Thursday when he noticed the man in trouble and
sprawled on the bench.
   The unidentified man's legs were atop the bench but his body was
wedged between the bench and the building. His head was touching the
ground.
   ``Are you OK?'' DiPrete asked the groggy man, but got no
intelligible response, The Providence Journal-Bulletin reported
today.
   While DiPrete's bodyguard put in a radio call for help, two women
told the governor the man had been there for an hour.
   ``It's unbelieveable, he's been here for an hour and nobody's
done anything,'' said DiPrete, who had been on his way to a
television appearance after speaking to a Providence College
journalism class.
   The man was taken to Rhode Island Hospital, where a spokesman
said he was unhurt but intoxicated and was held for observation.
</TEXT>
