<FIRST>u w AM-GettingStarted Bjt   03-10 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Getting Started, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slowly, the Wheels of Foreign Policy Are Turning</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quick trip Secretary of State James A.
Baker III took to Vienna this week could mark a turning point in the
development of the Bush administration's foreign policy.
   Baker made tentative arrangements to visit Moscow in May where he
will discuss a summit meeting for President Bush with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   By the time Baker gets his first look at the Soviet Union, a
slow-moving review of U.S. arms control policy will be completed, as
well as a review of the way the United States deploys its strategic
nuclear forces.
   That would free Baker to set a date for the resumption of
negotiations with the Soviets in Geneva to sharply reduce U.S. and
Soviet long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear submarines.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze wanted Baker to
agree to resume in April or May. But Baker demurred. Bush and Baker
want to finish the U.S. internal reviews first.
   When the talks were suspended in December the two sides agreed to
pick up again in mid-February. But Bush ordered a delay to review
the bidding.
   The treaty the two sides were working on is not ready, of course.
Verifying compliance _ which is a diplomatic way of saying making
sure the other side can't cheat _ is unresolved. There are other
problems, as well.
   Still, the negotiators had come a long way since President Reagan
put aside his visceral distrust of Moscow and approved the search
for ways to lower tensions by destroying some of the world's most
powerful weapons.
   The review ordered by Bush implies some backtracking on the U.S.
side.
   But Baker told reporters as he flew home on Monday that the
administration's intention was not to start over, but to build on
the existing foundation.
   He wants to make sure the treaty that finally emerges in Geneva
can be ratified by the Senate. The 1979 Strategic Arms Limitation
Treaty was yanked by President Carter before a ratification vote
because it faced defeat. And treaties in 1972 and 1974 to limit
underground nuclear tests were not submitted by President Ford
because he feared defeat at the hands of conservative Republicans.
   All three treaties are being observed, more or less. But Bush and
Baker want formal approval of any accord with the Soviets to reduce
long-range nuclear weapons.
   Baker seemed to get along well enough with Shevardnadze, who met
so frequently _ more than 30 times _ with Baker's predecessor,
George P. Shultz, that U.S.-Soviet relations benefited from their
ease with each other.
   At the same time, Baker did not spare the criticism he felt the
Soviets had earned by their diplomatic overture to Iran.
   He called it ``posturing,'' and suggested the Soviets were
interfering with a U.S. effort to isolate Iran over the death
threats leveled by the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini against Salman
Rushdie for writing a book Khomeini considers heretical to Islam.
   The Soviets have their own interests, of course, in trying to
mend fences with a fundamentalist government that used to denounce
Moscow and Washington with equal venom as ``the great Satans.''
   One is to try to influence the Afghan rebel leaders who are in
Iran to support the establishment of a new government in Kabul that
is not hostile to Moscow.
   After all, the United States under Reagan tried its own hand at
Iranian diplomacy by surreptitiously shipping loads of missiles to
Tehran to try to secure the freedom of American hostages in Lebanon
and encourage moderation in Iran.
   The result was the Iran-Contra scandal.
   Baker also expressed displeasure over the help the Soviets have
been giving Nicaragua as the Central American country builds up its
armed forces. He complained that the arsenal is a threat to
Nicaragua's neighbors.
   Shevardnadze's response was to call for a halt in U.S. support to
Honduras, El Salvador and other friendly governments, which Baker
turned down.
   On the Middle East, the disagreement was more nuanced.
   Baker said he welcomed Soviet help in trying to resolve the
Arab-Israeli conflict. Given the fact the United States tried for
years to keep Moscow out of the picture, Baker's statement was not a
platitude.
   But he didn't bite at the continuing Soviet call for an
international peace conference. Baker wants more time before he
begins an inevitable U.S. campaign to try to push Israel to the
bargaining table under terms Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir considers
dangerous.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid heads the State Department staff of
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
