<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--MissileSites     03-10 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Missile Sites,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Teams Inspect Belgian Missile Sites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors Friday checked an air
base where U.S. cruise missiles were based until their elimination
under a 1987 treaty, and they also examined a missile repair
facility, the Foreign Ministry said.
   The two inspection teams will return to the Soviet Union on
Saturday, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Alexis Brouhns.
   The inspectors visited Florennes air base, 65 miles south of
Brussels, where 16 ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares
were kept. Inspectors also went to Gosselies, near Florennes, to
check the European repair facility, where unarmed missiles are still
repaired, Brouhns said.
   The missiles arrived in Belgium in 1985 and were removed in
December 1988, one year after former President Reagan and Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty.
   It was the Soviet inspectors' second visit to Belgium. Their
first visit was in August.
   The INF treaty provides for the elimination of all Soviet and
U.S. land-based missiles with ranges of about 300 to 3,400 miles by
June 1991.
</TEXT>
