<HEAD>Site of Exhibition Documenting Nazi Terror Hit by Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unknown attackers set a fire early Friday at the
site of an exhibition documenting Nazi terror on display inside the
former Gestapo headquarters in Berlin, police said.
   Several windows were broken and parts of the nearby structure
were charred, West Berlin police said. They called it a politically
motivated incident.
   A container used to transport the flammable liquid for the attack
was found near the site, police said. A watchman doused the flames
before major damage occurred.
   The foundation of the former Nazi secret police headquarters
houses an exhibition called ``Topography of Terror,'' which
documents the torture and other brutal methods the Gestapo used
against those suspected of opposing Adolf Hitler's Third Reich.
