<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Islam     03-10 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Islam,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Flare Over Islamic Headgear Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday detained dozens of Moslem
fundamentalists who protested a ruling that prevents women at
universities from covering their heads in accordance with Islamic
tradition.
   About 500 protesters chanting Islamic slogans faced a police
barricade when they began marching after the Friday sermon from the
Hacibayram Mosque in the center of Ankara. A police official said 15
people were detained.
   Two female students were detained in a separate incident at the
downtown post office where a demonstration began after hundreds of
Moslem fundamentalists tried to send telegrams to the president,
premier and members of Parliament.
   At least 15 Moslem fundemantalists were detained in Istanbul at a
similar demonstration in the neighborhood of the Istanbul
University, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
   Anatolia said police detained 10 protesters in the western
province of Bursa and 20 others in the southern province of Adana in
demonstrations after the Friday sermons.
   Protesters in each incident also denounced Salman Rushdie, author
of ``The Satanic Verses.'' They chanted slogans such as ``Down with
Europe, America and Israel!'' and ``Death to Salman Rushdie!''
according to news agency reports.
   The protests grew after a constitutional court on Tuesday called
unconstitutional a parliamentary decision in December that permitted
Islamic-style head covering at the universities.
   Turbaned women say their Islamic beliefs require them to cover
their heads while in mixed company. Their defenders contend the ban
is a restriction of democratic freedoms.
   Defenders of secularism say the head-covering is an ideological
symbol of Moslem fundamentalism and thus a threat to Turkey's
modernization efforts in the past 60 years.
   Kemal Ataturk, founder of modern Turkey, reduced the role of
religion in this overwhelmingly Moslem nation. He abolished the
caliphate, adopted laws from Western Europe, replaced Arabic with
Latin script and extended full civil and political rights to women.
   Premier Turgut Ozal, a devout Moslem who has been sympathetic to
protesting students, on Thursday criticized the court's decision.
   ``We want to be a Western country,'' Ozal said. ``We want to be a
community in which freedoms are broad and people don't become angry
because of religious beliefs ... three or four girls wearing turbans
are neither going to drag Turkey backwards or help it to advance.''
</TEXT>
