<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Soviet     03-10 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Soviet,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Hails Church Nominations in Lithuania</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vatican-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican on Friday made a major
reorganization of the church in Lithuania and hailed it as a
breakthrough for Roman Catholics in the Soviet republic.
   The steps included the naming of three heads of dioceses by Pope
John Paul II, the first residential bishops appointed in Lithuania
since the end of World War II.
   The changes are believed to have needed at least the tacit
approval of the Soviet government.
   Lithuania, an independent country before the war, was occupied by
the Soviet Union in 1940. About 80 percent of its 3.5 million people
are said to be Roman Catholics.
   ``The Holy See is pleased that we could arrive at a
reorganization that was desired by Catholics in Lithuania,'' said
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   Under the reorganization, Cardinal Vincentas Sladkevicius was
named archbishop of Kaunas and Monsignor Julijonas Steponavicius was
appointed archbishop of Vilnius.
   Sladkevicius had been serving in Kaisiadorys and Steponavicius in
Vilnius but each with the title apostolic administrator. This meant
they were not fully empowered as residential bishops.
   While in practice the functions are similar, the naming of a full
residential bishop has considerable importance for the church as a
sign of a more normal climate.
   Oly in December the Soviet government allowed Steponavicius to
resume his official duties after 28 years in internal exile. He was
exiled to northern Lithuania in 1961 for refusing to collaborate
with Soviet authorities.
   In a third appointment Friday, the pope named Monsignor Antanas
Vaicius bishop of Telsiai, where he had been serving as apostolic
administrator.
   John Paul also named apostolic administrators for Kaisiadorys and
Vilkaviskis.
   In response to a question, Navarro said he didn't believe the
steps meant the way was open for a possible papal visit to
Lithuania. John Paul has said that he has been refused permission to
visit Lithuania on at least two occasions.
   ``I wouldn't make any connection'' to such a visit, Navarro said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is scheduled to visit Italy
in November and was recently reported to have expressed interest in
meeting with the pope. The Vatican says John Paul would welcome such
a meeting, which would be the first between a Roman Catholic pontiff
and a Soviet leader.
</TEXT>
