<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Gulf-Storm     03-10 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gulf-Storm,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Sandstgorm Hits Persian Guff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe sandstorm struck the northern and
central Persian Gulf on Friday, reducing visibility to a few hundred
yards and disrupting airline flights in Kuwait and Bahrain.
   Civil Aviation officials said two flights from Sri Lanka and
Bangladsh, bound for Kuwait, were diverted to Manama because of the
storm. When the storm hit Bahrain, at least two departing flights
were delayed for an hour or more.
   Visibility on Bahrain's coastal highway was reduced to less than
600 yards as the huge cloud of yellow dust darkened skies and
covered everything with a coat of silt.
   Temperatures fell to about 46 degrees. Seas were running 3 to 7
feet in deeper waters.
   ``Thick dust was generated by strong winds flowing around a low
pressure system which moved eastward across the region in the
northern gulf,'' said an official from the Bahrain Meteorological
Section.
   Sandstorms are common in the gulf but residents said Friday's was
the most severe in years.
   Small amounts of rain are normal in the arid region this time of
year, but this season has been unusually dry.
</TEXT>
