<HEAD>Bush Searching for Tower Replacement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs with Fitzwater comment; picks up at pvs 5th graf,
Speculation has</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush cast a wide net today for a
replacement for rejected nominee John Tower as defense secretary and
was expected to move swiftly on his choice, his spokesman said today.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush was
considering multiple candidates for the post and that ``phone calls
are being made.''
   Fitzwater would not characterize the list and said that while the
president had ``no timetable'' on his announcement, one was expected
relatively soon. He even held out the possibility that a decision
could come later today.
   Bush ``is being encouraged by everyone to do it in spokesman said.
   Presidential aides began looking at various candidates
immediately after ta hurry,'' the
he Senate voted 53-47 Thursday to reject Tower,
Bush's first choice, for the post.
   The president was meeting with advisers on the issue throughout
the day, and both he and top aides were making phone calls to
prospective candidates, Fitzwater said.
   ``A lot of names have been suggested,'' he said, adding that some
of them were among those passed over the first time around when
Tower was selected.
   ``It's not starting from scratch. Basically, there's a large
r Tower and suggested that
some senators made up their minds ``based on groundless rumor.''
   ``Now, however, we owe it to the American people to come together
and move forward,'' he said.
   A new nomination may could come before week's end, a senior
administration official said Thursday. The official, speaking on the
condition of anonymity, said a long informal list of candidates had
been compiled even before the Tower vote.
   The official noted that some of the names had been compiled late
last year, before Tower was finally selected in December. ``We're
not starting from scratch,'' the official said.
   Fitzwater, however, insisted that Bush himself had not given
serious thought to a replacement as long as Tower's nomination was
before the Senate.
   ``He's had discussions with the chief of staff (John Sununu) and
Brent Scowcroft in terms of what kind of candidates he's interested
in. ... But I would hasten to point out there's some difference
between that and actually having a list of candidates,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Scowcroft himself has been the subject of much speculation for
the defense post. Some members of Congress have even suggested a job
switch with Tower _ since the national security adviser's post does
not require Senate confirmation.
   Scowcroft said Thursday he was not in line for the job, but that
hasn't stopped the talk.
   Among the other contenders, Edwards is popular among lawmakers of
both parties. He is former senior Republican on the House defense
appropriations subcommittee and his expertise on military matters is
widely respected.
   Lewis, chairman of Union Pacific Corp., was transportation
secretary under former President Ford and co-chairman of the
recently disbanded National Economic Commission. He would bring to
the job considerable management experience.
   Rumsfeld served as defense secretary under Ford.
   Of the three senators being mentioned, Warner, a former Navy
secretary, might be the most easily confirmed _ but his nomination
would rob Republicans of one Senate seat, since governors fill
Senate vacancies and Virginia's governor is a Democrat.
   That would not be a problem for Rudman from New Hampshire or
Cohen from Maine, since both states have GOP governors.
   Administration sources have said that Bush, not wanting to
subject another candidate to the grueling experience Tower went
through, seemed likely to pick someone either currently or recently
in government who had been through the confirmation process, or a
member of Congress.
   However, the names of some business executives have also cropped
up _ including Donald Rice of the Rand Corp. and Frank Borman,
former astronaut-turned-executive.
   And, two who served in the administration of former President
Jimmy Carter are also being mentioned as dark-horse possibilities:
Zbigniew Brzezinski, who was Carter's national security adviser; and
James Schlesinger, who was his energy secretary _ after serving as
Ford's first defense secretary.
   Bush planned to spend the weekend in Camp David and invited
members of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and their wives. But Fitzwater
said the get-together was mainly social and had nothing to do with
finding a replacement for Tower.
