<HEAD>Soviet Union, Poland, Bulgaria to Open Trade Offices in Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, Poland and Bulgaria
will open trade offices in South Korea next month, government
sources said.
   It will bring to five the number of communist nations to exchange
trade offices with South Korea, with which they have no diplomatic
relations. Hungary and Yugoslavia opened trade offices in Seoul last
year.
   One government source, speaking on conidtion of anonymity, said
Thursday the Soviet Union's trade office will open in Seoul on April
3. The trade offices of Poland and Bulgaria will be set up several
days later, he said.
   South Korea will reciprocate by opening trade offices in Moscow,
Warsaw and Sofia by the end of April, he added.
   Anti-communist South Korea has improved ties recently with the
Soviet Union and other communist nations. Hungary became the first
communist nation to set up full diplomatic ties with South Korea
last month.
</TEXT>
