<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ukraine,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Found Guilty of Organizing Memorial Service, Beatings Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights activist said a court in the Ukraine
on Friday found a religious activist guilty of organizing an
unauthorized meeting, and that people who surrounded the court were
attacked by police.
   Anatoly Dotsenko, a spokesman for the recently formed Ukrainian
Helsinki Society, said Irina Kalenets was found guilty of helping
organize a gathering of thousands of people Feb. 26 dedicated to
Ukrainian national poet Taras Shevchenko.
   He said the court in the city of Lvov found that the gathering
was not a religious service but an unauthorized public gathering.
Ms. Kalenets is a leader of a women's religious group and a human
rights activist, he said.
   Dotsenko said he received his information by telephone from one
of the society's founders, Vyacheslav Chernovil in Lvov.
   A second person, Mikhailo Gorin, also was taken to court on
similar charges but the results of that case were not known,
Dotsenko said.
   He said police surrounded the court during Gorin's trial and
began to beat and arrest people who gathered outside the police
barricade.
   There was no independent confirmation of his report.
   Lvov, a center of Ukrainian nationalism, is located in the far
western part of the republic. The western part of the Ukraine only
became part of the Soviet Union after World War II, and pockets of
resistance to Soviet rule remained until the early 1950s.
