<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     03-10 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Vietnamese to Go Home Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hong Kong official said Friday he expected a
second batch of Vietnamese boat people to return to their communist
homeland next month.
   Secretary of Security Geoffrey Barnes, speaking upon his return
from an international meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, on the
region's flood of asylum-seekers, said Vietnam has agreed to accept
another 150 Vietnamese who have volunteered to go home after fleeing
to Hong Kong by boat.
   Hong Kong adopted a tough policy to treat all Vietnamese boat
people arriving after June 15 as illegal immigrants subject to
repatriation unless they can prove they fled persecution.
   About 11,000 Vietnamese have sailed into this British colony
since then, and some have decided they would prefer to return to
Vietnam than face an uncertain future in crowded Hong Kong camps.
   A group of 75 Vietnamese flew to Hanoi on March 2 in the first
large-scale repatriation of boat people.
   Barnes quoted Vu Khoan, the leader of the Vietnamese delegation
at the Malaysian conference, as saying he hoped to see another group
of Vietnamese return home soon.
   ``He (Vu) also said he would like to see a larger group going
back than last time,'' Barnes said.
   Barnes said he expected the next repatriation would take place in
April. ``In the meantime of course we'll try to encourage more to go
back voluntarily,'' he said.
</TEXT>
