<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Arens     03-10 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Arens,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Foreign Minister to Meet with Bush on Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens will meet
with President Bush on Monday to discuss the Middle East peace
efforts and other issues of interest to the region, the White House
announced Friday.
   Arens will also meet with Secretary of State James A. Baker III
and with members of Congress during his three-day trip to
Washington, said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater said Bush did not have any new Middle East peace
initiatives to suggest to Arens.
   He declined to be specific about what Bush might bring up. Topics
could include the recent State Department human rights report that
criticized Israel's armed forces for excessive violence in putting
down Palestinian uprisings in the occupied territories.
   Arens' visit comes as the Israeli army shifts some of its troops
out of Gaza Strip refugee camps to reduce tension and fatal clashes
in the teeming Palestinian communities.
   Arens, a member of the conservative Likud party, has more
hardline views on dealing with the Palestinians than more moderate
Israeli leaders have. He has criticized a move by the European
Community to organize an international peace conference for the
region.
   The Bush administration also is cool to the idea.
   Arens also has chided the United States, where he grew up, for
opening talks for the first time with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which he accuses of being involved in interntional
terrorism.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir also is expected to visit the
United States in April.
</TEXT>
