<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-10 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Warns Detainees Against Resuming Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday
threatened to crack down on anti-apartheid activists allegedly
trying to revive a mass hunger strike by detainees.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok cited six organziations that
he said were planning to restart a protest fast next week in Durban,
Port Elizabeth and other cities.
   ``Should unrest flare up again or should a single person die as a
result of the hunger strike, the organizations and persons fomenting
these campaigns will have to bear the responsibility for their
devilish deeds,'' Vlok said.
   The organizations named by Vlok included the recently formed
Hunger Striker's Support Committee and the Congress of South African
Trade Unions, the country's largest black labor federation.
   Detainees in Johannesburg began the hunger strike Jan. 23 to
demand that they be freed or put on trial. The strike spread to
other cities, but was suspended in most prisons after Vlok told
church leaders Feb. 16 that he would release a ``substantial
number'' of detainees.
   The government says it has freed 279 detainees since then, while
about 500 people remain held without charge. Anti-apartheid groups
say fewer people have been released and contend about 700 still are
in detention.
   On Friday, the Association of Democratic Journalists announced
the release of free-lance journalist Brian Sokutu, who had been held
for the entire 33 months of the emergency. Like many of those
released, Sokutu is under restriction orders. He is not allowed to
attend any meetings that criticize the government.
   Anti-apartheid leaders accuse Vlok of not keeping his promises,
saying he had given the impression he would release at least half of
those held without charge.
   ``Our hopes for a new attitude on the part of the police and the
government have not been realized,'' said Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu and Stephen Naidoo, the Roman Catholic archbishop of
Cape Town.
   ``The crisis precipitated by the government's
detention-without-trial laws is intensifying,'' their statement
added.
   As many as 500 detainees have participated in the hunger strike,
but only about 20 in the port city of Durban currently are fasting.
Neither the detainees nor any anti-apartheid organization have
publicly called for a new mass hunger strike, but they have warned
it could resume if the government does not release most of those in
detention.
   An estimated 30,000 people, almost all black, have been detained
without charge for varying lengths of time during the 33-month state
of emergency.
</TEXT>
