<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-10 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assistant manager of a grocery store
said he was skeptical when a well-dressed man said he was rushing to
catch a plane and needed a favor.
   ``I don't know. What's the favor?'' Don Baker said he asked the
man who appeared at Chicotsky Fine Foods on Thursday.
   ``Well, you'll like it,'' said the man before peeling off $1,000
in $100 bills and instructing Baker to call the Loaves and Fishes
Soup Kitchen, which had been vandalized earlier in the week.
   ``Tell them they have $1,000 to pick up some groceries,'' the man
said.
   The businessman, who said he was the president of a floor-care
equipment business, told Baker he had shopped at Chicotsky's and
gave him a business card. Baker declined to identify him because ``I
don't think he was doing this for any publicity purpose.''
   Helen Voldness, director of the Loaves and Fishes Metroplex Food
Bank that supplies the kitchen, said the donation will allow the
kitchen to restock after vandals broke in earlier in the week,
forcing it to close for the first time in its seven years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAYLAND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourth- and fifth-graders whose junk food
favorites have jumped in price by 100 percent say desperate times
call for desperate measures.
   Indignant at prices hiked from 25 cents to 50 cents for cafeteria
snacks such as ice cream or potato chips, the youngsters are staging
a boycott.
   ``If everyone stops buying for a week, it will take them a while
to recover,'' said Jacob Berlin, a fourth-grader at Claypit Hill
School.
   Students at the school in the Boston suburb began their protest
last month with a petition drive.
   That failed, and the 9- through 11-year-olds decided to get tough.
   ``It's not noticeable enough (a protest) to say, `Wow, prices are
going up,'' Jacobs said.
   Students feel some increase would be reasonable, but 100 percent
was too much, he said.
   The food service annual budget of $350,000 for four schools
relies on cafeteria revenues, and the price hike was necessary to
make up for losses suffered because of a shrinking number of
students in the upper grades to patronize the high school snack bar,
said Lillian Mills, who runs food services for the Wayland school
system.
   Early accounts show snack sales at Claypit Hill are down, Ms.
Mills said.
   While teachers have tried not to interfere, fourth-grade teacher
Rick Colpitts said he used the protest for classroom discussions on
economics and the uses of petitions and boycotts.
   ``As a teacher, I'm proud that they were able to take an issue
and mobilize around it,'' Colpitts said Thursday. ``I think it was
good that they were able to stand up and try to change things _
peacefully.''
</TEXT>
