<FIRST>u a AM-MissingClimbers     03-10 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Climbers,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observation Plane Reports Flash of Color Where Missing Climbers Might
Be</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALKEETNA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane-force winds that have hampered
the search for three missing Japanese climbers on Mount McKinley
abated somewhat Friday, and an Air Force pilot saw a flash of red or
orange as he flew near the continent's tallest peak.
   Maj. Neal Sharra radioed, however, that he saw no movement in the
area along the missing men's likely route, and officials cautioned
the color might be a box of emergency provisions left for climbers
in trouble.
   The three climbers, who were last seen Feb. 22 while attempting a
rare wintertime ascent of the 20,320-mountain, are equipped with
orange tents and were wearing identical red climbing suits.
   Rescuers were waiting Friday for the wind to die down, hoping
they could fly helicopters near the mountain for a more extensive
search. The Air Force observation plane that saw the color had been
sent up primarily to monitor visibility and turbulence.
   Bob Seibert, a mountaineering ranger with the National Park
Service, said the search, once winds allow it to begin, would first
concentrate on the place where the color was spotted.
   Rescuers were ready to board aircraft early Thursday, but they
remained in Talkeetna hour after hour as winds that at times topped
90 mph persisted around Mount McKinley, 65 miles to the northwest.
   By Friday morning, Seibert said, the weather ``looks different
than it has for the past week and a half. I feel better (about it)
than I did yesterday.''
   Chief Warrant Officer Myron Babcock, leader of the Army rescue
team, agreed that the winds were not as bad, ``but they're still
twice as high as we'd like them to be.''
   The climbers' rations probably ran out days ago, but the Park
Service has a cache of food, fuel and water at 17,200 feet along
with a semi-permanent ice cave, officials said.
   ``If they stayed put (at 17,200 camp), they'd be fine,'' said
Roger Robinson, a Park Service mountaineering ranger. ``The
resources there are phenomenal.''
   It was that brightly colored box of provisions that might have
caught the eye of the pilot, Seibert said.
   The Japanese last were seen by a three-man Austrian climbing
team. The Austrians were descending the mountain, and the Japanese
were climbing. There have been six successful winter ascents since
1967, with four climber deaths during that period, the Park Service
says.
   Although the Japanese are equipped with a radio, its use and
range is limited. ``They have a little FM radio,'' Robinson said.
``It's pretty restrictive as to who you can talk to.''
   Members of the Japanese party are leader Noboru Yamada, 39, Teruo
Saegusa, 31, and Kozo Komatsu, 34, all of Tokyo.
</TEXT>
