<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Japan-AircraftTechnology     03-10 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Aircraft Technology,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci Defends Fighter Jet Deal with Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Friday that the Pentagon had not sold out U.S. economic interests in
agreeing to transfer to Japan technology for building an advanced
version of the F-16 fighter.
   ``It is my judgment that the FSX represents a good deal for
Japan, a good deal for the United States and an excellent deal for
the U.S.-Japan security and industrial relationship,'' Carlucci told
a Senate Armed Services subcommittee.
   He asserted that ``in the end, much of the criticism of the FSX
deal reflects an irrational fear of Japan's technological prowess.''
   Under the deal, St. Louis-based General Dynamics would join
forces with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to co-develop and
co-produce a next-generation fighter, called the FSX, for deployment
by Japan in the late 1990s.
   Proponents argue that the agreement represents the best deal the
United States could negotiate in the face of Japanese opposition to
buying F-16s directly from the United States. They say the deal will
serve to promote beneficial technology transfer in both directions
while generating income and jobs for U.S. industry.
   Critics, however, contend that the arrangement amounts to a
giveaway of advanced technology that Japan may use to help propel
its civilian aircraft industry into head-to-head competition with
the United States in the world market. They say Tokyo should
purchase American-made planes to help offset the $50 billion U.S.
trade deficit with Japan.
   In the face of congressional criticism, the Bush administration
has been conducting an interagency review of the FSX deal prior to
sending the agreement to Capitol Hill.
   At the White House, officials said the National Security Council
expected to receive Friday the results of the review, handled mainly
by the Pentagon and the Commerce Department.
   ``We expect the review will be completed and we won't have a
presidential decision for some time,'' said White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater. He said President Bush would examine the issue
next week.
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., chairman of the defense industry and
technology subcommittee, told the hearing, ``I believe that the
process whereby this agreement was reached was flawed in that the
departments of State and Defense systematically excluded from the
negotiations the agencies which deal with our economic and trade
policies.''
   ``The fundamental decision at the start of these negotiations was
not to link our defense and trade relations. That decision was
unsustainable,'' he said.
   Bingaman is among 21 senators co-sponsoring a sense-of-the-Senate
resolution that expresses ``strong reservations'' about the FSX
deal. Also, a group of 24 House members has sent a letter to Bush
saying they intend to fight the agreement when it goes to Capitol
Hill.
   Carlucci told the panel that the FSX deal is not ``an agreement
which sells out U.S. economic interests for the sake of purely
military or strategic interests.''
   ``In fact ... our Defense and State negotiators were well aware
of the economic equities at stake and proceeded from the view that
economic security is a cornerstone of our future national
security,'' he testified.
   He added that officials conducting the interagency review also
``will not find that our negotiators `lost their shirts' or `gave
away the store' on technology transfer, as has been alleged by
some.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
