<DOCNO> AP890310-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DakotaMen     03-10 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dakota Men,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calendar Aimed At Helping Needy Farmers Is Going Under</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization that set out to help needy
farmers through sales of a calendar featuring young, bachelor
farmers is folding, a state official said.
   Food Inc.'s debts ``far outweigh the meager assets that they
have'' and it is unable to pay its bills, James Vukelic, North
Dakota's solicitor general, said Thursday.
   Food Inc., which stands for Farmers Of Ongoing Determination,
produced a calendar called ``Dakota Men,'' which pictured a young
man for each month. The 1988 calendar featured North Dakota farmers.
The '89 issue contains farmers from both Dakotas.
   The venture was launched in 1987 but ran into serious trouble
last year when an audit revealed that some of the $175,508 raised
from the sale of the first calendars in 1988 had been spent on
questionable expenses, including parties, and none went to charities.
   The state attorney general's office filed suit against the
organization charging it with mismanagement and misrepresentation. A
settlement was reached last December whereby Food Inc. could
continue operating under certain restrictions and close supervision
by the state.
   However, the matter severely damaged sales of the 1989 calendar.
Roger Jaeger, an Esmond farmer who is executive director of Food
Inc., said 1989 sales were not what the organization expected.
   Vukelic said the state was concerned now about the liquidation of
the organization.
   ``When we were informed by representatives of Food Inc. that they
intended to shut down their operation, we were primarily concerned
in seeing that the assets of the corporation were liquidated and we
want to oversee that process,'' he said.
   The state has not been provided with all the specifics on Food
Inc.'s assets, Vukelic said.
   Jaeger said he hoped to have more details about the
organization's shut down later this month.
</TEXT>
