<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Executions     03-10 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Executions,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Hangs 81 Convicted on Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Friday hanged 81 people, including
three Afghans and two women, who were convicted on drug smuggling
charges, state-run Tehran radio reported.
   The executions took place in Tehran and 26 other cities.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said those executed were
found guilty of possession and sale of more than 11 tons of heroin,
opium, hashish and other narcotics.
   In addition to the drug charges, some of the condemned also were
found guilty of other crimes, such as theft, illegal possesion of
arms, kidnapping, and committing ``indecent acts in contravention to
Islamic law,'' the radio said.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the two women were
hanged in the capital's Qasr prison.
   ``I hope narcotics will be weeded out in this country. I ask the
youth to take lesson from our fate,'' said Reza Shamlou, 24, before
his death, according to IRNA, also monitored in Cyprus.
   The Iranian daily newspaper Ettelaat expressed support for the
anti-drug campaign, but carried a commentary by Ayatollah Hussein
Ali Montazeri, Khomeini's designated successor, who said ``poverty,
the root of social corruption, should be given great consideration
if the problem is to be successfully solved.''
   Friday's executions bring to 356 the number of executions
reported by Iran since a new anti-drugs law went into effect Jan 21.
The previous high toll for one day was 70 executions on Feb. 14.
   The new law carries the death sentence for possession of even
small quantities of drugs, and gives addicts six months to kick the
habit or face jail terms.
   Earlier this week, the radio quoted an unidentified source at the
country's main law enforcement agency, the Komiteh, who said the
six-month grace period granted to addicts to kick the habit would
expire July 23, after which they will be subject to prosecution.
   The Komiteh official said the amount of drugs seized during the
current Iranian year, which ends March 21, totals more than 50 tons,
Tehran radio said.
</TEXT>
