<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Pentagon Bjt   03-10 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Pentagon, Bjt,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plunges into Search for Tower Replacement, Quayle Turns up Heat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush plunged anew into the search for
a defense secretary Friday, reviewing names and asking about
candidates less than 24 hours after the Senate killed his nomination
of John Tower.
   In sharp contrast to Bush's low-keyed reaction to his first
legislative defeat, Vice President Dan Quayle turned up the heat and
accused Senate Democrats of engaging in ``a McCarthyite mud-slinging
campaign'' against Tower and waging an ``assault on the powers of
the presidency.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged ``there
is some difference in tone'' between Bush and Quayle. Bush had said,
``We owe it to the American people to come together and move
forward.''
   White House officials said Bush would pick a replacement quickly.
He sought advice on the nomination in telephone calls and in
meetings with people he trusts, said Fitzwater.
   Many potential candidates were mentioned, including former Rep.
Jack Edwards, R-Ala., Sens. William Cohen, R-Maine and Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, former defense secretaries Donald Rumsfeld and James
Schlesinger, former CIA deputy director Bobby Inman, Paul O'Neill,
chairman and chief executive officer of Alcoa, and Norman Augustine,
chairman and chief executive officer of Martin Marietta Aerospace
Corp.
   Edwards' law office said he wasn't interested in the job, and
Augustine let it be known that neither was he.
   Cohen said the talk about him was just ``unfounded rumors.''
Brent Scowcroft, the president's national security adviser, said
Thursday he wouldn't get the job but his name was still being
mentioned.
   Cohen speculated that the next nominee would be ``someone who's
gone through a recent (FBI) check. (The nominee) must be
well-respected and able to work in a constructive way with
Congress.''
   Fitzwater, at a late-morning briefing, said, ``The president is
reviewing candidates both in terms of receiving names from any
number of people and sources in the government, in the White House
and outside the government as well.
   ``He has asked that several of them be checked out in one fashion
or another in terms of availability or interest as well as
background.''
   Fitzwater refused to say how far the field had been narrowed but
said, ``You may be assured the search is intense and is being
carried by a number of people as rapidly as possible.''
   The main reason the search was expected to go quickly was because
Bush went through the same drill before choosing Tower last December.
   ``It's not like we're starting from scratch,'' Fitzwater said.
``Basically there's a large group of people to consider off that bat
that they've gone through in quite detail before,'' he said. Other
names were being added, he said.
   Bush will meet over the weekend at Camp David with the Joint
Chiefs of Staff for previously scheduled talks on defense issues,
but Fitzwater said the president did not have to talk with them
before making a decision.
   Meanwhile, Quayle flew to Indianapolis and, in a prepared speech,
harshly criticized Senate Democrats and warned there will be a
lingering bitterness over the Tower fight.
   ``Never in all my years in the Senate have I encountered anything
like the feeling of outrage that exists today among my former
Republican Senate colleagues,'' he said. ``Never have I encountered
such anger and bitterness in the Senate chamber.''
   Quayle said ``the harmful consequences of the Tower affair will
not soon pass. I'm afraid that the misguided Democratic assault on
the powers of the presidency will continue.''
   He said the Democrats, losers in five of the last six
presidential elections, have ``set out to undermine the presidency
by encroaching on its powers.''
   At the White House, Fitzwater said Quayle had given a copy of the
speech to the White House on Thursday but that he did not have to
have his remarks cleared in advance.
   Fitzwater said he did not think Bush had read the speech.
However, Bush and Quayle talked over lunch on Thursday. ``The
president is aware of the vice president's views.''
   Commenting on different tactics adopted by Bush and Quayle,
Fitzwater said, ``I think the Senate understands these positions.
... I think everyone understands where they're both coming from.''
   In another development, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the leader of the
fight to defeat Tower's nomination, struck a conciliatory note,
saying ``I hope the passions that are now bubbling in Washington
will soon cool.''
   Nunn, chairman of the Armed Services Committee, said, ``We cannot
prevail as a great power if either our allies or our adversaries
look to Washington and see endless division and rancor instead of a
principled, unified American policy.''
</TEXT>
