<HEAD>Plane With 69 Aboard Crashes In Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 30 sent to hospitals, fire aboard
the plane, report from the scene. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DRYDEN, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Ontario jet with 69 people aboard
crashed Friday shortly after taking off from Dryden airport, an
airline official said.
   Paul McKnight, vice president of the Toronto-based regional
carrier, said some people survived the crash, but he couldn't say
how many. CKPR radio, which had reporters at the scene, said about
30 people were taken to a hospital.
   McKnight said there was a fire aboard the plane, but it was not
immediately clear whether the fire occurred before or after the
crash.
   Sixty-five passengers and four crew members were aboard the
Fokker F-28 jet when it crashed into trees after taking off on a
noon flight to Winnipeg, Manitoba, he said. The radio reporters said
rescue workers bulldozed a passage through the woods to reach the
crash site.
   Dryden, a town of 6,500 people on the Trans-Canada Highway, is
about 200 miles northwest of Duluth, Minn.
