<FIRST>r i AM-Royals     03-10 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Royals,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queen Urges Students to Help Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Queen Elizabeth II told
thousands of high school students an education is not enough unless
it's ``reinforced by the desire to help others.''
   The Queen, in Barbados as the guest of honor in celebrations
marking the 350th anniversary of the island nation's Parliament,
laid the stone for a new building at Queen's College.
   ``In a world which is becoming all the time more and more
interdependent, the knowledge and skills which you acquire here will
give the best return only if they are reinforced by a desire to
serve others,'' the queen told high school students who came from 35
schools.
   She pointed to the Commonwealth, of which Barbados is a member,
as a good example of ``working together for the common good.''
   ``It's members belong to different cultures, climates beliefs and
ideals but we have seized unto the essential idea of working
together for the common good,'' she said. ``We have the unique
advantage of feeling at home where we may go within the
Commonwealth.''
   The queen praised the reputation of the school which she said had
been built on longstanding traditions of excellence and achievement.
   Her husband, Prince Philip, presented 34 students with awards
given to youths who have made good deeds and ``constructive use of
leisure time.''
   Earlier, the queen knighted social worker Clyde Gollop and
businessman Stanley Blanchette.
   The queen last visited this former British colony in 1985. The
island, with a population of 270,000, is dependent mostly on
tourism. It gained its independence in 1966.
   The royal couple return to Britain on Saturday.
</TEXT>
