<SECOND>AM-Clark Plea,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Principal Blasts School, Warner Bros.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SLIPPERY ROCK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school principal whose
disciplinary methods are the focus of a new movie said his recent
suspension was the work of ``puritanical demagogues.''
   Joe Clark, subject of the recent Warner Bros. Inc. movie ``Lean
on Me,'' said he is not questioning his suspension for arranging an
assembly at his New Jersery school at which four strippers performed.
   ``But for them to get sanctimonious on me. ... They were going to
suspend somebody. So I said, `You want to suspend somebody, suspend
me. I need a rest. I'm tired and you're going to pay me,''' Clark
told the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette before speaking at Slippery Rock
University on Thursday evening.
   The suspension was ordered by Paterson's superintendent of
schools, Dr. Frank Napier, according to Robert G. Rosenberg,
attorney for the board of education. The five-day suspension is due
to begin Monday.
   The assembly at Eastside High School included an act by dancer
Wanda Dee in which she stripped four male dancers down to their
G-strings. Clark was not at the school the day of the assembly last
month and has said he never expected the dance group he hired to
lapse into lasciviousness.
   Clark said controversy over his actions has followed him since he
became principal of Eastside in 1982.
   ``I'm seriously thinking about getting out of education,'' Clark
told The Pittsburgh Press.
   Although Clark's speech was applauded often, his remarks drew a
small group of protesters.
   One of the group's leaders, Shawn Williams, a senior at the
University of Pittsburgh, criticized Clark for kicking out hundreds
of students who had poor grades. Williams said that although
Eastside students had achieved higher test scores, ``This
improvement is due to the principal's purging the school of hundreds
of its weakest students.''
</TEXT>
