<DOCNO> AP890310-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Basra     03-10 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Basra,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army of Workers Moves to Shattered Basra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BASRA, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein has sent 100,000
workers and heavy equipment to transform this ancient southern port,
shattered by eight years of war, into ``the pearl of the gulf,''
officials report.
   Workers were moved to Basra from other parts of Iraq with 40,000
trucks, mechanical diggers and other heavy machinery after Saddam
visited the city in February and said he wanted reconstruction
completed in three months.
   Iraqis see Basra, founded 1,400 years ago and once called the
Venice of the East, as the symbol of their resistance to repeated
Iranian offensives during the Persian Gulf war. Iranian troops
fought to within six miles of Basra last spring.
   ``We will sweat as much blood as we spilled defending Basra to
make it the pearl of the gulf,'' Gov. Anwar Sa'eed Hadithi said in
an interview Thursday.
   He said the government in Baghdad had ``opened its purse'' to
make funds available in addition to the $5 billion originally
alloted for rebuilding.
   ``The new Basra will be an industrial, trade and tourist center
and will attract more people to work here,'' the governor said.
   Hadithi said more than 3,000 damaged houses would be bulldozed
and their owners given grants of up to $32,000 to build new homes.
   Before the war, Basra was Iraq's second largest city and had a
population of 1.5 million. About half the people fled during the
war, but Hadithi said most had returned since the cease-fire took
effect Aug. 20.
   He said the remnants of some public buildings would be left
standing as monuments, and statues of army commanders killed
defending the city would be erected.
   ``The buildings will stand witness to the savage Iranian shelling
of the city,'' Hadithi said. ``The arms of the statues will point
eastward to warn future generations of Iranian ambitions in our
country.''
   Officials predicted the $500 million international airport,
reopened the day of the truce, would become a major transit point
between Europe and the Far East. The civil aviation authority is
offering cut-price fuel, catering discounts and waived landing fees
as incentives to airlines.
   Last week, the Iraqi Ports Authority began clearing a stretch of
the muddy Shatt-al-Arab waterway, the confluence of the Tigris and
Euphrates rivers, which connects Basra with the gulf and represents
the southern frontier with Iran.
   Whether the border runs in the middle of the Shatt or on the east
bank, which would give Iraq full control, is a major obstacle
U.N.-sponsored peace talks. Iran also is resisting Iraqi demands
that the waterway be cleared of wrecked ships, unexploded bombs and
eight years of silt deposits.
   The Iraqi clearing operations are being carried out north of the
point at which the Shatt, Iraq's only outlet to the sea, becomes the
boundary.
   Officials said at least 10 sunken vessels had been raised in a
nine-mile stretch running south from Maqal, the Basra port.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hamadi     03-10 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tape Fails To Reveal Who Shot U.S. Navy Diver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tape played in court Friday
covered the tense moments when a U.S. Navy diver was shot aboard a
hijacked TWA jetliner, but no gunfire could be heard in the
static-filled recording.
   The recording was heard as the trial of confessed TWA hijacker
Mohammed Ali Hamadi resumed in a high-security compound at
Frankfurt's Preungesheim prison.
   However, it failed to shed more light on which of the hijackers
shot and killed U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem during the June 1985
hijacking.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the hijacking of TWA Flight 847, during which 39 Americans
were held hostage for 17 days.
   Hamadi has admitted taking part in the hijacking but has denied
killing Stethem, of Waldorf, Md.
   The airliner was comandeered on a flight from Athens to Rome and
forced to land in Beirut, Lebanon, three times and twice in Algiers,
Algeria.
   The tape covers 49 minutes of conversations between the plane and
the tower during the second landing at Beirut airport on June 15,
when Stethem was shot and tossed onto the tarmac to die.
   When the aircraft landed, one of the hijackers told the control
tower to ``send out a representative of the Amal.''
   The Amal, a Shiite Moslem faction in Lebanon, controlled the
Beirut airport at the time of the hijacking.
   After repeating their demands, one of the hijackers is heard
giving a five-minute deadline, ``or you can take the prettiest
Marine to your hospital.''
   Witnesses have testified that Stethem had been beaten before he
was shot. The hijackers apparently mistook him for a Marine.
   A translator who interpreted the Arab-language segments of the
tape to the court said he could not determine whether Hamadi or his
accomplice was speaking in the tape. Hamadi's accomplice has been
identified in court papers as Hassan Ezzeddine, who is still at
large.
   Hamadi claims his accomplice had talked with the tower and killed
Stethem.
   After a warning from the hijacker that time was running out, the
plane's co-pilot, Philip Maresca, is heard shouting, ``They're
killing a passenger! They're killing a passenger!''
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem, who have
attended the trial regularly since its start July 5, leaned toward
each other in their chairs, anticipating the sound of the shot that
killed their son.
   But no shot could be heard.
   ``Did you hear the noise of the shot?'' one of hijackers is then
heard asking.
   The hijacker warned that a second person would be killed in five
minutes.
   ``One body is already on the runway. If no one is here, there
will be a second,'' the hijacker is heard saying.
   The hijacker later repeats the warning, saying an American will
be killed every five minutes if an Amal representative fails to show
up.
   Witnesses have told the court that about a dozen Amal militiamen
then boarded the plane.
   Hamadi listened closely, interrupting often to correct the
Arab-language translator.
   FBI agent Gary Noesner, who also testified Friday, told the court
that co-pilot Maresca believes Hamadi was the hijacker talking with
the control tower. Maresca has been asked to return March 22 to
testify about the tape.
   The trial was adjourned until Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
