<FIRST>r a AM-RooftopRooters     03-10 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rooftop Rooters,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rooftop Rooters Vow To Fight Planned Private Club Overlooking Wrigley
Field</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A longer version on sports wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rooftop rooters are a tradition among Chicago Cubs
fans, but the team and its neighbors are up in arms over a proposal
for a private club atop a building across from Wrigley Field that
would sell seats for baseball games.
   ``They are clearly stealing our product,'' Cubs President Donald
C. Grenesko said.
   ``We strenuously object to it. If they can do it, then the people
next door can do it, and the people next door to them and the people
next door to them,'' he told the Chicago Sun-Times in an interview
published Friday.
   Grenesko was attending a team owners meeting Friday in Florida
and could not be reached for additional comment, said spokesman Ned
Coletti.
   But Mike Quigley, vice president of a neighborhood group that
battled unsuccesfully to block night baseball at Wrigley Field, said
his group will fight on the team's side this time.
   ``We feel the neighborhood is already past the saturation point
in ability to deal with parking and traffic and liquor-related
problems in association with the ballpark,'' said Quigley, speaking
for Citizens United for Baseball in Sunshine.
   ``The last thing we need is 30 or 40 private clubs just adding to
that,'' he said.
   The neighborhood around Wrigley Field is a close-packed, mostly
residential area on the North Side.
   Unlike the fans who relax in lawn chairs with a beer and a
television set on other rooftops to watch Cubs games, members of the
planned club would pay thousands of dollars for their privilege. The
Cubs' 65 new skyboxes in the stadium already are sold out for this
season at prices ranging from $45,000 to $65,000, the Sun-Times
reported in Friday's editions.
   North Side lawyer Gilbert Liss, a partner in the club project,
declined to comment on it Friday but he told the Sun-Times it would
be private.
   ``They are saying that 50 people, added to the 40,000 who are
already there, are going to cause an undue burden to the
neighborhood,'' Liss said. ``Well, that's ridiculous.
   ``Mr. Grenesko is not pleased. On the other hand. Mr. Grenesko
features the rooftops in (TV) advertising for the Chicago Cubs and
the happy fans.''
   Alderman Bernard J. Hansen, whose ward encompasses Wrigley Field,
said Friday he intends to file an amendment to a zoning ordinance he
has introduced in the City Council to prohibit such a club.
   The amendment would make it illegal for a private club to operate
within 500 feet of an open-air stadium, Hansen said.
   ``They're pirating the use of the Chicago Cubs,'' he said.
   Alderman Helen Shiller, whose ward includes the three-story
building on which construction of the club already has begun, also
opposes it, saying she doubts the project is legal.
   She said work evidently was done on the building without proper
permits.
   ``We started receiving complaints (in January) from neighbors
very upset because construction was going on,'' she told the
Sun-Times.
   Liss told the newspaper the club is allowed under zoning
regulations and ``what we are doing is what's permitted by the law.''
   But Shiller disagreed.
   ``The law, I think, is clear,'' she said. ``In order to exist,
this club needs a zoning change and in order to apply for it they
are going to have to come before the community.''
</TEXT>
