<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Troops     03-10 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Troops,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Troop Cuts Planned in Country's Northwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets have said their planned military cuts
include the reduction of up to 20,000 troops based in the Leningrad
military district, which includes the Kola Peninsula, Norway's
ambassador said Friday.
   Ambassador Olav Buchert-Johannessen said Soviet Defense Ministry
officials disclosed the plans in a meeting with a Norwegian
parliamentary delegation visiting Moscow. The cuts are part of a
500,000-man cut in Soviet armed forces announced by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in December.
   Buchert-Johannessen said the Norwegian officials were told ``up
to 20,000'' troops, would be cut in the Leningrad military district,
which equals 15 percent to 20 percent of the forces.
   ``Such a unilateral step as this we consider very positive,''
Buchert-Johannessen said. Norway is a U.S. ally and member of the
North Atlantci Treaty Organization.
   The Leningrad military district is part of what the Soviets refer
to as the Northwestern Theater of Military Operations.
   The Pentagon's 1988 assessment of Soviet military might says the
Soviets have 12 divisions, 1,350 tanks, 3,750 armored personnel
carriers and infantry fighting vehicles, 2,100 artillery units, 90
tactical submarines, and 160 tactical aircraft in the northwestern
theater.
   Buchert-Johannessen said the Soviet military officials told the
Norwegian lawmakers that they were still considering exactly how
many troops will be cut, and from which divisions.
   Gorbachev has said his country will cut its armed forces by a
half million men over the next two years _ 240,000 of them from the
European theater.
</TEXT>
