<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan     03-10 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Takes Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan on Friday enthusiastically
welcomed the challenge of his friend, President Bush, to make
America a ``kinder, gentler nation'' and pledged to use ``a gentle
touch'' in running the Department of Health and Human Services.
   At his formal swearing-in ceremony, Sullivan said his goals will
include finding better ways to serve the poor, continuing the search
for an AIDS cure, helping to rid the nation of drug abuse and
containing soaring health care costs.
   ``During my tenure, the offices of the department will have a
human face, the regulations will carry a gentle touch,'' the new
secretary said after taking the oath of office in a ceremony
attended by Bush and his wife, Barbara.
   Sullivan is a personal friend of the Bushes. Mrs. Bush serves on
the board of trustees of the Morehouse School of Medicine in
Atlanta, which Sullivan, a blood specialist, founded and served as
president.
   Bush said Sullivan has his ``complete confidence and my full
support'' at HHS, whose nearly $400 billion budget is largest of all
federal departments.
   Reflecting on Sullivan's goal at Morehouse to train minority
physicians to work in medically underserved urban and rural areas,
Bush said, ``What sets Lou Sullivan apart is that something extra he
brings to his work, a sense of mission.''
   Though Bush and Sullivan have agree on the major issues
confronting the department, they appear to have different positions
on programs that offer drug addicts clean needles to help stop the
spread of the AIDS virus.
   Marlin Fitzwater, the president's spokesman, said Bush is
``opposed to exchangeable needles under any condition.''
   Sullivan has told reporters he does not believe clean needle
programs condone drug abuse and he supports needle exchanges in
communities that want them. He said the federal government could
provide assistance to local communities in setting up such
facilities to see if such programs work in helping stop the spread
of the deadly virus.
   Sullivan was confirmed by the Senate last week and was officially
sworn in the same day. The ceremony on Friday was a formal
swearing-in attended by a several hundred department employees,
administration officials and a few members of Congress.
   Sullivan was joined on the podium by his wife, Ginger, and two
sons and daughter. His son, Halsted, a senior at the University of
Virginia, sang ``The Star Spangled Banner.''
</TEXT>
