<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--France-Strike     03-10 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--France-Strike,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delivery Strike Keeps Newspapers Off French Stands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parisians had to rely on television and radio for
news Thursday as a strike by newspaper delivery workers entered its
second day.
   The strike by workers of the Nouvelles Messageries de la Presse
Parisienne, the nation's sole newspaper distribution company,
paralyzed delivery of morning newspapers in the capital and other
French cities.
   Many of the capital's colorful kiosks remained shut and bore
signs reading, ``Newspapers not delivered.''
   A few newspapers, including the Communist-daily L'Humanite and
the afternoon daily Le Monde, managed to distribute a few thousand
copies.
   The strike also affected delivery of some news magazines,
including Paris-Match, L'Express, Le Nouvel Observateur and others.
   The 2,600 workers, members of the Communist-led Confederation de
Travaille, are demanding job security as they face modernization in
the printing and distribution of newspapers.
</TEXT>
