<DOCNO> AP890310-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-High-DefinitionTV     03-10 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High-Definition TV,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Urges U.S. to Adopt European Standard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community Commission on Friday
urged the United States to adopt the European production standard
for high-definition television, saying the EC's approach would be
better for consumers and the TV industry than a competing U.S.
proposal.
   The commission's Washington delegation sent a letter outlining
the EC's approach and criteria for a worldwide HDTV production
standard to the State and Commerce departments.
   The commission said the European standard ``has been shown to be
feasible and the best for producers, broadcasters, the TV industry
and the consumer. In this regard, the commission seeks the support
and cooperation of the United States government.''
   The Europeans are proposing that the next generation of
television _ which promises wall-sized TV screens with the clarity
of 35 mm film _ use a world production standard of 1,250
sequentially scanned lines and 50 frames per second. The United
States in 1984 proposed a 1,125 line-60 frame standard, and since
that time has received the backing of Japan, Canada and Mexico.
   The stakes are high for the United States, which fears that
multiple standards would jeopardize overseas sales of U.S. movies
and TV programs.
   A Commerce Department official said the department thinks the
1,125 line-60 frame standard ``should in fact be reviewed.''
   Jim Spurlock, spokesman for the National Telecommunications and
Information Administration, noted that his agency recently asked the
film and television industry to comment on the U.S. standard.
</TEXT>
