<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WorldSugar     03-10 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Sugar,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Outlook: Production Record, Consumption Even Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook for world sugar production in
1988-89 has been revised downward slightly to 106.4 million metric
tons, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Although down about 0.5 percent from a forecast of 106.9 million
tons in December, production still would be at a record level.
   Total consumption in 1988-89 was forecast at 107.5 million tons,
up slightly from December, the report said. With use exceeding
production, global stocks are expected to decline for the fourth
year in a row.
   ``Stocks at the end of the 1988-89 season may be less than 20
percent of consumption, down from the peak of 31 percent in 1982-83
and the lowest since 1980-81,'' the report said.
   Reduced sugar stockpiles ``suggest strong prices'' in the coming
year, but the report said much depends on 1989-90 world sugar
prospects and decisions about imports.
   In the U.S. market, prices for raw sugar delivered to New York
averaged 22.13 cents per pound in 1988, compared with 21.83 cents in
1987, the report said. Prices in February averaged 22.07 cents per
pound.
   Retail prices for refined sugar have risen faster, averaging
25.49 cents per pound in the Midwest last year, compared with 23.6
cents in 1987, the report said. In February, those averaged nearly
29 cents, up from 22.75 a year ago.
   Nationally, U.S. retail sugar prices averaged 36.6 cents per
pound in 1988, up 4 percent from 1987, the report said. Retail sugar
prices averaged 35.4 cents per pound from 1982 through 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
