<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     03-10 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Lawmakers Storm Out Of Legislature To Protest Carbide
Verdict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition lawmakers stormed out of a
state legislature Friday to protest a Supreme Court verdict settling
claims with the Union Carbide Corp. for the Bhopal gas disaster that
killed at least 3,403 people.
   The Supreme Court also heard arguments on Friday challenging the
government's authority to settle with the Danbury, Conn.-based
company Feb. 14 for damages in the world's worst industrial disaster.
   In Bhopal, all 60 opposition party legislators walked out of the
320-member Madhya Pradesh state legislature to protest the verdict.
   Opposition politicians, newspapers and others have criticized the
settlement, ``ruled full and final,'' as inadequate. The government
originally sued for $3 billion.
   A five-judge Supreme Court panel headed by Judge Sabyasachi
Mukherjee heard arguments on a petition that seeks to strike down
1985 legislation making the government the sole representative of
victims of the gas leak.
   If the law were struck down, ``the entire settlement will fall on
its back,'' said Rajiv Dhavan, an attorney for Union Carbide.
   Union Carbide has already deposited the $470 million with the
court.
   Arguments on the petition are to continue Monday.
   Charanlal Sahu, a Bhopal-based attorney, filed the petition
Wednesday. He says he is among the victims of the leak at a
pesticide plant in the central Indian city on Dec. 3, 1984.
   The leak of poisonous methyl isocyanate gas killed more than
3,400 people and injured at least 20,000 others. The plant was
operated by Union Carbide of India Ltd., a subsidiary of the
U.S.-based multinational company.
   More than 570,000 claims were filed with the government by people
who said they were harmed by the disaster.
</TEXT>
