<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Lebanon     03-10 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Israeli Troops, Four Lebanese Militamen Hurt By Roadside Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Friday on a main road
north of Israel's self-declared ``security zone,'' wounding two
Israeli soldiers and four other people, officials said.
   Police in Lebanon the six included Israeli troops and allied
Lebanese militiamen. In Jerusalem, an Israeli army official said the
victims included two Israeli soldiers and four Lebanese civilians.
   The conflicting reports could not immediately be reconciled.
   The police said the explosion occurred along the main
Kawkaba-Marjayoun road in the southern Lebanese town of Marjayoun,
about six miles north of the security zone. The region is patrolled
by Norwegian soldiers working in the United Nations peacekeeping
force.
   The Israeli official said one of the civilians was seriously
wounded and was flown to Rambam Hospital in the northern Israeli
city of Haifa.
   In Beirut, the pro-Iranian Siite Moslem Hezbollah, or Party of
God, claimed responsibility for the roadside bomb. The group said
four Israeli helicopter gunships evacuated the casualties and that
fires were blazing in the area.
   ``An Islamic resistance squad carried out a courageous operation
against the Israeli enemy in the Marjeyoun area,'' a Hezbollah
statement said.
   The Islamic resistance, a coalition of Iranian-backed groups, has
been involved in guerrilla warfare in the security zone, which has a
predominantly Shiite Moslem population.
   U.N. peacekeeping troops and Israeli soldiers were put on alert
and a joint Israeli-SLA force immediately blanketed the area with
machine gun fire, said a police spokesman who cannot be identified
under standing rules.
   Tension has been running high between Israeli troops and
peacekeepers serving with the U.N. Interim Force in south Lebanon.
   On Thursday, Israeli troops beat up four U.N. peacekeepers near
their headquarters in the Lebanese border town of Naqoura, according
to security sources in south Lebanon.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said six
Israeli troops went into a restaurant on the main road to Naqoura,
where they harassed and slapped one Irish and three Swedish soldiers
before confiscating their cameras and films.
   The Israeli troops accused the four U.N. soldiers of taking
pictures of an Israeli-made Merkava tank they were aboard before
entering the restaurant, the sources said.
   On Tuesday, Israeli troops drove a tank into a group of UNIFIL
vehicles after the peacekeepers detained an Israeli military convoy
at a checkpoint in south Lebanon. No U.N. soldiers were injured,
although several vehicles were damaged, according to U.N. sources.
   The security zone is a six- to 10-mile wide buffer retained by
Israel after it withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon in
1985, ending a three-year occupation. Israeli troops patrol the area
looking for Palestinian guerrillas who sometimes cross the border to
attack Israeli settlements.
</TEXT>
