<FIRST>u w AM-Cheney-Reaction 2nd-Writethru a0768 03-10 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-Reaction, 2nd-Writethru, a0768,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Bush-Pentagon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 grafs Warner comment after 7th graf pvs, Nunn, speaking;
inserts 1 graf Foley comment after 11th graf pvs, Praise for; CORRECTS
spelling of Wirth, 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Loud Applause for Choice from Democrats, Republicans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nomination of Rep. Dick Cheney
as defense secretary won bipartisan applause Friday from
congressional colleagues of the Wyoming Republican.
   ``He's a very able and impressive person,'' said Sen. Tim Wirth,
D-Colo. ``He's one of the smartest people in Congress.''
   ``An excellent choice,'' said Sen. Charles Robb, the freshman
from Virginia who was one of the last Democrats to announce his
opposition to John Tower, whom the Senate had refused to confirm as
defense secretary Thursday.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the Armed Services Committee chairman who
led the Democrats' fight against Tower, issued a joint statement
with Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the committee's senior
Republican, that said:
   ``Dick Cheney is well known and highly respected by the members
of the Senate. We have worked with him on many issues involving
national defense and intelligence matters.''
   Nunn and Warner said that, at Bush's request, the committee would
open hearings on the nomination next week.
   Nunn, speaking to reporters in Philadelphia, said, ``I know of no
impediment to his nomination.
   And Warner said he found Cheney's choice ``a wonderful, perfect
nomination.''
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine said he was
``pleased that President Bush has moved quickly'' and added that
Cheney ``has served with distinction in the U.S. House of
Representatives since 1978.''
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole quickly hailed the appointment
in a barbed comment that reflected the bitterness lingering from the
Tower confirmation struggle.
   ``He's tough. That's what we wanted. A tough, tough, tough guy,''
he said of Cheney. ``This time it will be a confirmation, not an
execution.''
   Praise for Cheney, a six-term congressman and the No. 2
Republican in the House, cut widely across party lines, with both
Democrats and Republicans bruised by the lengthy battle over Tower
indicating they hope Cheney will be quickly confirmed.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley called the appointement
``splendid'' and added, ``I would predict an early and unanimous
confirmation.''
   ``It's a very fine selection,'' said Rep. Charles Bennett,
D-Fla., a member of the House Armed Services Committee.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., another member of the Senate
committee that will consider Cheney's confirmation, had high praise
as well, but said he would not give final judgement until hearings
are held.
   ``I know of no reason why it wouldn't be unanimous, but I want to
reserve judgment,'' said Gore.
   ``I like him a lot,'' he said. ``I served with him in the House.
... While I am going to reserve final judgment particularly as a
member of the committee I know of no reason at this point not to
accept speedy confirmation.''
   But the initial reaction from those who have known Cheney was
that Bush had made a shrewd choice.
   ``Dick Cheney is a close friend and colleague,'' said Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee and
one of the strongest supporters of Tower.
   ``I have the greatest respect for his broad range of experience
and knowledge,'' said McCain. ``I look favorably on this nomination
and hope that he will be confirmed expeditiously.''
   ``Few people in Washington understand the executive and
legislative branches of government as well as Dick Cheney,'' said
Rep. Tony Coelho of California, the House Democratic Whip. ``This is
a smart move on the part of the president but a great move on behalf
of the country.''
   And Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., one of the most conservative
members of the Senate, said ``on first glance it looks like a very
good appointment. He has long experience in Congress and the
executive branch. He appears to have a very solid record on defense
issues.''
   Bill Greener, a former Air Force colonel and the Pentagon's chief
spokesman during the Ford administration, when Cheney was White
House chief of staff, said Friday the congressman was ``a perfect
choice.''
   ``There should be loud cheers in Washington,'' Greener said.
   ``He's a great manager. He is a quick learner with an absolute
amazing mentality. And he's always been a `strong defense' person.
He's also very open and easy going. He's a perfect choice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
