<FIRST>u i AM-BerlinCoalition     03-10 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berlin Coalition,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists Form Coalition to Govern West Berlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Social Democrats and West Berlin's
equivalent of the anti-NATO Greens formed a government Friday that
pledges to reduce Allied military control of the city and curb
police action against street protest.
   The coalition agreement between the Social Democrats and the
far-left Alternative List won nearly unanimous approval Friday at a
special Social Democrat congress. An Alternative List meeting is
scheduled for Sunday.
   Walter Momper of the Social Democrats is to become mayor when the
new legislature meets next week, replacing Eberhard Diepgen, whose
Christian Democrats were set back in the Jan. 29 city elections.
   Voters gave the Christian Democrats and Social Democrats 55 seats
each in the 138-member legislature and the Alternative List got 17.
The far-right Republican Party won the other 11.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats have been slipping
in opinion polls, and the so-called ``Red-Green'' government in West
Berlin will be a major test of whether such a coalition can work
nationally.
   Several polls have indicated Kohl's center-right coalition may
lose the national elections in December 1990.
   ``I think that with this Red-Green coalition ... alternative
policies will play a much more essential role than before in the
city and on the federal level,'' Alternative List leader Christian
Stroebele told reporters.
   He said there will be ``decisive change in the city and that will
have a ripple effect'' throughout West Germany.
   Under the agreement, the Alternative List will control three city
departments: environment and development, schooling and sports, and
women, youth and family.
   The party has advocated stronger environmental controls, curbs on
police, restrictions on the use of motor vehicles and more
government-subsidized housing.
   Otto Schily, a prominent Greens member of the federal parliament,
said his party and the Social Democrats should study the possibility
of a national coalition.
   Business spokesmen have said some companies might leave West
Berlin because of the leftist government, particularly if it raises
taxes to finance social programs.
   The Christian Democrats had dominated city politics in recent
years and promoted business develoment to help reduce the isolation
of West Berlin, which is 90 miles inside communist East German.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
