<FIRST>u i AM-CostaRica-Hull     03-10 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Hull,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Hull, Linked to Contras, Freed in Costa Rica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American-born John Hull, who has been
linked to the Nicaraguan rebel supply network, was released from
prison Friday after he posted $37,500 bail, his defense lawyer said.
   Attorney Rita Herrera said the 69-year-old Hull, jailed Jan. 13
on charges of drug trafficking and violating Costa Rican security,
was freed shortly after friends collected enough money to meet bail.
   ``Since Mr. Hull lacked the money, many friends ... offered to
help him and this afternoon we were able to gather all the bail
money,'' Ms. Herrera told The Associated Press by telephone from San
Carlos, where the proceedings against Hull are taking place.
   The town is 100 miles to the north, near the Nicaraguan border
and Hull's farm.
   Ms. Herrera said Hull was resting at the home of a friend, but
she declined to say where.
   A Superior Penal Court judge in Alajuela ruled on Thursday that
Hull could be released and set bond. It earlier refused to release
Hull on bond.
   Hull, originally from Evansville, Ind., has lived in Costa Rica
for 20 years, and his lawyers say he became a Costa Rican citizen
eight years ago.
   While in jail, he had a heart attack and was hospitalized for
three weeks.
   Hull is accused of allowing his ranch to be used by the
Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, and for narcotics trafficking
between 1982 and 1985.
   He denied the charges.
</TEXT>
