<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-IMF     03-10 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-IMF,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Warns Of Turmoil in Egypt If IMF Timetable Is Followed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak warned
on Friday that the timetable set by the International Monetary Fund
for economic reforms in his country could cause political and social
upheaval in Egypt.
   The IMF wants Mubarak to speed up his reforms before a new
meeting can be held on a rescheduling of Egypt's $44 billion foreign
debt.
   The first such conference was held in May 1987.
   ``We are not against the reforms.'' the Egyptian president told
reporters. ``It is the timetable that bothers us.''
   Mubarak spoke after meeting with senior European Economic
Community officials in Brussels, including EEC Commission President
Jacques Delors.
   His stop was part of a European tour to win support for an
international Middle East peace conference which Israel opposes.
   He outlined his economic reform program in his talks with Delors
and explained the political and social risks inherent in speeding
them up.
   International banks want Mubarak to slash Egypt's budget deficit,
apply energy price reforms, liberalize interest rates and
rationalize its multitier exchange rate system.
   ``But some price reforms the IMF is asking of us would mean
increasing some prices sevenfold,'' Mubarak said.
   Earlier Friday, the EEC approved two development projects
totaling $4.9 million.
   The bulk of the money _ $3.33 million _ will go to a four-year
rural development project in the Nile Valley.
   The remainder will go to promote joint ventures, notably between
small and medium enterprises in the EEC and Egypt.
   On the Middle East, Mubarak said Israel ``should not fear an
international conference (which) cannot impose a (peace) settlement
on anyone.''
   He said the conference ``would only be a guarantee ... for direct
talks between the main actors in the Israeli-Arab conflict.''
   Mubarak said he did not ask Delors to urge the 12 EEC states to
recognize Palestine.
   ``The question of recognition is a detail,'' he said. ``What
counts is that an international peace conference should get off the
ground.''
   Mubarak also denied that Egypt is assembling Swiss-made parts
that could be used to create a chemical weapons plant at Abu Zaabal,
north of Cairo.
   The New York Times said Friday U.S. officials believe Egypt is
doing this.
   Mubarak said, ``This is the first I've heard of it. We are
against chemical weapons and, of course, don't make any such
factories.''
   Mubarak was due to leave Brussels Saturday for The Hague, the
Netherlands, to attend the International Conference on Atmospheric
Pollution.
   He is scheduled to have a private meeting with President Francois
Mitterrand of France, who will also attend the conference.
   On Sunday Mubarak will travel to West Germany for a five-day
state visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
