<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Tibet     03-10 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Tibet,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetans In New York Rally For An Independent Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tibet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Tibetans and sympathizers
carried a wooden coffin and blew horns Friday in a march from U.N.
headquarters to the Chinese U.N. Mission to demand Tibet's
independence from China.
   On the 30th anniversary of a failed Tibetan uprising, protesters
gathered across the street from the United Nations and chanted
``China out of Tibet!'' and ``U.N. help Tibet!''
   China regards as an internal affair the unrest in Tibet that
killed at least 16 people this week. As a permanent member of the
Security Council, China can block action on Tibetan affairs by
vetoing any proposed resolution.
   A crowd estimated by police at up to 200 people assembled to the
warbling notes of fluted horns that monks in Tibet play as a
religious instrument.
   Speakers recounted the suffering of the Tibetan people after
China crushed the 1959 rebellion, contending that more than 1.2
million Tibetans have been killed and more than 6,000 monasteries
destroyed.
   Carrying such signs as ``Home Rule for Tibet'' and ``Stop Torture
of Monks,'' the protesters marched to China's U.N. Mission to
complete their rally, carrying a coffin labeled ``Over Million
Killed.''
   The march gathered more followers as it wended across Manhattan.
Police estimated 300 arrived at the Chinese Mission, where the
protesters tore to bits a Chinese flag printed on cardboard.
   The organizer of the rally, the U.S. Tibet Committee, is a
private U.S. human rights committee staffed by Tibetans and
Americans that promotes Tibetan independence.
</TEXT>
