<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     03-10 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vrdolyak, Daley Each Blame Other for Brawl at Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican mayoral candidate Edward Vrdolyak, who
won the top spot on the city's April election ballot Friday, traded
accusations with Democratic rival Richard M. Daley over who was
behind a melee at a Vrdolyak rally.
   The scuffle broke out while Vrdolyak spoke at a rally Thursday
night on the city's Northwest Side. Witnesses told police the
icident began when three men approached the podium and began booing
the candidate.
   ``It appeared they were going to attack Vrdolyak,'' said Police
Officer Janice Redmond.
   Vrdolyak supporters responded by throwing punches at a dozen
people Vrdolyak said were Daley supporters, and the hecklers fled
the scene. One man, hit in the eye and leg, was treated and released
at Resurrection Hospital, said spokesman Warren Nelson.
   There were no other injuries and no arrests, police said.
   Daley campaign officials denied any involvement and suggested
Vrdolyak himself had set up the incident.
   Vrdolyak said one of the cars was traced to Daley supporters and
that William Daley, the candidate's brother and campaign adviser,
had encouraged the harassment.
   ``All of a sudden three weeks before the election he comes out
with this. This is ridiculous,'' said Daley, Cook County state's
attorney.
   ``If Vrdolyak thinks these people were hired by the Daley
campaign, it is more likely that he or someone in his campaign hired
them so they could blame it on the Daley campaign,'' added Daley
spokeswoman Avis LaVelle.
   Vrdolyak held a news conference to deny the accusation and said
he would withdraw from the race if anyone could prove otherwise.
   Also Friday, the Board of Election Commissioners announced that
Vrdoylak had won the lottery to determine whose name would top the
ballot for the April 4 general election. Daley's name will appear
second, followed by third-party candidate Timothy Evans, a South
Side alderman and the only black in the campaign.
   The election will choose a successor to Harold Washington, the
city's first black mayor.
   Vrdolyak, a former Democratic alderman, switched parties in 1987
and waged a write-in campaign to win the GOP nomination in the
February primary.
   The winner of the general election will serve out the final two
years of Washington's second term. The City Council appointed Eugene
Sawyer acting mayor after Washington died of a heart attack in
November 1987., Sawyer, also black, ran in the Democratic primary
but lost to Daley.
</TEXT>
