<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-10 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Weather Across Much of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gale-force wind and strong waves pounded Florida's northern coast
on Friday, but sunny skies brought record high temperatures and mild
weather to much of the nation.
   Scattered rain Friday fell in the Pacific Northwest.
   A flood warning was posted for the John Day River at Service
Creek, Ore., because warm temperatures had caused a rapid melting of
the snow. Similar flood warnings were posted in Montana.
   An ice jam caused minor lowland flooding at Wilson, Neb., and
several county roads were closed by flooding in Dodge County, Neb.
   Temperatures were unseasonably warm from much of the Mississippi
Valley across the Rockies and the Plateau.
   Several cities set high temperature records for the date,
including Amarillo, Texas, with 86 degrees; Colorado Springs, Colo.,
with 75; Goodland, Kan., with 82; and Pueblo, Colo., with 83.
   The low temperature for the nation Friday was 1 degree above zero
at Houlton, Maine.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 90 degrees at Gage, Okla.
   Several beachfront homes were flooded in Fernandina Beach, Fla.,
as high tide rose 2 feet above normal. Authorities closed some
coastal roads and chased thousands of people from the sand at
Daytona Beach.
   Saturday's forecast called for rain over eastern upper Michigan,
from western Montana across the Northern Plateau and the northern
two-thirds of the Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 30s and 40s from New
England across inland New York state, the Great Lakes, Minnesota,
North Dakota and northeast Montana; in the 50s and 60s from
southeast New York state across northern Florida, over the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, from eastern Missouri across Iowa and the
northern Plains, the Rockies, northern Plateau, Great Basin and the
northern Pacific coast; in the 80s from much of Texas across inland
Southern California; in the 90s over the desert Southwest; in the
70s over the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
