<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     03-10 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Back Election Boycott With Traffic Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels said Friday they
will begin a traffic ban before the March 19 presidential elections,
which they are boycotting.
   Closing the highways has been a favorite rebel tactic in the
9-year-old civil war. The bans virtually paralyze vehicle traffic,
the principal means of transportation in this Central American
nation, and the rebels enforce them by shooting up or firebombing
trucks, cars or buses found on the roads.
   Venceremos, the clandestine rebel radio, said the ban would start
at midnight Wednesday and continue until further notice.
   It said the purpose was to reinforce ``public sentiment against
the March 19 election.''
   Five traffic bans were declared last year, including one to
support a boycott of legislative and municipal elections. Army
trucks with soldiers riding shotgun were used in some areas to take
people to the polls.
   The rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance won a majority in
the national legislature in the elections last March and its
candidate, businessman and coffee grower Alfredo Christiani, is
favored to win this one.
   Christiani is running against Christian Democratic candidate
Fidel Chavez, a lawyer and former foreign minister, and Guillermo
Ungo of the Democratic Convergence, a coalition of non-combatant
leftist groups.
   A few hours before the traffic ban was announced, President Jose
Napoleon Duarte blamed the rebel Faribundo Marti National Liberation
Front for a delay in negotiations to end the war.
   Duarte's Christian Democratic administration rejected a Jan. 24
proposal by the rebels to begin talks if the election was postponed
until at least September and their conditions for security and a
clean vote were met.
   He accused the guerrillas of ``rejecting dialogue'' and resorting
to ``delay and deceit.''
   ``Their strategy is to create conditions that will gain them
points internationally and nationally, with proposals of peace that
they do not want to honor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
