<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Sarah     03-10 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Sarah,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lecture Reporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush served up the last question at
his news conference on Friday with a lecture to outspoken reporter
Sarah McClendon that ``the loudest voice won't always be
recognized.''
   But the feisty Texas newswoman, who has covered 10 presidents,
had the last laugh: her question wasn't for Bush but for Defense
Secretary-designate Richard Cheney.
   ``I wanted to ask you new man what he feels...,'' she began.
   Ms. McClendon, a fixture at White House news conferences since
1944, was seeking to get the president's attention in her usual way
_ by calling out robustly for recognition.
   At first ignoring her calls, Bush wound up the news conference _
called to announce his choice of Cheney _ by recognizing her.
   But, at the same time, he told her: ``I will make a new
announcement of press policy, Sarah. The squeaking wheel will not
always get the grease in life, and the loudest voice won't always
get recognized.''
   ``You and I have known each a long time and so this is the last
time that I can succumb to the tendency to go to the loudest or most
frantic wave. I can't do it and it's not fair to calmer souls.''
   Ms. McClendon, who operates her own Texas news service, said
afterwards that she has known Bush a long time and took no offense
from his remarks, which she called ``just a bunch of gaff.''
   ``It doesn't bother me at all. I have a right to get in my
questions just as everyone else. We don't all have a seat in the
front row,'' she said.
</TEXT>
