<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strikes     03-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strikes,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spreading Postal Strike Closes Main Warsaw Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers began a sit-in strike at Warsaw's
main post Friday in a spreading pay dispute by postal employees that
has made it difficult to pay bills, collect pensions and conduct
other business.
   The first Warsaw post office closed Tuesday, and by Thursday 38
of the 242 branches were on strike, according to official reports.
   Post offices also were closed in the southern cities of Krakow
and Radom, where an official report said workers at 10 post offices
were refusing to handle mail not labeled emergency.
   Strikers are seeking wage increases and changes in working
conditions at the offices, which provide a wide range of services
including collecting rent and utility and insurance payments.
   Workers seek monthly raises averaging 30,000 to 35,000 zlotys _
$54 to $63 at the official exchange rate _ according to Zuzanna
Dabrowska of the banned Polish Socialist Party.
   She put the average postal employee's monthly salary at 32,000
zlotys, or $57. The state PAP news agency said pay raises last year
made the average mail carrier's salary 55,000 zlotys, or $99, and
the average cashier's monthly salary 66,000 zlotys _ $118.
   Mail carriers also are demanding that they not be required to
deliver weekly newspapers and magazines, except perhaps to disabled
people, and are disputing pension and benefit payments.
   PAP quoted the management of Warsaw's main post office as saying,
``The possibility of pay increases here, like in all other
enterprises, are directly dependent on economic effects.''
   Banners announcing the strike covered the entrance doors at the
main post office.
   The banners did not indicate if the strikers were affiliated with
the outlawed Solidarity union movement or the government-sanctioned
OPZZ union.
   Ms. Dabrowska said strike committee members were not associated
with either group and the sit-in would continue at the main post
office at least until Monday.
   Poland has had labor disputes since the beginning of the year,
with workers trying to cope with inflation that exceeded more than
60 percent last year. Government officials hope to reduce that to 50
percent this year.
   A strike entered its 11th day at the Poltex J. Marchlewski cotton
mill in Lodz, and bankers told managers the plant is facing
insolvency.
   PAP said mill workers voted to continue the strike after a
discussion. It quoted a strike committee member as saying, ``The
financial situation of the factory is bad. The workers do not feel
responsible for that.'' He blamed taxes, management and financial
regulations.
   Industry Minister Mieczlyslaw Wilczek is considering liquidating
the plant, PAP said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
