<FIRST>r w AM-Gasoline-Smog     03-10 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gasoline-Smog,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Tougher Emission Standards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government, trying to head off an
increasingly severe urban smog problem this summer, ordered tougher
hydrocarbon emission standards for gasoline Friday, but the federal
action is not as tough as some states would like.
   The Environmental Protection Agency announced that for the first
time, gasoline will have to meet nationwide volatility levels. These
levels, which are controlled during the blending process, determine
how easily gasoline evaporates and, in turn, how much hydrocarbon
pollutants get into the air.
   Hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides are key ingredient of ozone and
urban smog.
   Under the EPA requirements, gasoline volatility may be no greater
than 10.5 pounds per inch in most parts of the country this summer.
In some states, especially during the hottest months, the standard
is somewhat tougher.
   The EPA action is the first time the federal government has told
the petroleum industry it had to curb volatility to a specific level
on nationwide basis. There have been local limits in southern
California since the early 1970s.
   The EPA estimated the federal requirement, which sets a 10.5 psi
gasoline volatility level or lower in every state, would mean a 13
percent reduction of hydrocarbon emissions into the air. Gasoline
volatility generally has been at at a level of 11.5 psi.
   But the EPA said that level causes a release of gasoline vapors
``beyond the capacity of existing vehicle-emission controls'' to
handle. As a result, vapors are released into the air from auto fuel
systems as well as while gasoline is transferred from one storage
area to another or while vehicles are being fueled, officials said.
   ``Most of our major urban areas suffer from unhealthful summer
smog levels,'' said EPA Administrator William K. Reilly in a
statement. ``The standards set today will help reduce this harmful
pollutant.''
   The country had the worst urban smog problem in recent years last
summer with nationwide ozone levels higher than anytime in this
decade and 14 percent greater than the year before. Federal maximum
ozone levels were exceeded 60 percent more often last summer than in
1983, the worst previous year.
   But a group of northeastern states have pushed for even tougher
restrictions and officials in those states have expressed concerns
that their state requirements _ which would limit gasoline
volatility to 9 psi this summer _ might be scuttled by the federal
regulation.
   By law, federal emission rules normally would pre-empt local
requirements unless specific waivers are provided, EPA officials
said. The EPA said last month it plans to grant a waiver to
Massachusetts, but the agency has not acted on waiver requests from
the other six states states.
   The tougher gasoline volatility standards enacted for this summer
are to go into effect May 1 in Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
Connecticut, New York, New Jersey, Vermont and Maine unless
preempted by the federal regulation.
   The tougher state standards have been strongly opposed by the
petroleum industry. The American Petroleum Institute has filed suit
in New York seeking to prevent that state's tougher restrictions
from going into effect. It argues the state requirements _ which
establish a maximum 9 psi volatility level for gasoline sold between
May 1 and Sept. 15 _ could cause driving problems and problems in
gasoline distribution.
   But supporters of the more stringent requirements deny that the
lower volatility levels adversely affect gasoline performance. They
maintain the oil companies' opposition to the tighter standards stem
from the fact the gasoline with the lower volatility is more
expensive to produce.
   ``The Northeast is faced with a sever ozone problem (in the
summer months). We have two choices. We can either reduce emissions
that contribute to ozone formation or we can continue to ask people
to restrict their activity during ozone episodes,'' said Michael
Bradley, executive director of a coalition of state enviornmental
officials formed to implement the tougher requirements in the seven
northeastern states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Banker     03-10 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Banker,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Lebanese Banker Reappears, Denies Kidnap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent Lebanese international banker
Roger Tamraz reappeared Friday and denied reports he was kidnapped
and held for ransom by a militia leader who lost money when his bank
went under.
   Earlier Friday, however, a Tamraz business associate told The
Associated Press in Nicosia, Cyprus that the banker was freed after
arranging to pay the final installment of a $3 million ransom.
   Tamraz, 48, checked into the seaside west Beirut Summerland Hotel
shortly before sunset.
   ``I was not kidnapped,'' he said in an interview with The
Associated Press. ``I was on my own doing my own thinking.''
   Tamraz, who was reported kidnapped Feb. 19, said the ransom
report was ``based on rumor and figment of the imagination, and
there's nothing to it.''
   The Christian-controlled radio station, Voice of Lebanon, said
Thursday that Tamraz was being held by Elie Hobeika, commander of a
Christian militia in the eastern Bekaa valley town of Zahle.
   The report said that Hobeika, a former commander of the Lebanese
Forces, the main Christian militia, was forcing Tamraz to pay $3
million he claimed was owed him after the collapse of Bank
Al-Mashrek, Lebanon's second-largest bank.
   Tamraz, who is a United States resident, headed the Christian-run
bank until December, when a run on its assets began. An arrest
warrant was issued for Tamraz pending investigation of the bank's
affairs.
   The respected newsletter, Middle East Economic Survey, estimated
Al-Mashrek's deficit in Lebanon at $100 million. A largely
state-owned conglomerate owned a major share in the bank.
   Tamraz fled from Christian east Beirut to the Moslem-held western
part of the capital in January and lived in the Summerland hotel
until shortly before his disappearance. Since last fall, Lebanon has
had two rival governments, one Christian and one Moslem.
   The Tamraz associate, who spoke by telephone from Paris and
declined to be identified, said a ``loan instrument'' was fixed to
transfer the final $750,000 in ransom money to the kidnappers
through a Swiss bank.
   He said Tamraz' release was delayed for two days while the loan
was arranged.
   Hobeika is held responsible for the September 1982 massacre of
hundreds of Palestinian civilians by Christian militiamen in two
Beirut refugee camps after Israel invaded Lebanon. The charge was
confirmed by Israeli reports but denied by Hobeika.
   In his interview Friday, Tamraz predicted he would be vindicated
of charges in connection with the bank's demise. Investigators say
the bank, under his direction, made shaky investments in Spanish
real estate and a money-losing cargo airline. It also took over
three ailing banks and assumed their deficits.
   In the past Tamraz, a Maronite Catholic, blamed Lebanese central
bank governor Edmond Naim for deliberately undermining the bank in
order to get rid of him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
