<HEAD>Two Shot In Belfast Pub, One Dies In Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ireland's Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd `They said...' with wounding in Falls
Road</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were cut down by gunfire
as they left a busy tavern Friday night in mainly Roman Catholic
west Belfast, and one died in a hospital, police reported.
   Witnesses said two gunmen stepped from an automobile across the
street from the Orient Bar, fired several shots and sped off in the
car.
   They said Protestants and Catholics frequent the pub. There was
no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Also in west Belfast, an elderly man was shot in the arm in a
garage on the Falls Road, a predominantly Catholic area, and taken
to a hospital, a police spokesman said.
   Five other people have been killed in Northern Ireland this week.
The death toll is at least 2,730 in the 20 years since the Irish
Republican Army began fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland.
   Two British soldiers were killed Wednesday night when a mine
containing 400 pounds of explosives blew up their armored jeep near
Londonderry. Six other soldiers in the two-vehicle patrol were
wounded.
   Two innocent men were killed by IRA gunmen Tuesday, in a case of
mistaken identity, while they chatted with friends at a gas station
in Coagh village, County Tyrone.
