<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Strike     03-10 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Strike,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners' Strike Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic Albanian miners on Friday
stayed away from their jobs for a second day to protest the
treatment of ethnic Albanian leaders in troubled Kosovo province,
the state Tanjug news agency said.
   Elez Zeinalihi, director of the mine, told The Associated Press
in a telephone interview that he and local party leaders talked to
about 120 miners for two hours Friday morning and tried to persuade
them to resume work.
   ``They even refused to talk to us,'' Zeinalihi said about the
strikers. ``I don't know what will happen now.''
   Zeinalihi said the miners, who began their strike Thursday, were
protesting what they described as the ``hounding of (some ethnic)
Albanian leaders'' by police, and demanded an explanation of why
Azem Vlasi, a former Communist Party leader of Kosovo, and two other
officials were recently arrested.
   The 400 miners of three shifts at the mine about 140 miles south
of Belgrade were visited Thursday by Kosovo's Premier Nazmi Mustafa,
who urged them to deal with their grievances through legal means,
Tanjug said.
   ``Do not complicate the already serious situation,'' he
reportedly warned the miners.
   Miners of two pits at the Trepca lead and zinc mines also stopped
work Friday morning for an hour, Tanjug reported.
   Last month, about 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners staged an
eight-day sit-in at the Trepca mines, demanding that no changes be
made in Yugoslavia's 1974 constitution, which granted Kosovo
wide-ranging autonomy. The miners also demanded the resignations of
three senior Communist Party officials.
   The action, which brought Kosovo to the verge of a general
strike, prompted federal authorities to impose emergency measures in
the region and led to the arrest of Vlasi, two directors of the
Trepca mines and several other people accused of sedition.
   The strike ended after the three party officials, who are
generally believed to be supporters of Serbia's party chief Slobodan
Milosevic, bowed to the strikers' demands and handed in their
resignations.
   Since then, however, Serbian govermnment officials and the
republic's partisan press have been demanding that the resignations
be withdrawn and the strikers punished.
   Milosevic has been pressing for constitutional changes that would
introduce more Serbian control over the affairs of Kosovo in an
effort to provide more security for the Slav minority, which claims
persecution by the majority ethnic Albanians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
