<DOCNO> AP890310-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Tibet 1stLd-Writethru a0649 03-10 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Arrests Reported in Tibet; Foreigners Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing, UPDATING with
American's remarks upon arriving in Nepal. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tibetans and Chinese news reports painted
radically different pictures of how the remote region, after a week
of riot and martial law, marked the 30th anniversary Friday of a
fruitless uprising against China.
   State TV said more than 30 Tibetan ``rioters'' surrendered to
police and admitted to taking part in disturbances this week in
Lhasa, the capital.
   It said Tibetans peacefully ``celebrated the 30th anniversary of
democratic reforms in Tibet.''
   Tibetans reached by telephone Thursday and Friday spoke of
large-scale roundups and pervasive fear in the city of 70,000.
   One woman said arrests began soon after the last Western tourists
were expelled from the city. Tourists were ordered out when martial
law was imposed at midnight Tuesday, and the last planeload of
foreigners left Friday.
   Protests and riots cost 16 lives by official count, but Western
travelers say most Tibetans put the death toll at 20 to 30.
   A group of five men _ an American and four Swedes _ arrived in
the Nepalese capital of Katmandu Friday night and said they were
happy to be out of Lhasa. They left Lhasa Tuesday morning and were
the first batch of foreigners to reach Nepal.
   ``I feel very lucky to get my passport back from the Chinese and
make my journey safely to Katmandu,'' Russell Liebman, 22, of New
York City, told The Associated Press there.
   A 22-year-old Swede from Uppsala, who identied himself only as
Pontus, said they had reserved a vehicle and ``we had a 2{-day ride
... along the Tibetan plateau. But after reaching Nyalam, we had to
walk rest of the day through the snowfields to reach Zangmu, the
last Tibetan township situated near the border (with Nepal).''
   Liebman said, ``I still feel dazed after witnessing the warlike
scenes. ... We saw three bodies of the people killed in actual
shooting near our place.''
   Liebman said they took many photographs, but police confiscated
the film when they ran back to their hotel after shooting broke out.
   China's nightly news said martial law stopped a riot planned for
Friday in Lhasa.
   New martial law orders issued Thursday demanded the immediate
surrender of anyone who planned, instigated or participated in the
riots or was harboring criminals or hiding looted goods.
   The official press, in reports on government officials returning
to work and Tibetans bringing food and blankets to Chinese soldiers,
depicted Tibetans as supporting the crackdown.
   ``A veteran Tibetan worker took a bottle of yak-butter tea to
police,'' said the official Xinhua News Agency. When an officer
refused because of military regulations, ``the old man insisted that
the policeman at least come to his home nearby `to get a warmup from
the cold','' the report said.
   Earlier this week, foreign travelers said most Tibetans were
terrified of martial law and the police.
   ``Tibetans told me the night they declared martial law people
were staying up late cleaning their houses of anything that might be
incriminating,'' an American said Friday. ``They were burning
pictures of the Dalai Lama,'' the exiled spiritual leader who fled
to India after the uprising in 1959.
   During the riots, Tibetans demanding independence and chanting
loyalty to the Dalai Lama threw stones, ransacked Chinese-owned
shops, set fire to Chinese property and attacked government
buildings.
   On Friday, the Dalai Lama urged Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping to
end the violence in Lhasa and begin talk on a peaceful solution.
   In an interview with the BBC, he said negotiations with the
Chinese are ``the only way.''
   In New York, about 200 Tibetans and sympathizers carried a wooden
coffin from U.N. Headquarters to China's U.N. Mission, chanting
slogans and blowing prayer horns.
   For China, the March 10 anniversary marks the beginning of
``democratic reform,'' the institution of communist political and
economic systems in the remote Himalayan region.
   Tibetans remember the day as one when tens of thousands converged
on the Dalai Lama's palace to prevent what they thought was a
Chinese military attempt to kidnap their god-king.
   A week later, the Chinese allegedly fired two mortar shells into
the palace grounds, and the Dalai Lama and his family fled secretly
to India.
   When he was gone, the Chinese army destroyed the Tibetan
resistance, killing hundreds of people, perhaps thousands.
   China says Tibet has been an inalienable part of its territory
for seven centuries. Many Tibetans say their land was independent
for much of that time and they seek a sovereign state under the
Dalai Lama.
</TEXT>
