<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Venezuela     03-10 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Venezuela,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charge Human Rights Abuses In Venezuelan Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International on Friday urged the
Venezuelan government to investigate reports of human rights abuses
during last week's riots over price increases and other economic
measures.
   In a telexed message to President Carlos Andres Perez, the
London-based human rights organization said that although security
forces had to confront violent unrest, that did not mitigate concern
about alleged unlawful killings of civilians and beatings of
detainees.
   Rioting and looting broke out across Venezuela Feb. 27 after
public transportation fares were increased as part of a government
auserity program. Government officials said the week of violence
left 256 people dead and thousands injured. Unofficial reports put
the casualty tolls much higher.
   The group said it had reports of people shot in their homes
during police raids. It also said anxiety was growing for the safety
of people unaccounted for since they were taken into custody.
   Amnesty called for the release of detainees held for non-violent
activities.
   The group said the alleged human rights abuses were in line with
patterns that had developed in Venezuela in recent years and which
it had described in a memorandum to the government last August.
   Amnesty International campaigns against capital punishment and
torture and for the release of non-violent political prisoners.
</TEXT>
