<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Nuclear     03-10 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Nuclear,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Attacked Over Reactor Breakdown, But Officials Say No
Danger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties on Friday said
officials were irresponsible for not shutting down a nuclear power
plant where two of four emergency cooling systems broke down.
   The Hesse state government said there were no radioactive leaks
and the local population was not in danger in the accident Thursday
at the Biblis power plant 30 miles south of Frankfurt. The plant has
a history of problems.
   The state Environment Ministry said the two cooling systems broke
down after workers tried to fix a cooling water pump. An emergency
water pump also broke down, leaving only two emergency cooling
systems working, the ministry said in a statement.
   The reactor's output was reduced, but workers repaired the
malfunctioning pump and the unit was never shut down, the ministry
said. The cause was not immediately known, it said.
   ``There was no danger for the workers or for the environment,''
said ministry spokeswoman Annette Grossbongardt. ``No radioactivity
was released.''
   But the opposition Social Democrats and Greens parties in the
Hesse state legislature accused the ministry of playing an
``irresponsible game with the safety of the populace'' by keeping
the reactor running while the cause of the malfunction was unknown.
   Ernst Welteke, a Social Democratic leader in the Hesse
legislature, said the same unit of the Biblis plant had 175 recorded
malfunctions between 1975 and 1988, according to official government
documents.
   Several Social Democrats and Greens said the plant, one of the
oldest in West Germany, should be shut down.
   In December 1987, a small amount of radioactive steam was
released from the plant into the atmosphere. The accident caused a
public outcry when it was disclosed a year later.
</TEXT>
