<FIRST>u a AM-Hatcher-Refuge     03-10 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hatcher-Refuge,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Fugitive Arrested After Soviets Reject His Plea for Political
Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive Indian wanted on 14 kidnapping
charges in North Carolina was arrested Friday by the FBI after
failing to persuade officials at the Soviet consulate to grant him
political asylum.
   The fugitive, Eddie Hatcher, was inside the consulate about three
hours before the Soviets asked him to leave, said a friend who had
accompanied him inside. At one point Hatcher sent out a handwritten
statement claiming that federal and North Carolina officials were
trying to destroy him.
   Hatcher, 31, and Timothy Jacobs, 20, held as many as 20 people
hostage in the offices of The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton,
N.C. in February 1988. The two Tuscarora Indians said they took over
the newspaper to draw attention to their claims that law enforcement
officials were involved in drug trafficking and other corruption.
   The 10-hour siege ended when Gov. Jim Martin agreed to form a
state task force to investigate their charges. The task force found
no evidence to support the claims and Martin later said they were
based on rumor and gossip.
   ``The state of N.C. and the government of the United States has
made every vindictive attempt to destroy my life, my family and my
people. They will not cease until they have accomplished this,''
said Hatcher's statement, written on a sheet of yellow legal paper.
``I see no hope in the American government, nor do I see fairness.''
   In October, a federal jury acquitted both men on federal
hostage-taking and firearms charges after a three-week trial. But a
Robeson County grand jury indicted the two Indians in December on
kidnapping charges.
   After the indictment Hatcher was arrested in Pembroke, but Jacobs
sought sanctuary at the Onondaga Indian Reservation near Syracuse,
N.Y.
   Hatcher later fled to the same reservation after his $25,000 bond
was posted by the National Council of Churches. He then left New
York and sought refuge on the Fort Hall Reservation in Idaho,
disappearing from that reservation several weeks ago after being
taken under tribal custody.
   Jacobs was arrested in New York after leaving the reservation; a
state judge is considering whether he should be extradited to North
Carolina to face the charges.
   Both men have claimed their lives would be in jeopardy if they
return to Robeson County.
   In a telephone call from the consulate to The Associated Press
bureau in Raleigh, N.C. Hatcher said he gave the Soviets documents
and news articles to support his plea for political asylum.
   Bernadette Sambrano, a member of the International Indian Treaty
Council who was with Hatcher inside the consulate, said the Soviets
rejected his request and asked him to leave. Hatcher was arrested by
FBI agents as soon as he walked off the grounds.
   Sergei Aivazion, Soviet press attache for the consulate, said he
had no comment on the incident. Chuck Latting, spokesman for the
FBI's San Francisco office, was also not immediately available for
comment, his office said.
   ``The people in the United States are always crying about human
rights violations in the Soviet Union,'' Hatcher said in the
telephone interview. ``I want them to know about the human rights
violations in this country against the Indians and the poor. ...
   ``I'm tired of being persecuted for winning the federal case,''
he said.
   Hatcher's attorney, civil rights lawyer William Kunstler, reached
by The Associated Press before Hatcher's surrender, said he had
spoken with his client at the consulate and was waiting to see what
would happen.
   ``I would urge them to give him sanctuary,'' Kunstler said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LibraryofCongress     03-10 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Library of Congress,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Department Charged With Violating Pentagon Procurement Procedures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internal investigation has uncovered
improper use of an information computer system of the Library of
Congress by some military agencies which may have tried to bypass
regular Pentagon procurement procedures in awarding research
contracts, Librarian James H. Billington said Friday.
   Billington said the Library had ordered the Federal Library and
Information Network (FEDLINK) to cancel the contracts or transfer
them to the proper Pentagon authorities.
   Under Library of Congress jurisdiction, FEDLINK administers
information and library services contracts on behalf of member
libraries and information centers in order to get the best possible
price for the government. The services are open to any federal
agency.
   FEDLINK has grown since 1976 to become the nation's largest
provider of automated library network services, according to
Billington. It gives government libraries and other government
participants access to hundreds of databases and to many new
information technologies.
   During the investigation which began in January, it was learned
that FEDLINK had been signing contracts for services which had
nothing to do with libraries or information databases, according to
the Library's inspector general, John W. Rensbarger.
   He said various contractors were to provide services which
included ``an analysis, assessments and independent appraisals of
the Navy's AH-lW Night Targeting System,'' ``development of a
standard Missile-2 Security Plan,'' and ``support of the Army
Machine Gun Program.''
   By using FEDLINK's contracting services, procurement officers at
several U.S. military installations, such as the Navy's Charleston,
S.C., shipyard and the Air Force's Seventh Communications Group in
Washington, D.C., apparently bypassed special Pentagon rules on
competitive bidding and other procurement procedures, said
Rensbarger.
   He said the questionable contracts involved orders from various
Army, Navy and Air Force units totalling some $45 million last
fiscal year. Total FEDLINK activities in the fiscal year which ended
Sept. 30 involved contracts for $97.1 million with 135 vendors to
provide services for some 1,395 different federal entities,
according to the Library.
   ``We still do not know why these inappropriate contracts were
made,'' said Rensbarger. ``Our investigation and that of the Defense
Department are continuing.''
   A Pentagon spokeswoman had no immediate comment on the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
