<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-PoisonGas 1stLd-Writethru a0763 03-10 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Poison Gas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian President Mubarak Denies Chemical Arms Plant Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT graf after 4th, `The New...' with U.S. comment. Pick
up 5th pvs, `Washington has accused...' ADDS 4 grafs with Redman statement.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt denied
on Friday that his country is assembling Swiss-made parts that could
be used to create a chemical weapons plant at Abu Zaabal, north of
Cairo.
   ``This is the first I've heard of it,'' Mubarak told reporters.
   ``We are against chemical weapons and, of course, don't make any
such factories. We don't back the idea of such factories or even
nuclear ones.''
   The New York Times said Friday that U.S. officials believe Egypt
is assembling Swiss-made parts that could be used to build a
chemical arms plant.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington the
United States opposes all weapons of mass destruction _ chemical,
biological and nuclear _ and has raised the issue with Egypt.
   Washington has accused Libya, the radical North African nation
bordering Egypt, of building a plant capable of producing poison gas
at Rabta, about 60 miles north of the Libyan capital of Tripoli.
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi has replied, ``This is a medical
plant.''
   Mubarak spoke Friday after he met with senior European Economic
Community officials, including EEC Commission President Jacques
Delors, as part of a European tour to win support for an
international Middle East peace conference which Israel opposes.
   Mubarak also discussed his economic reform program at the EEC
head office.
   The Swiss engineering company Krebs A.G. said Friday it has cut
its business links with a military-industrial complex in Egypt that
reportedly planned to build the poison gas plant.
   Krebs said it believed the parts it shipped to Egypt would be
used to produce pharmaceuticals. Krebs' president, Hans Rudolf
Weber, told The Associated Press on Friday that the company severed
its business relationship with the Egyptian complex on advice of the
Swiss government. He would not elaborate.
   The New York Times report said Krebs delivered to Egypt parts
that will be installed in the plant, which it said is part of a
military-industrial complex that is also scheduled to include a
joint Egyptian-American plant for assembling the M-1 tank.
   Mohammed Wahby, a spokesman for Egypt's Embassy in Washington,
denied the report earlier. ``We are not involved in the manufacture
of chemical weapons,'' the Times quoted him as saying.
   The Times quoted an unidentified U.S. official as saying Bush
administration efforts to stop proliferation of chemical weapons
applies to all countries and not just those which have had hostile
relations with America.
   The newspaper quoted another U.S. official as saying Washington
recently told Cairo it was concerned about the project.
   Redman said the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction ``in
areas of instability such as the Middle East is a particular
concern'' and the United States has urged ``all states in the region
to forgo the development and acquisition of all such weapons.''
   He said the issue has been raised with Egypt but gave no details.
   ``In the case of Egypt, we consult frequently and closely on
these kind of subjects,'' Redman said. ``The Krebs-Egyptian project
again illustrates the difficulties of controlling production
technologies that have dual uses, both legitimate civilian uses and
potential chemical weapons uses.
   ``We have been in touch on this particular issue with the Swiss
government for some time. The attitude of the Swiss government has
been serious and responsible.''
</TEXT>
