<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     03-10 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Head: Doctrine Of Limited Sovereignty Is Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's new president of Parliament
said Friday the ``Brezhnev Doctrine'' of limited sovereignty for
Soviet allies is dead.
   Also Friday, the official MTI news agency reported the ruling
Communist Party has committed itself to reforms that include free
elections in a multiple-party system, representative democracy and a
free press. The party also expressed willingness to form a coalition
government.
   Matyas Szyeroes, elected president of the body Friday, told a
news conference that Hungary must never be servile and accept advice
that would erode its independence.
   ``In Hungarian-Soviet relations, the `Brezhnev Doctrine' is
already dead,'' said Szueroes, the Communist Party Central
Committee's secretary in charge of foreign affairs.
   The ``Brezhnev Doctrine'' permits military intervention in a
Soviet bloc country in the event of a liberal insurrection. The late
President Leonid I. Brezhnev announced it after the Red Arnmy
crushed the liberal ``Prague Spring'' of 1968 in Czechoslovakia.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III this week urged Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to renounce the doctrine.
   ``Those in the East should be free of the fear that armed Soviet
intervention, justified by the `Brezhnev Doctrine,' would be used
again to deny them choice,'' Baker said in a speech in Vienna on
Monday.
   In an interview published in the Magyar Nemzet daily on March 4,
Szueroes said Soviet-Hungarian relations did not develop over the
years ``in the spirit of equal rights and mutual benefits.''
   ``The `Brezhnev Doctrine' caused a further deformation,
accompanied by greater power aspects on the one side, and a kind of
servility on the other, as well as insistence on certain dogmas
until the mid-1980s,'' he said.
   Those comments and others Szueroes made in a radio interview
indicated criticism of the Hungarian leadership under party chief
Janos Kadar, who was replaced by Karoly Grosz in May.
   On Friday, Szueroes said: ``Even at the time of the `Brezhnev
Doctrine,' a lot depended on the leadership of the small countries,
whether they subjected themselves to it or tried to serve more
consistently the interests of their own country.''
   He also reiterated an earlier statement that in the future
Hungary could adopt a neutral foreign policy.
   In an action program published Friday, the policy-making Central
Committee said it supports ``representative democracy'' and an
independent judiciary, free elections and open politics based on the
constitution.
   It also expressed willingness to consider ``the possibility of
coalition in governing.''
   Other pledges in the document, adopted Tuesday and carried Friday
the MTI news agency, included independent trade unions and interest
groups, free creative and intellectual work, freedom of conscience
and religion, individual rights and administration free of
corruption.
   The document said the reforms could be preserved by legal
guarantees, openenness and a ``reponsible, free press.''
   The document also mentioned ``mistakes'' by the Communist
leadership under Kadar, who gained power after Soviet troops crushed
the Hungarian uprising of 1956.
   In emphasizing the need for reform, the Central Committee said
the current economic and political structure was ``full of
mistakes.''
   Last month, the leadership said it would accept a new
constitution that omits references to the party's leading role and
endorses the development of a pluralistic society.
   Hungary has embarked on an ambitious reform program. Parliament
approved a set of draft principles this week that Justice Ministry
officials said would guarantee a multiparty system and separation of
powers.
   In another development Friday, Interior Minister Istvan Horvath
outlined a program to deal with the continuing influx of refugees
from neighboring Romania. He said Romania continued to discriminate
against minorities, many of whom are ethnic Hungarians.
   Horvath said Romania approved 1,936 emigration requests last
year, more than double the number in 1987. He said the government
plans to set up refugee stations to process residency requests.
</TEXT>
