<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HeartDonor     03-10 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heart Donor,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father of Heart Recipient Describes Family Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATTERSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a teen-ager who died
unexpectedly three years after receiving the transplanted heart of
her would-be boyfriend said Thursday he knows now what the donor's
family went through.
   ``When you walk in and see your daughter dead, it hurts bad,''
said Raymond Ashlock on the eve of the funeral of his daughter,
Donna.
   Donna, who would have been 18 on April 1, had turned down her
father's telephone invitation to go to lunch at 11:20 a.m., he said.
When Ashlock came home at noon, he found her dead in bed with the
phone next to her.
   ``It was a shock,'' Ashlock said. ``There were no signs of her
being sick.'' He noted she had been hospitalized with a flulike
illness three or four weeks ago ``but snapped right out of it.''
   Hospital officials said that the death apparently occurred during
a nap as a result of irregular beating of the heart, a common
complication in heart transplants. Donna had experienced some
rejection of the heart, and had been scheduled for a second
transplant.
   Ashlock said his daughter would not have lived the past three
years without the heart she received from a high school classmate
and admirer, Felipe Garza. ``I thought I knew what the Garzas went
through three years ago, but I didn't,'' the red-eyed father said.
Ashlock said Felipe's parents came to his home to offer condolences
hours after Donna's death.
   Felipe, who had a crush on Donna, suddenly collapsed and died of
a brain hemorrhage on Jan. 4, 1986. Although he wasn't sick, he had
suffered blackouts and had mentioned that he wanted Donna to have
his heart if he died. Her original heart had been irreparably
damaged by a virus.
   The story was widely publicized, and Donna got to meet President
Reagan and singer Michael Jackson, and was the honored guest at an
American Heart Association Valentine's Day dance.
   Donna returned to high school in this Central California farming
town 75 miles southeast of San Francisco and resumed as normal a
life as possible, considering her sudden fame, heart medication and
frequent trips to San Francisco for medical care.
   Ashlock said Donna will be buried Friday in a pink casket
decorated with roses identical to one she liked at the recent
funeral of a family friend.
   ``She said, `if I die, I want to be buried like that,''' Ashlock
said.
</TEXT>
