<FIRST>r a AM-HeartDonor     03-10 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heart Donor,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Who Received Donated Heart from Classmate is Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATTERSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who had received the heart
of a high school admirer in a 1986 transplant operation was
remembered at her funeral Friday as ``truly a profile in courage.''
   Before a crowd of 500 that oveflowed the church and stretched for
a full block down the sidewalk, the Rev. Paul Fliflet praised
17-year-old Donna Ashlock's courage and strength and thanked God
``for the impact she has made on many other people's lives.''
   The Assembly of God pastor also saluted Donna's parents for their
fortitude since their daughter received a transplanted heart in
January 1986 from a high school classmate, Felipe Garza.
   ``For three years, Mary and Ray Ashlock lived from crisis to
crisis,'' the minister said. ``To see the devotion they had for this
daughter would touch anyone's heart.''
   Donna gained national celebrity because of the uniqueness of her
heart transplant. Felipe, who had had a crush on her, told his
family that if he should die he wanted his heart to go to Donna, who
needed a new heart because hers was irreversibly damaged by a virus.
   Even though he had not been ill, Felipe collapsed on Jan. 4,
1986, and died of a cerebral hemhorrage. The size of his heart and
his tissue type were a good match for Donna, and his heart was
placed in her body.
   But Donna's body kept trying to reject her donated heart, leading
to her death Tuesday.
   She was buried in the same cemetery where Felipe is interred.
   At the funeral, many of Donna's friends at Patterson High School
wore pink ribbons as armbands. Those who could not fit inside the
church listened to the service broadcast over a loudspeaker.
</TEXT>
