<HEAD>Small Tourist Plane Crashes in Lima, 10 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small air taxi frequently used by tourists
crashed into a two-story building in a Lima suburb Friday during
foggy weather, killing all 10 people on board, officials said.
   There were no immediate reports of people hurt or killed on the
ground.
   The official from the Aerocondor company said the plane was
returning from flying over the famous Nazca lines, 250 miles
southeast of Lima, when it crashed. The Nazca lines are pre-Hispanic
drawings in the desert believed to represent a primitive calendar.
   The Aerocondor official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said in an interview from the crash site that the pilot, co-pilot
and all eight passengers on board had died.
   He said he did not have the identities of the passengers, but a
police official said they included foreigners. Both officials spoke
in interviews broadcast on Radioprogramas, Peru's leading radio news
station.
