<FIRST>u a AM-Vincennes-Base     03-10 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Base,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Constant Concern in Nation's Biggest Navy Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vincennes-Bomb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military security is paramount here, the home of
the nation's largest Navy complex with 12 major facilities including
a submarine base, two air stations and a vast Marine Corps base.
   ``San Diego is a big Navy town. It (security) is a big concern
for us and a big concern for the Navy,'' police Sgt. Dave Douglas
said Friday.
   Security was tightened Friday following a bomb attack on a van
driven by the wife of Capt. Will Rogers III, the USS Vincennes
commander who directed the attack that mistakenly downed an Iranian
airliner.
   ``We don't discuss security. We just say it's an increase in
security measures,'' said Navy Chief Craig Huebler, spokesman for
the Naval Base San Diego. ``Increased, heightened awareness.''
   No special measures were imposed in October when the Vincennes
returned from its deployment in the Persian Gulf, he said. The ship
was protecting oil and merchant shipping from crossfire of the
Iran-Iraq war.
   ``We had no special security arrangments made at the time, nor
have there been any special security arrangements made with anybody
aboard the ship or their families,'' Huebler said.
   There also is no record of any threats being made against Rogers,
his family or any other crewmember of the Vincennes, he said.
   State Rep. Bill Lowery, a Rogers family friend, said the captain
said Friday that he hadn't expected to be vulnerable in San Diego,
the nation's sixth-largest city known as much as a sunny vacation
spot as a military town.
   Rogers said those stationed abroad certainly realize they're at
peril, Lowery said. But ``no one expects you have to be worrying
about your wives and kids back home,'' Lowery quoted Rogers as
saying.
   Rogers and wife were being protected, as was their son, who is
attending school in Colorado, officials said. The couple had been
living in the La Jolla area as Rogers awaited his next assignment.
   FBI and Naval Investigative Services agents, police and
bomb-sniffing dogs made a sweep of the Rogers' home and neighborhood
Friday after the explosion.
   Huebler said a decision on further security measures would depend
on what is discovered by the FBI, which is conducting the
investigation into the bombing. Protecting off-base personnel
presents difficulties, Huebler added.
   ``You're talking about ... a family living out in the San Diego
community, and when you're living in that environment there's not a
great deal that you can do on a regular basis,'' he said.
   There are 141,000 sailors and Marines in the San Diego area,
including the Camp Pendleton Marine Corps Base. Because of the
number of personnel, combined with the total acreage of Navy and
Marine facilities, it is commonly considered the nation's largest
Navy complex, Huebler said.
   The Marine Corps is under the direction of the Secretary of the
Navy.
   Large-scale security exercises are held annually in San Diego,
and all of the bases go through their own security exercises
annually, Huebler said. ``There have not been any major breaches of
security in San Diego,'' he said.
</TEXT>
