<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     03-10 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Peacekeepers Arrive in Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILLY PADDOCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Nations peacekeepers began
arriving Friday to monitor the territory's transition to
independence.
   Twenty-four officers from the Finnish and Danish armies were the
first peacekeepers to arrive. They were joined by U.N.
administrative personnel from Poland, Canada, Spain, Italy and other
countries.
   A 70-man British army signals unit also flew to Namibia to
provide communications for the multinational force.
   The U.N.-approved independence process in Namibia officially
begins April 1, but a large portion of the 4,650-member peacekeeping
force is expected to arrive before then. The South
African-controlled territorial army is scheduled to leave by April
30.
   South Africa has administered Namibia since World War I but
agreed last year to grant independence as part of a regional peace
accord which also calls for the phased withdrawal of Cuban troops
from Angola.
   The largest components of the peacekeeping force will be
battalions from Finland, Malaysia and Kenya. Col. Hanno Paronen,
leader of the Finnish contingent that arrived Friday, said the Finns
would be based in Caprivi, a narrow strip of land in the
northeastern corner of Namibia.
   The peacekeepers will monitor voting scheduled for early November
to elect an assembly that will draft a constitution for an
independent Namibia.
   The South-West African People's Organization, which has waged a
guerrilla war against South African rule since 1966, is favored to
win. But it may have difficulty collecting the two-thirds' support
needed for complete control of the assembly.
   Two groups of Australians are due in Windhoek by Sunday,
according to Maj. John Hutchings, an Australian officer who serves
as a U.N. military consultant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
