<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-EasterSeriesII Adv23   03-10 1182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Easter Series II, Adv 23,1217</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs, March 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Military and Jesus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: The Execution Detail</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is the second part of a three-story Easter
series about Jesus and the role of the military in his arrest and
crucifixion, based on Scripture, historical sources and ancient
non-canonical Christian writings.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly before dawn, the centurion Longinus began buckling on his
gear. A courier had brought word of an early morning execution. It
smelled of a rush job, apparently timed before the fractious holiday
crowds clogged the streets.
   Some sort of trial was already nearing its conclusion in the
governor's atrium at the fort. The prisoner, Jesus, a hill-country
Jew who captivated the multitudes, had been arrested by a Roman
patrol only last midnight.
   Longinus had been tapped to finish the business. An orderly
fastened the padded bronze greaves around his lower legs and
tightened the thongs holding the protective leather cuirass on his
chest.
   He slipped on the felt-cushioned bronze shoulder pieces, called
``heart guards,'' and drew on his helmet, with its lined cheek
pieces, hinged visor and decorative crest.
   His name isn't specified in Scripture, but ancient writings
identify him as Longinus. Scripture makes clear that his role in
Jesus' final hours keenly troubled him.
   But for the moment, it only seemed puzzling that the military
governor, Pontius Pilate, would be conducting a trial at such an
early hour, after the prisoner had been shuffled about through the
night among Pilate; the high priest, Caiaphas; the Galilean puppet,
Herod, and now Pilate again.
   Longinus had heard reports of the stir this fellow Jesus caused,
the throngs he attracted. His popularity with ordinary people left
both local and Roman authorities apprehensive about how to curb him.
``They feared the people,'' Scripture says. ``They did not find
anything they could do, for all the people hung upon his words.''
   But Pilate, a master of ruthless artifice, and Caiaphas, his
tractable, Rome-sanctioned high priest, had maneuvered to avoid a
public outcry by acting between midnight and the edge of day.
   Longinus recalled the scene a week ago when the Galilean rode
into the city to cheers of an ecstatic throng. ``Hosanna!' they
cried, meaning ``Save us!'' They waved leafy branches, spreading
fronds and garments in front of him.
   ``Son of David! Blessed be he who comes in the name of the Lord,
even the King of Israel! Hosanna in the highest!''
   Next day, Roman sentries in turrets of the fort overlooking the
temple square had watched Jesus' onslaught on the commerce there,
swinging a braided whip, overturning money-changing tables and
merchants' booths, driving out dealers, tourists and guards alike.
   ``My house shall be called a house of prayer, but you have made
it a den of robbers,'' he thundered.
   Longinus directed a sergeant to turn out a six-man detail in
front of the guardhouse. Before heading there himself, he nibbled
some figs and a chunk of honeyed bread.
   Centurions were career officers, the backbone of the Roman army.
Senior centurions commanded centuries of l00 men, each with 10
maniples, or squads.
   Under the legionary tribunes in charge of 600-man cohorts, the
centurions were responsibile for discipline, drill, inspections,
quartermaster supplies and operations. Efficiency of the Roman
legions depended on them.
   The Roman historian Polybius wrote:
   ``Centurions are required not to be bold and adventurous so much
as good leaders of steady and prudent mind, not prone to take the
offensive or start fighting wantonly, but able when overwhelmed and
hard-pressed to stand fast and die at their posts.''
   Scholars believe four Roman legions were stationed in the
Judean-Galilean province at that time, the 3rd, 6th, 10th and 12th,
each with about 6,000 men at full strength. Each legion included a
cavalry wing, siege weapons, camels for carrying supplies, slingers,
archers and other infantry soldiers. Most were mercenary auxiliaries
recruited from Thrace, Syria, Gaul, Germany and other imperial
provinces.
   Pilate kept the bulk of his forces at his headquarters in the
coastal city of Caesarea. But he regularly brought reinforcement to
Jerusalem for the Jewish Passover, when the annual influx of
pilgrims turned the city into a tinder-box of turmoil and clamor
against the colonial yoke.
   Longinus left his quarters and strode to the guardhouse where his
detail loitered with their legionary ensign, crucifixion tools and
spears, the iron points topping wooden shafts.
   The sound of a flogging floated out from the guardroom, the crack
of the bone-tipped flagellum mingling with the whoops of soldiers as
they roughed up a prisoner, taunting him as king, slapping him about.
   Shortly, three condemned culprits were jostled into the yard, one
of them, Jesus, badly mauled, lacerated and bleeding, a circle of
thorns jammed on his head.
   Longinus winced, but his martial demeanor returned automatically.
He was a professional. An adjutant brought from Pilate's chambers
the execution tags to be hung around the prisoners' necks.
   Two of them were simply stamped ``thief,'' but the third verdict,
for treason, was written out in Pilate's scrawl for Jesus, ``King of
the Jews.''
   Pilate as procurator held the ``jus gladii,'' full powers of
criminal justice. Only he in this restive province could impose
capital punishment. He did so regularly, a common fate for resistant
Jews. For a quarter century, their landscape had been spiny with
crosses.
   Longinus aligned his detail with the prisoners, each carrying a
heavy crossbeam, and moved them off through the Jerusalem streets.
Onlookers trailed the procession, shoving, gawking curiously, as
temple subordinates scoffed and some women wept over the maimed,
weakened Jesus.
   He kept falling under the heavy beam, and Longinus brusquely
conscripted a muscular African onlooker to carry it.
   When they reached the execution site, Golgotha, ``Place of the
Skulls,'' it was still early, only the third hour, 9 a.m., says the
earliest account in Mark. The prisoners were bound to the
crossbeams, thick nails pounded through their wrists. Once the beams
were hoisted by pulleys to the uprights, the convicts' feet were
nailed to the posts.
   The tortuous ordeal stretched on: the shooting bursts of pain,
the convulsions, the straining upward to breathe, the massive
cramps, the writhing limbs. The temple claque jeered, women sobbed,
the thieves screamed and raved. Jesus exhibited stoic grit:
``Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do.''
   At the foot of the cross, soldiers threw dice for Jesus' robe.
Longinus allowed it. It was a Roman rule: to the executioner
belonged the ``spoila.''
   At noon, the sky darkened, thunder crashed and a shuddering
earthquake rent the ground. The overcast continued until the ninth
hour when Jesus cried loudly, ``Father, into thy hands I commit my
spirit!''
   He had died in only six hours. Usually, crucifixion took about
l2. A spearman ran him through to make sure he was dead.
   Longinus looked up at him as the sun broke through and a bird
chirped.
   ``Certainly this man was innocent,'' he murmured. ``Truly this
man was a son of God!''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NEXT: The Tomb Sentries</NOTE>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, March 23</NOTE>
