<FIRST>a i PM-ForgottenRefugees Adv17   03-10 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forgotten Refugees, Adv 17,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs March 17 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Forgotten Refugees: The Thousands Who Fled Caucasus Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weeks before a killer earthquake tore
down the homes of a half-million Armenians, the Soviet Caucasus was
already shaken by a tragedy that has left 300,000 other people
without places to live or work.
   Its cause was the distrust and dislike of one people of another.
   First by the hundreds, then by the thousands, Armenians and
Azerbaijanis fled their homes in fear they might become the next
victims.
   The Soviet government appeals to them to return home, but for
many, the fear remains.
   ``I consider that it's better to die here in Yerevan than to try
to live there,'' said Gena Agabekyan, an ethnic Armenian who fled
Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, three months ago.
   Strife between the predominantly Moslem Azerbaijanis and mostly
Christian Armenians broke into the open in February 1988 in a
dispute over the Nagorno-Karabakh district of Azerbaijan.
   Armenians, who make up the majority of the district's population,
complained of discrimination under Azerbaijani control, and demanded
annexation with the Armenian republic.
   Violence flared throughout 1988, and 91 people were killed, most
of them in November. That's when the exodus began from both
republics.
   To date, about 141,000 Azerbaijanis have fled Armenia, and
159,000 Armenians have left Azerbaijan, the Soviet Interior Ministry
says.
   The refugees have been all but forgotten in the aftermath of the
Dec. 7 earthquake that killed 25,000 people and left much of
northwestern Armenia in ruins. No international aid has poured in
for the refugees, as it did for earthquake victims, and little help
comes from within the Soviet Union.
   In an attempt to cool tempers in the Caucasus, the name for the
general area between the Black and Caspian seas, and to snuff out
the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute, the Kremlin has placed the region
under its direct control. It has announced plans to pump millions of
rubles into the district to improve schools, services and even
upgrade television broadcasting in the Armenian language.
   But officials acknowledge that they are overwhelmed by the double
tragedies of ethnic flight and earthquake.
   ``If there hadn't been an earthquake, we would have settled
everyone long ago, and everything would be normal,'' Yuri
Khodzhamiryan, a deputy Armenian premier, told a recent news
conference.
   As it did for quake victims, Armenia's government set up a
commission to help resettle refugees. They receive a one-time
payment of 100 rubles ($160) each and have been offered jobs in
rural areas.
   Early on, the Soviet press trumpeted the return of a handful of
refugees to their homes, clearly trying to encourage others to
follow suit. But officials say fewer than a sixth of the refugees
have returned home.
   Meanwhile, those waiting for new jobs and homes are getting
restless.
   Despite a ban on public gatherings, the refugees have massed
regularly on Lenin Square in downtown Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
   On one recent afternoon, Gena Agabekyan and 100 other refugees
complained outside the State Agriculture Committee offices that the
government was refusing to give them jobs or homes.
   Agabekyan, 50, said he was left without a job when he was fired
as a crane operator for the state-run Azerbaijan Film Committee in
Baku ``because I am an Armenian.''
   Even government officials, who usually claim that interethnic
brotherhood prevails in the Soviet Union, acknowledge that the
hostility felt by the neighboring Caucasus peoples for each other
was behind the refugee wave.
   ``People were driven out only because they were of different
nationality,'' Arkady Volsky, the head of a new governing committee
in Nagorno-Karabakh, told the defense newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda.
   Yerevan, a city of 1.2 million people, has become a magnet for
both refugees and people made homeless by the earthquake.
   The Armenian Land Use Institute has set up a refugee placement
center in the city. Its deputy director, Telemak Mutafyan, said
there is no shortage of jobs or housing in Armenia but many refugees
are not willing to adjust to new conditions.
   ``Azerbaijanis left rural areas here, and Armenians come to us
from Baku and Kirovabad and other Azerbaijani cities,'' Mutafyan
said. ``A city man adjusts with great difficulty to a village.''
   Many refugees are staying with relatives in Yerevan, but others
have settled on their own in buildings condemned as unsafe,
according to Mutafyan.
   Ironically, the earthquake may have a silver lining for some
refugees. The Kremlin has ordered that the devastated area be
rebuilt in two years, and thousands of construction workers are
needed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 17</NOTE>
