<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv10   03-10 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 10,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Friday, March 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Industry Optimistic About Farm Economy Rebound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite last summer's disastrous
drought, tractor dealer Chuck German says the U.S. agricultural
economy is poised for recovery and growth thanks to lessons learned
in the decade-long crisis that gripped the farm belt.
   But German doubts manufacturers' bullish forecasts for strong
sales of tractors, combines and farm implements. He doesn't see a
quick fix, but a gradual improvement largely dependent upon
cooperation from Mother Nature.
   German, 52, is president of German Implement Co. of Princeville,
a community of 1,700 about 20 miles north of Peoria. His experiences
the past 10 years are common among people who sell tractors.
   ``Our last good year was 1979,'' German said. ``Things started
going downhill in 1980 and they really hit a low ebb in 1984. Our
volume that year was half of our 1979 volume.''
   In 1981, German laid off 25 percent of his employees
indefinitely, saying ``it's sad, but it's been a matter of survival
and waiting for things to pick back up.''
   Like most experts, German thought the farming industry was ripe
for recovery last spring as tractor and combine sales started
picking up. But sales eased quickly in the drought that parched the
Midwest.
   Instead, German watched the drought claim three neighborhing farm
equipment dealers. Illinois has lost 1,500 dealers since 1949,
according to the Illinois Retail Farm Equipment Association.
   German survived but had to cut expenses again, just as he did at
the start of the decade when the farm economy soured.
   Now, German said his manufacturers _ Ford Motor Co. and Japan's
Kubota Ltd. _ are telling him to expect big demand in 1989.
   While he agrees farmers need to replace aging equipment, German
doesn't expect any activity in his showroom, which his father opened
in 1940, unless rain falls more regularly than last year.
   ``Farmers are conservative and waiting for moisture,'' he said.
``That's the big factor. My manufacturers are enthusiastic but I'm
not.''
   That's because the farmers who survived the farm crisis are
astute money managers who think long and hard before spending on
average $60,000 for a tractor and $110,000 for a combine, he said.
   Manufacturers, like Deere &amp; Co. of Moline, are upbeat about 1989
prospects. That's partly because Deere enjoyed record earnings last
year of $315 million despite the drought, which produced the worst
year of tractor and combine sales industry-wide since records were
first kept in 1963.
   Deere flourished in the drought by cutting costs, entering joint
ventures with foreign companies and expanding its product line _
especially in the lucrative lawn and garden market.
   The company's diverse array of insurance and financial services
also helped the bottom line.
   Officials at Ford's agricultural machinery unit in New Holland,
Pa., are equally upbeat, claiming they were ``solidly in the black
in 1988 and looking at some good years ahead.'' They decline to
release earnings or sales figures.
   Ford spokesman Gene Hemphill said the company wasn't hurt by the
drought as badly as others because it does not have a high
concentration of dealers in the Midwest, which suffered most from
the drought.
   Case IH of Racine, Wis., was not as lucky as Ford and suffered a
$95 million loss in 1988 on the heels of a $253 million loss in
1987. The company hasn't shown a profit since 1981 but officials
think prospects have improved.
   The company remains bullish about the agricultural equipment
market, said Vickie L. Rickey, Case IH vice president.
   Other signs of an agricultural rebound include low stockpiles of
grain and higher commodity prices, said Emmett Barker, president of
the Farm and Industrial Equipment Institute in Chicago, an
industry-supported think tank.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs March 10.</NOTE>
