<FIRST>a i AM-Italy-Drought Adv13 1stLd-Writethru 03-10 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Drought, Adv 13, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0487,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, March 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Italian Drought Means Higher Prices for Some Foods but Not Pasta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds, CORRECTS spelling of durum in 4th graf ``Italians ... wheat''
and in 20th graf ``Normally ... 10 tons.'' ^By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSETO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of nothing but sunshine and
blue skies, rains finally are falling on Italy's parched croplands.
   Some areas had not seen rain in 80 days. In others the rainfall
in the last five months was less than half the average.
   But the new rains may be too late. It will take months to
determine what the drought has done to the wheat crop, fruit and
olive orchards, vineyards, citrus groves and vegetable farms.
   Italians already know it will mean higher prices for some foods
and possibly even for their bottle of wine. However, they may be
saved higher costs for their pasta, which is made from durum wheat.
   ``While until a month ago we were very concerned about the
effects of the drought on the recent harvest, the recent rains have
pretty much calmed our fears,'' said Albino Ganapini, a spokesman
for Barilla, Italy's largest pasta producer. ``If the rainy season
continues normally, as meteorologists are predicting, then we will
have a normal harvest.''
   He said the planting had been increased by 4 percent this year
and noted that Italy normally imports about 25 percent of the wheat
it uses for pasta anyway.
   But farm groups say the drought will mean higher prices for
fruits and vegetables. Producers say the retail price of artichokes,
one of the most popular Italian vegetables, could triple from the
current average price of 900 lire (67 cents) apiece.
   Growers say fruit, olive and citrus trees will produce less this
year because of the drought, which also is expected to diminish the
grape harvest, bringing the prospect of higher prices for wine.
   For some farmers this is the third bad year in the last five of
poor harvests.
   ``I've never seen a drought like this,'' said Alfio Pieraccini,
who has farmed for 50 years on this fertile plain that stretches
toward the Tyrrhenian Sea from the foot of the Tuscan hills.
   Pieraccini said it was too late to recover the cost of planting.
   Agriculture Minister Calogero Mannino recently told a Senate
committee the ministry cannot yet realistically evaluate the damage,
which varies widely from region to region.
   Earlier, the ministry released a preliminary estimate of $1.5
billion. But it said the amount of rain over the next few months
could drastically alter the picture.
   Giuseppe Avolio, the president of the Italian Confederation of
Farmers, said the damage could reach $7.4 billion.
   So far the government has declared only Sardinia a disaster area.
The island has had below average rainfalls for three years and
despite some recent rain, the situation there is still grave. Its
barren fields are unable to support sheep and goats that represent a
third of Italy's herd.
   About 5,000 farmers demonstrated recently in Cagliari, Sardinia's
capital, to demand that the government provide more drought relief
funds.
   The regional government estimates damage in Sardinia alone at a
half billion dollars or more.
   But despite the recent rains, Agriculture Minister Mannino said
other regions in Italy could still be declared disaster areas. The
drought has withered crops from Lombardy in the north to Sicily in
the south.
   Regional officials in Lombardy say the drought might destroy 30
percent of the crops in the region known as one of the most fertile
in Europe.
   Normally the fields on the Pianura di Grosseto, the wide plain in
southern coastal Tuscany, are green with durum wheat by February.
The harvests usually average 40 to 50 metric tons an acre, but this
year farmers expect the average will be no more than 10 tons.
   Farmer Pieraccini of Grosseto, still active at 76, takes his
troubles in stride.
   In 1985 he suffered because of a killer frost that destroyed
olive, fruit and citrus trees as far south as Sicily. Last year,
heavy rain washed away 40 percent of his crop. This winter, at least
70 percent of his wheat has died.
   ``What happens, happens,'' he shrugs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 13</NOTE>
