<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-HousingRestrictions Adv12-1stLd-Writethru b0653 03-10
1061</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Housing Restrictions, Adv 12-1st Ld-Writethru, b0653,1084</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12 ^For Release Sunday, March 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Planning: Zoning Boards Decide Who Can Constitute a Household</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to recast.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-No Children, moved as b0646</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   People living in ``families'' that don't conform to the age-old
concept of Mom, Dad and the kids are locked in battles in a number
of communities where personal freedom is pitted against the desire
to control who lives next door.
   In some of Denver's most exclusive neighborhoods, for example,
unmarried people can't legally live together under a ``living in
sin'' zoning code. In Poughkeepsie, N.Y., four or more people can't
live in the same rental dwelling if they're not of the same family.
And in Chicago, eight couples in a public housing project got
married late last year to avoid eviction.
   Many communities have laws restricting housing according to
varying definitions of what constitutes a family. The reasons range
from preserving ``quality of life'' in the face of an influx of
outsiders, to cutting backlogs of people waiting to get into public
housing, to fighting drugs.
   Supporters of Denver's 30-year-old code say it encourages strong
family-oriented neighborhoods. ``We should stand up and say we stand
for families and traditional values,'' said City Councilman Ted
Hackworth.
   ``I just do not think it's appropriate for the city to regulate
whether you are married any more than we should regulate whether you
go to church,'' said Councilwoman Cathy Reynolds, who has fought for
13 years to repeal the law.
   Elinor Lewallen, whose neighborhood is covered by the ordinance,
said she opposed it because if her husband were to die, she would be
barred from seeking a live-in companion so she could continue living
in her home.
   The City Council is scheduled to vote on the matter March 27.
   Poughkeepsie, in its ordinance passed last month to keep college
students from overcrowding apartments, defined ``family'' as a group
which ``in theory, size, appearance, structure and function
resembles a traditional family unit,'' cooking together and sharing
expenses.
   ``The local newspapers got it a little confused. They said it
meant that Kate and Allie wouldn't be able to live together, but
that's not right,'' said City Clerk Patricia Havens. ``Kate and
Allie'' is a CBS-TV show in which two divorced women and their three
children share an apartment.
   Delray Beach, Fla., approved an ordinance last August allowing
only one person outside of the immediate ``family'' _ defined as
parents and children _ to live with a family in a single-family
home. City officials say it is meant to curb overcrowding that can
lead to increased garbage and noise, traffic congestion, and health
and safety problems in neighborhoods.
   As of last month, officials had cited 11 homes _ all owned by
Haitians.
   The American Civil Liberties Union of Florida is deciding on a
challenge, said attorney Jim K. Green of the Palm Beach County
chapter of the ACLU.
   Tamarac, Fla., officials temporarily tabled a similar ordinance
after the ACLU threatened action. The proposal said no more than
three unrelated people, and no more than five foster children, could
live in a single-family home.
   ``We're creating a recipe for more homelessness,'' said Broward
County ACLU attorney Larry Corman.
   Many housing authorities prohibit unwed couples in public housing.
   In Woonsocket, R.I., Dana Dagnese and Susan Arsenau, who have
lived together for six years and are expecting their third child,
filed a lawsuit in January alleging that the Woonsocket Housing
Authority violated their rights to ``freedom of association, family
privacy and equal protection of laws'' by denying them emergency
housing.
   U.S. District Judge Ronald R. Lagueux refused last month to issue
a preliminary injunction, saying, ``Here is a couple in an illicit
relationship who are creating children for the welfare rolls, where
others who qualify for housing are shunted aside.'' No trial date
has been set.
   The Chicago Housing Authority banned overnight guests in the
Rockwell Gardens project after a September police raid to combat
gang violence. That meant eight women could not allow their live-in
boyfriends to stay with them without a trip to the altar. The 16
residents _ including one couple with seven children _ were married
en masse in Novemeber.
   In Massachusetts, three couples filed a lawsuit five years ago
charging they were illegally barred from public housing in Worcester
because they were unmarried. State law prohibits discrimination on
the basis of marital status.
   The Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination ruled in
their favor, the Worcester Superior Court upheld that ruling, and
the case is pending before the Massachusetts Appeals Court. The
housing authority contends the law applies to individuals _ for
example, a divorced woman with children _ not couples.
   ``To open up public housing slots to unmarried couples ... would
create such an enormous strain on a system which is already so badly
burdened,'' said Housing Authority attorney Michael Clancy.
   In West Hollywood, Calif., the nation's first city with a gay
majority of city officials, a 1985 domestic partnership ordinance
gives unmarried couples the same rights as married couples.
   ``If you have a domestic partner, you can't be evicted if you
have someone living with you,'' said Deputy City Clerk Vivian
Vukojevich. ``It can be a gay couple or lesbian couple or
heterosexual couple.''
   Sometimes the definition of ``family'' is intended to circumvent
zoning restrictions, as in a bill sought by the Rhode Island
Department for Children and Their Families to protect group homes
from local opposition.
   No legislative action is expected for several weeks on the
measure, which says a department-run group home ``providing
residential care and-or treatment to eight or fewer children
residing out of their natural homes shall be considered a family for
purposes of zoning.''
   And in King William County, Va., 23-year-old twin sisters Kim
Taylor and Cam Porter, Pamunkey Indians, are gathering signatures
from Pamunkey women all over the East Coast to change a tribal law
barring them from the reservation because they both married white
men. Pamunkey men can marry whites.
   Chief William ``Swift Eagle'' Miles, who supports the sisters'
petition, said when they gather what they think are enough
signatures, they can request a tribal council meeting to discuss the
issue.
   Taylor said she wasn't able to marry anyone on the reservation
``because they're all girls or they're my cousins.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 12</NOTE>
