<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-10 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0757</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines filed for protection from
creditors in bankruptcy court, the sixth day of a Machinists strike,
blaming pilots for a ``cash crisis'' that paralyzed the nation's
seventh-largest airline.
   The move Thursday came a day after Eastern insisted such a step
remained a last resort in the airline's effort to endure the strike,
which had strong support from pilots and flight attendants.
   The filing under Chapter 11 in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York
is designed to give Eastern a reprieve from debts while it tries to
restructure and extricate itself from the worst crisis in its
60-year history.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, spurred by the bloody
riots in Venezuela, is putting together a new approach to the heavy
debt burden being carried by Third World countries, a problem that
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady has called ``perhaps the most
difficult'' facing the new administration.
   The new plan, or at least some details of what it will contain,
could be revealed as early as Friday, when Brady is scheduled to
address a private conference on Third World debt at the State
Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Clay Ford is retiring as a vice chairman
of Ford Motor Co., paving the way for a fourth generation of family
leadership of the automaker founded by his grandfather, Henry Ford.
   The retirement of Ford, disclosed Thursday, is effective at the
end of March and has been anticipated for months. He will remain on
the board of directors and as chairman of the board's finance and
executive committees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emhart Corp.'s board of directors rejected
an investment group's unsolicited $2.4 billion takeover offer and
said it had received rival buyout bids from other parties.
   Peter L. Scott, Emhart's chairman, recommended shareholders not
tender any of their stock to Topper Acquisition Corp., whose
investors include oil heir Gordon P. Getty and New York developers
Lawrence and Zachary Fisher.
   Topper, which has offered $35 a share for Emhart, had no
immediate comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel approved legislation to add $1.30
an hour to the $3.35 minimum wage over the next three years as
Democratic leaders said they are willing to compromise with the Bush
administration by adding a reduced ``training wage'' for new workers.
   The move to raise the minimum for the first time in eight years
was approved Thursday on a party-line vote by the House labor
standards subcommittee. The bill is nearly identical to one approved
by the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese exporter said it had canceled a
large order for Washington apples because of concerns over the
health effects of the chemical Alar, the latest sign of slowing
sales due to the controversy.
   W.L.H. Group of Seattle this week canceled an order for 5,000
boxes of Washington apples and may not order any more U.S. apples
the rest of the season, Sue Lin, an employee in the Seattle office,
said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said it opposes the
continuation of preferential tax breaks that federal regulators have
been using to attract buyers for insolvent savings and loan
associations.
   ``Unequivocally, we do not favor the continuation of favorable
tax treatment,'' White House Budget Director Richard Darman told the
Senate Finance Committee.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. on Thursday took
control of an additional 45 failed savings and loans, with $13.6
billion in assets, in eight states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government has decided to sell its
controlling interest in the nation's problem-ridden telephone
company despite strong union opposition, government and union
sources said.
   Such a sale would be the most dramatic example to date of
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's efforts to privatize
government-owned companies and modernize the Mexican economy.
   ``The problem is to do it without making it sound like another
confrontation with a labor union,'' a government source said
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market slipped Thursday as the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials dropped 4.11 points to 2,291.43.
   The dollar drifted lower against other major currencies.
   Bond prices edged lower in quiet trading.
   Silver and gold futures prices advanced and grains and soybeans
rebounded, while livestock, meat and energy futures retreated.
</TEXT>
