<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-10 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo today, while share prices gained on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   After opening lower at 128.85 yen, the dollar finished the day
almost unchanged at 128.88 yen, down 0.35 yen from Thursday's
129.23-yen closing. It ranged during the day between 128.82 and
129.08 yen.
   Dealers said the U.S. currency's decline was prompted by a
Federal Reserve Board official's comment early today that the dollar
needs to fall further in order for the United States to reduce its
trade deficit.
   Anxiety over February U.S. unemployment figures, due to be
released later today in Washington, also sidelined many players,
said a dealer at a major commercial bank who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``Because of the upcoming release of employment numbers, there
was no major movement today in Tokyo,'' said an exchange dealer at a
major U.S. commercial bank in Tokyo. ``There was some active selling
by insurance companies in the early morning when the dollar got up
above 129 yen, but that was about it all day.''
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 181.21 points on Thursday, rose 45.33
points, or 0.14 percent, to close the week at 31,701.78.
   Share prices droped sharply during the morning session, with the
Nikkei index falling 116.33 points before noon. However, strong
buying by private investors pushed the index up in the afternoon
session.
   ``Some shares, which once were considered overpriced, have come
down to a level which appears reasonable to investors,'' said
Ichitaro Watanabe, a dealer at Nikko Securities Co.
   Dealers said the market had been bearish since the end of
February because of fund managers' unwillingness to risk their
portfolios near the end of the accounting period for mutual and
trust funds. Japan's fiscal year ends on March 31.
   ``Most fund managers appear to have won reasonable profits thanks
to the bullish market throughout the year,'' said Keiichi Nishida, a
dealer at Kidder Peabody Securities in Tokyo. ``Most have already
cashed in and there doesn't seem to be much incentive in the market
for buying at this point.''
   But he said investors might turn to buying again if share prices
go down further.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
