<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-10 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Lower In Thin Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground in thin European trading
this morning as the market waited for the release of the latest U.S.
unemployment figures. Gold prices rose about $5 an ounce.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market had come to a virtual
standstill in anticipation of the U.S. unemployment statistics for
February, which were to be released later today.
   Economists were predicting a decline in the unemployment rate to
5.3 percent from 5.4 percent.
   Some traders said the U.S. unemployment report could shake the
market out of its current lethargy if the figures come in
significantly above or below expectations.
   But others doubted that the report would be capable of lifting
the market out of its current doldrums.
   One trader said he thought it was ``rather ridiculous how the
market can be paralyzed'' because of what likely would be just a
minor change in a monthly statistic.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.35 yen to a closing 128.88 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 129.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8585 West German marks, down from 1.8600; 1.5863
Swiss francs, down from 1.5895; 6.3025 French francs, down from
6.3125; 2.0974 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1000; 1,364.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,366.00; 1.1970 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2000.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7235, compared with
$1.7183 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $395 a troy ounce and at
midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended
price of $397, both up from $391.55 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $396.70, up from $391.75 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.58 to close at a bid $396.08.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.03 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $5.88.
</TEXT>
