<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Glance     03-10 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Glance,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments in the seven-day strike against
Eastern Airlines by the Machinists union:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TICKET SCRAMBLE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of would-be travelers, suddenly transformed into
unsecured creditors, tried to get refunds or fly on other carriers.
   The bankruptcy court must approve refunds for those holding some
$200 million worth of tickets. But if a passenger's destination were
a popular one, another carrier might honor the ticket, although
possibly at a higher price. And passengers who bought tickets with a
major credit card likely would benefit from a federal law that
protects consumers who make credit card purchases but fail to
receive goods or services.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EASTERN-BANKRUPTCY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 in
federal bankruptcy court in New York. Eastern's filing listed more
than $1 billion in assets, $3.39 billion in liabilities and 15,696
creditors.
   Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo and Eastern President Phil Bakes
insisted they intend to restore the airline in bankruptcy court,
though in a smaller form.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>UNION REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Machinists union called for a boycott of Eastern's sister
airline, Continental, and Eastern's unions said they would devise
their own reorganization plan to submit to bankruptcy court next
week.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SECONDARY STRIKES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court refused to overturn a ban on sympathy
strikes in support of Eastern's striking Machinists by union members
operating Philadelphia's commuter lines.
   In New York, a federal judge heard arguments on whether to extend
a ban against commuter rail sympathy strikes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>METZENBAUM-TEXAS AIR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Several hours before Eastern filed in bankruptcy court, Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, filed a bill that would allow Eastern
creditors to receive funds from parent company Texas Air Corp.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FINANCIAL REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Two leading debt-rating agencies, Moody's Investors Service and
Standard &amp; Poor's, said they had downgraded the credit ratings of
some Eastern securities and placed others under review for a
possible downgrade. Also placed under review were securities issued
by parent Texas Air, sister carrier Continental and People Express,
a Texas Air subsidiary which no longer operates.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORKERS' PAYCHECKS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Workers' paychecks for the last week worked were frozen by the
bankruptcy filing. John Peterpaul, a Machinists vice president, said
Eastern filed for bankruptcy on payday ``in a spiteful attempt to
deny Eastern workers their last paycheck earned before the strike.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
