<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Profile     03-10 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Profile,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Profile of Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Eastern Airlines, which has filed for Chapter
11 bankruptcy protection from creditors due to the strike by its
Machinists which was honored by its pilots and flight attendants.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by Texas Air Corp.,
headed by Chairman Frank Lorenzo, since 1986.
   Headquarters: Miami.
   Employees: 31,200, including 8,500 members of the Machinists
union, which includes mechanics, bag handlers and other ground
workers; 3,500 pilots and 5,900 flight attendants.
   Size of fleet: 250 jets.
   Cities served: 118, with major markets in South Florida, the
Caribbean, East Coast and Latin America.
   Number of pre-strike scheduled flights: 1,040 daily.
   Passengers: 100,000 average daily.
   Assets: $4.5 billion.
   Liabilities: $3.4 billion.
   Main issues: Eastern, which claims it lost $1 billion in the past
decade and is losing more than $1 million a day, is seeking between
$125 million and $150 million in wage concessions. The Machinists
are seeking $50 million in raises.
   Where negotiations stand: President Bush ignored the
recommendation of the National Mediation Board to appoint an
emergency panel that would have delayed delay the strike 60 days.
The strike began at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday.
   After the strike: Eastern vowed to continue flying, but was
forced to slash operations to 4 percent of scheduled flights with a
skeleton crew of 1,500 workers after pilots joined the striking
Machinists. Federal court orders have prevented the Machinists from
proposed secondary picketing of railroads, which had threatened to
disrupt commuter lines in major metropolitan areas.
   The airline sought but failed to get the courts to order pilots
back to work.
</TEXT>
