<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     03-10 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Wants to Learn CFTC Role in Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy says he needs to know what
role the Commodity Futures Trading Commission played in an
investigation of the Chicago exchanges before his committee decides
whether to reauthorize the agency.
   Leahy, D-Vt., made the comment Thursday during an appearance
before the Agriculture Committee by CFTC chairman Wendy Lee Gramm.
   The committee chairman said he and fellow senators would have to
know what the commission did during the two-year undercover FBI
investigation of alleged abuses at the Chicago Board of Trade and
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Mrs. Gramm said her agency was cooperating with the FBI. But she
would not elaborate, saying the Justice Department told her to
refrain from further comment.
   But Leahy said, ``Without knowing, it's very difficult for us to
pursue oversight responsibilities.'' Leahy said he has asked
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh for a senators-only briefing.
   Both the Senate and House have been conducting hearings to
determine if the commission should be restructured to better police
the exchanges.
   The CFTC is the federal agency charged with overseeing the
exchanges involved with commodities trading, but its authority to do
so is granted by Congress. Its authorization expires in September.
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., asked Mrs. Gramm if the commission
asked the FBI to investigate.
   ``How the investigation got started is something I cannot comment
on,'' she replied. ``I can't say the nature of the cooperation of
the CFTC.''
   When asked by Sen. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., whether the CFTC could
have done its own undercover investigation, Mrs. Gramm said she did
not think her agency had the authority to do the kind of criminal
work such a probe entails.
   ``It is my view that we have a good cooperative effort (with the
FBI),'' she said.
   ``We are concerned about whether you do the best job you can,''
said Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D. He said he wondered why the
commission had never asked if it had the authority for undercover
work.
   Mrs. Gramm said the commission uses aggressive techniques for
uncovering fraud and abuse, and the exchanges have been responsive
to enforcement action by the commission.
   Daschle said he could not see any objective measure of the CFTC's
success and asked Mrs. Gramm to supply him with such evidence later.
   Leahy asked Mrs. Gramm to provide within 30 days an analysis of
the pros and cons of 11 proposals for tightening oversight of the
exchange floors.
   They are:
   _requiring the exchanges to devote more resources to floor
surveillance and compliance;
   _requiring greater representation on exchange governing boards of
non-floor membership interests like wire house and trade firms, and
public members;
   _barring exchange members who have been repeatedly disciplined
from serving on exchange disciplinary or oversight panels;
   _increasing penalties for trading abuses;
   _requiring broker associations to register and limit trading
among association members;
   _curbing dual trading in pits where the exchange audit trail
cannot demonstrate a one-minute accuracy rate of 90 percent or
better;
   _mandating improvements in exchange audit trails;
   _increasing physical presence of CFTC staff on exchange floors;
   _barring oral orders on the floor;
   _adjusting CFTC rules to attract and keep the best professional
staff possible; and
   _increasing CFTC powers.
   He also asked her to provide any other proposals that the
committee could consider.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
