<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-States-ExciseTaxes     03-10 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-States-Excise Taxes,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Lawmakers Make Case Against Increased Federal Excise Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State legislative leaders say they oppose
raising federal excise taxes because past increases in those taxes
on gas, alcohol and cigarettes have cost the states billions of
dollars in lost revenue.
   To prove that point, the National Conference of State
Legislatures, released a study Thursday estimating the cost to
states of federal excise tax increases. Conference leaders were
meeting today with President Bush and administration officials.
   ``Whenever the federal government has raised those excise taxes,
the states have lost money,'' said Samuel B. Nunez Jr., president
pro tem of the Louisiana Senate and president of the conference.
   The study estimated that the states have lost revenue amounting
to $3.7 billion as a result of increases in those federal taxes in
1983 and 1985, and projected the figure would grow to $7.2 billion
by 1992.
   The study said that higher federal excise taxes increase the
final cost of the taxed goods and that higher prices in turn reduce
the quantities purchased. Because states also tax those goods, based
on quantity rather than price, the amount of state excise tax
revenue is reduced, the study said.
   The conference is lobbying against an increase in federal excise
taxes as part of any deficit-reduction package this year. Maine
House Speaker John Martin, vice president of the conference, said it
would not oppose a federal income tax increase as part of a deficit
solution.
   The study was underwritten by a major cigarette company, but
Martin said the company, Philip Morris USA, had nothing to do with
its contents.
   States traditionally rely on excise taxes on cigarettes, alcohol
and motor fuels for large portions of their revenues. Most states
earmark those revenues for specific purposes, with most fuel taxes
going for transportation needs.
   Martin said further increases in the federal excise taxes would
inhibit states and local governments from further increases in their
own excise taxes _ thus limiting an important revenue source.
   The study estimated that a 1 percent increase in the price of
gasoline reduces sales 0.6 percent, and that comparable increases in
the price of cigarettes reduce sales 0.4 percent, and in distilled
spirits, 1 percent.
   In 1983, the federal tax on cigarettes rose from 8 cents to 16
cents per pack, and the tax on gasoline rose from 4 cents to 9 cents
per gallon. The tax on distilled spirits rose from $10.50 to $12.50
per gallon in 1985, the study said.
   The study was conducted for the conference by the Policy
Economics Group of Peat Marwick Main &amp; Co., a national certified
public accounting firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MinimumWage     03-10 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Follows Senate Panel in Clearing Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic measure to increase the minimum
wage by $1.30 an hour to $4.65 over three years is gaining ground in
Congress even as President Bush insists he will veto any raise
higher than his own proposal.
   The plan to raise the $3.35-an-hour minimum wage for the first
time since 1981 won approval from the House labor standards
subcommittee on Thursday. Democratic leaders, at the same time,
called for a compromise on a sub-minimum ``training wage'' for new
hires in hopes of passing the increase this month.
   Rep. Austin Murphy, chairman of the subcommittee, said he plans
to propose a reduced minimum when the bill reaches the House floor,
although requirements will be far stricter than what the
administration wants.
   The House bill drawn up Thursday is virtually identical to the
one passed Wednesday by the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee, where Chairman Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., says he hopes
the legislation is on a ``fast track'' for approval.
   But the Bush administration repeated warnings Thursday that an
increase beyond 90 cents an hour over three years and without its
own reduced minimum for all newly hired workers would be vetoed.
   ``The entire package is the bottom line, both the $4.25 figure
and the six-month training wage at $3.35,'' said Dale Tate, a
spokeswoman for Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole. ``We've come more
than halfway towards meeting the goal'' of proponents of a minimum
wage increase.
   Despite the differences, Democrats were encouraged that the White
House favors an increase at all.
   ``Recent White House proposals ... are both constructive and
encouraging,'' said Murphy, D-Pa.
   The Bush package would keep the hourly floor at $3.35 for all
newly hired workers for their first six months employment on any
job. Otherwise, 30 cents an hour would be added to the minimum
annually for three years.
   The Democratic plan would raise the minimum to $3.85 on enactment
and add 40 cents an hour in the next two years, to reach $4.65 in
1991.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., has scheduled action on the
measure by his House Education and Labor Committee next Tuesday. He
said he hopes for a full House vote the following day, although a
spokeswoman for Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said no vote
is expected there until members return from the Easter recess in
April.
   Hawkins became the latest Democratic leader to reverse field on
the training wage issue, saying Thursday he's willing to accept a
sub-minimum if it is limited and includes education and ``real
training'' requirements.
   Democratic committee aides said the Murphy plan being drawn up
would limit a sub-minimum to first-time workers and likely have
specific requirements for training on different occupations. The
aides said duration of the sub-minimum would be for between 30 and
90 days and that the lower wage would be pegged to a percentage of
the standard minimum wage.
   ``Our amendment will be more restrictive than the proposals we
have heard from the president,'' said Murphy. ``However, our effort
will show we are sincere and prepared to address all the components
of this issue.''
   Democrats and organized labor have long opposed a second tier for
new employees because of fears that workers would be laid off in
favor of those covered by the lower scale.
   But Hawkins said Thursday: ``If they want to have a training
wage, we will discuss it with them ... It would have to be a
meaningful training wage. It could not be one in name that allows
only a sub-minimum.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
