<FIRST>r f PM-FordRetires     03-10 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford Retires,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>William Clay Ford Retiring; Keeping Board Positions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third generation of the family that
founded Ford Motor Co. has stepped down with the next generation
waiting in the wings, soon to get more say-so in the nation's No. 2
automaker's operations.
   William Clay Ford on Thursday announced his retirement from the
company founded by his grandfather, effective at the end of the
month.
   The fourth generation of the automaking family is represented by
Ford's son, William C. Ford Jr., and nephew, Edsel B. Ford II. The
31-year-old William Ford Jr., called Billy, is managing director of
Ford of Switzerland and Edsel Ford is general sales manager for
Ford's Lincoln-Mercury Division.
   Both of the young Fords are members of the company's board of
directors, but neither holds key positions.
   ``I think that will be taken care of in the near future,''
William Ford said at a rare news conference at Ford headquarters
Thursday. He said he expected the cousins to be named to committees
of the company's board in the near future.
   Ford has been a member of the company's board of directors since
1948, the year before he graduated from Yale, and will remain a
member of the board and as chairman of its finance and executive
committees.
   Ford's retirement announcement, five days before his 64th
birthday, was no surprise. For weeks, there has been talk around
auto circles in Detroit about the roles of Billy and Edsel in the
company. A Fortune magazine article hit the newsstands in December,
saying that Ford Chairman Donald Petersen didn't believe the two
were ready for leadership posts.
   During the annual automobile show in Detroit in January, however,
Petersen said the cousins were ``now coming of age.''
   Ford said Thursday that members of the family should be in top
positions of the company. However, no family member should be given
a position simply because of the family name, he said.
   ``Nature has got to take its course,'' Ford said.
   The Ford family, through trusts and individually, exercises 40
percent of voting power of shareholders through a special Class B
stock. The number of votes connected with each share of Class B
stock is adjusted before each annual meeting to give those
shareholders the 40 percent.
   Ford called the Class B stock ``a great anti-takeover measure.''
   Ford, who took part in decisions that lifted the company out of
severe financial troubles in the early 1980s, has been chairman of
the board's design committee since it was created in 1957.
   Two of the main reasons the company was put on the road from
financial problems to the nation's most-profitable automaker were
the Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable automobiles, both of which
capitalized on sleek, aerodynamic looks.
   In offering a public farewell to Ford, company Chairman Harold
Poling said Thursday that development of the aerodynamic look
``wasn't exactly a unanimous thing in the company.''
   Later, Ford said, ``I was all for it. I think everybody kind of
resists change. Personally I find it very appealing.''
   He was the youngest of four children of Edsel B. Ford, president
of the automobile company from 1919 until his death in 1943.
   Ford's oldest brother, Henry Ford II, was the company's
president, chairman and chief executive officer before his death in
September 1987. His other brother, Benson Ford, was vice president
and chairman of the dealer policy board when he died in 1978.
   Ford also is the sole owner and president of the Detroit Lions
professional football club.
   Now that he has retired, Ford said he will have more time to
devote to golf and the Lions, one of the worst teams in the NFL last
year with a 4-12 record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0282 </DOCNO>
