<FIRST>r f PM-CadburySchweppes     03-10 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cadbury Schweppes,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cadbury Schweppes Moves Beverage Headquarters to Stamford from London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cadbury Schweppes PLC says moving the
worldwide headquarters for it beverage businesses from London to
Stamford will streamline operations as the British soft drinks and
confectionery group goes after a larger share of the multibillion
dollar soft drink market.
   ``We need to have a clear sense of vision at the center,'' Sir
Adrian Cadbury, chairman of Cadbury Schweppes, said Thursday at
Cadbury Schweppes Beverages offices.
   Cadbury Schweppes Beverages will occupy the same building as its
U.S. division, already based in Stamford.
   ``The United States is clearly the right location for our
international beverages headquarters,'' Cadbury said. ``It's the
largest and most developed soft drink market in the world. ... More
fundamentally, this country is the foundation of new ideas and of
innovation for the beverage industry generally.''
   Cadbury Schweppes Beverages is closing the Atlanta headquarters
of its Canada Dry and Sunkist soda divisions and moving them to
Stamford as part of the consolidation.
   Also affected are Cadbury Beverages' North American, European,
British and International units.
   Cadbury also announced that it will open a new, worldwide
research center in nearby Trumbull in June, consolidating work now
done at laboratories in Williamson, N.Y., and in Dollis Hill near
London, which are being closed. The Trumbull facility will employ
about 100 people, mostly scientists and engineers.
   James P. Schadt, president and chief executive of Cadbury
Schweppes Beverages, estimated that the moves announced Thursday
will create about 200 jobs in Connecticut, including 70 in Stamford,
and pump more than $10 million into the Connecticut economy in 1989
alone.
   The company has eliminated about 500 jobs worldwide during the
last year as part of its consolidation effort, Schadt said.
   Cadbury Schweppes Beverages' other products include Mott's and
Red Cheek apple-based juices and sauces, and Holland House, Rose's
and Mr. and Mrs. ``T'' cocktail mixers.
   The company had about 3 percent of the $26 billion in soft drink
sales in the United States last year, company officials said. It
employs about 6,300 people worldwide, including 350 in Stamford.
   Cadbury began consolidating its soft drink businesses in 1987
when Schadt, a former executive of Pepsico Inc., was named managing
director of the Cadbury Schweppes beverage businesses.
   The parent company announced earlier this month that its 1988
after-tax profit jumped 28.5 percent over a year ago, helped by
strong growth in Britain as well as Australia and neighboring
countries.
   After-tax profit in the 12 months ended Dec. 31 totaled 140.5
million pounds, the equivalent of $242 million, compared with 109.3
million pounds the year before.
   Earnings per share rose to 23.47 pence, or 40 cents, from 19.05
pence, helped by a change in the company's tax accounting.
   Sales rose 17.2 percent to 2.38 billion pounds, or $4.1 billion,
from 2.03 billion pounds.
   Cadbury and Schweppes merged in 1969. The company acquired Canada
Dry in 1986.
</TEXT>
