<FIRST>r f PM-TWA-FalseAds     03-10 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TWA-False Ads,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charged with Deceptive Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State of California has charged
Trans World Airlines with deceptive air travel advertising.
   The complaint filed Thursday alleges that TWA advertised in
newspapers and other media a low one-way fare to London, although in
fact the fare could be obtained only by buying a round-trip ticket.
   State Attorney General John Van de Kamp issued a statement saying
the suit _ in San Diego County Superior Court _ would bar the
airline from further unfair advertising, and assess civil penalties.
   Van de Kamp said TWA's advertising fails to clearly and
adequately disclose other fees that must be paid to utilize the
advertised one-way fare.
   The complaint also alleges that TWA falsely advertised that
customers who used the low London fare could obtain an Alamo rental
car free. But it says there is a mandatory fuel fee regardless of
how far the car is driven and even when the customers buy their own
fuel.
   The announcement said that in filing the action, the attorney
general's office took notice of a recent decision by the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the District of Columbia that rejected U.S.
Department of Transportation rules permitting airlines to omit
certain taxes and fees from advertised flight costs.
</TEXT>
