<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Scandal     03-10 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Scandal,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scandal-Shaken NTT To Cut Salaries Of Executives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scandal-shaken Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.,
in a gesture of public regret, will cut the salaries of its top
executives next month, news reports said Friday.
   The pay cuts, ranging between 10 and 20 percent, will be in force
for six months and affect 35 top executives, including NTT President
Haruo Yamaguchi and six other directors, Kyodo News Service said.
   Officials at NTT, Japan's largest corporation, were not available
for comment late Friday.
   Three former top NTT officials have been arrested for alleged
bribery in connection with a stock-profiteering scandal involving
unlisted stocks offered at bargain prices by Recruit Co., an
information conglomerate.
   The NTT officials allegedly gave Recruit favorable treatment in
exchange for the large profits they received when the stocks were
publicly traded and skyrocketed in value.
   Kyodo said Yamaguchi personally reported the pay cuts to Posts
and Telecommunications Minister Seiichi Kataoka earlier Friday.
Kataoka expressed support for the action, and urged NTT to do more
to mend its tarnished image, it said.
   Yamaguchi himself will take a pay cut of 20 percent, while the
salaries of directors and auditors will be cut by 10 to 15 percent,
Kyodo said.
</TEXT>
