<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DakotaName     03-10 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dakota Name,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Dakota Committee Endorses New State Name: Dakota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAM SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint committee of the Legislature has
voted 7-3 to rename North Dakota simply ``Dakota,'' ridding the
state of an ``unimaginative, unattractive, ordinary'' word.
   Critics called the much-ballyhooed idea a public relations stunt,
but the Joint Constitutional Revisions Committee on Thursday
endorsed a resolution that would put the name change on the November
1990 ballot as a constitutional amendment.
   Before that referendum is held, though, the resolution will have
to be approved by the state Senate and the state House. If the
voters eventually endorse the idea, the name change would also have
to be approved by Congress.
   Gov. George Sinner does not oppose the name change but has no
plans to lobby for it, press secretary Robert Jansen said.
   State Tourism Director Jim Fuglie, who has plugged the name
change in radio interviews across the country, was ecstatic about
Thursday's vote, vowing to resign his job and work full-time to
campaign for it if lawmakers eventually place the issue before the
voters.
   The word ``North'' is an ``unimaginative, unattractive, ordinary
word tacked onto the spectacular word, Dakota,'' Fuglie said.
   Backers also say the word ``North'' conjures up a cold, harsh
climate and detracts from the word ``Dakota,'' which means
``friend'' and is the name of a group of Indian tribes also known as
the Sioux.
   Dakota is ``such a beautiful word,'' said Rep. Janet Wentz.
``When we were given the name North Dakota, we didn't have anything
to say about it.''
   Sen. Ray Holmberg, one of the three legislators who voted against
the resolution, said the name North Dakota is ``extremely important
to the history and heritage of the state and should not be used as a
public relations experiment.''
   The proposal also has drawn fire in newspaper editorials and
letters to the editor, and became the focus of a tongue-in-cheek
campaign by a Montana paper to find a new name for the state. The
winner of the Billings Gazette contest was ``Manitscolda,'' as in
``Man, it's cold-a.''
   Before voting for the idea, committee members shot down an
amendment that would have changed the state's name to ``Dakotah.''
Sen. Donna Nalewaja, said she thought it might be ``classy'' to add
the ``h,'' but said it would meet resistance from voters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HiltonTrial     03-10 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hilton Trial,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>$38.8 Million Verdict For Workers In Long Casino Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has awarded 36 fired casino workers $38.8
million in a case that could affect the way Nevada's gaming industry
hires and fires its employees.
   The federal court jury on Thursday found the Las Vegas Hilton
guilty of age and sex discrimination, breach of contract, bad faith
and inflicting severe emotional distress in the firing of the
workers in September 1983.
   Hilton attorneys contended that casinos have the right to hire
and fire at will because of the volatile nature of the business and
the large amount of cash that is handled.
   The resort also claimed the dealers understood they could be
fired at will and accepted it as a tradeoff for large amount of
money they made in wages and tips.
   The dealers, though, claimed they were the victims of age and sex
discrimination when they were replaced by younger female workers,
and contended the hotel gave them an implied contract when hired
that they would not be fired except with justifiable cause.
   ``Casinos have traditionally held themselves to be above the
law,'' said Brian Berman, an attorney for the plaintiffs. ``We think
the jury sent a clear example to the employers in the state of
Nevada that they cannot do this.''
   Hilton executives testified that the workers were fired over the
1983 Labor Day weekend after other, unsuccessful attempts to clear
up an unusually low win percentage in the hotel's blackjack pit.
   The verdict came after four days of deliberation following a
14-week trial.
   The biggest portion of the award was for punitive damages, which
the jury assessed at $30 million.
   Steve Wynn, owner of the Golden Nugget Hotel and Casino, attacked
the verdict, saying it was stupid for a jury to award that much in
such a case.
   The affected dealers disagreed.
   ``It's been 5{ years of praying and a little hope,'' said Jack
Bosarge. ``We realized we were up against one of the biggest
corporations in the world, but we all stuck together and came out on
top.''
   Hilton attorneys said they would ask the verdict be set aside,
claiming the jury was misled by sympathy for the workers. If that
fails, resort attorneys said they would appeal.
   ``We're very disappointed,'' said Hilton attorney Raymond Kelly.
``(Casino manager) Robert Kelley and the Hilton did exactly what it
had to do under the circumstances.''
   All but five of the casino workers won claims for age
discrimination and were awarded sums ranging from $7,000 to $107,000
for lost wages. Each plaintiff also was given $200,000 for the
Hilton having inflicted severe emotional distress in the firings,
and will share the $30 million in punitive damages.
   ``Maybe the whole gambling business will learn something from
this,'' said Joseph Saunto, one of the fired workers. ``Maybe they
won't throw people away now when they're done with them.''
   The plaintiffs had sought nearly $50 million in actual and
punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
