<FIRST>r f PM-CreditCard-Fraud     03-10 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Credit Card-Fraud,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Getting Phony Charge Cards In Names Of Reporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly obtained credit cards in
the names of reporters whose bylines he saw in newspapers and
magazines has been arrested for investigation of submitting false
credit applications.
   Frank Charles Austin, 36, of Los Angeles, was accused of
submitting more than 30 credit applications to Sears Roebuck and JC
Penney, police said.
   Austin apparently received several cards and bought an unknown
amount of merchandise before his arrest, said police Detective
Reynaldo Morales.
   ``The amount of the fraud is not significant,'' Morales said.
``It is significant in that he was able to obtain the cards. It's
funny how easy it is to get a credit card.''
   Detectives began investigating last month after two unidentified
reporters at the Los Angeles Herald Examiner complained that someone
had tried to obtain charge cards using their names and place of
employment, the newspaper reported today.
   ``The suspect obtained names at random and using fictitious
information would submit fraudulent credit applications to several
credit-card granting companies,'' Detective Richard Van Nort said.
   Police said applications were submitted under the names of at
least 12 people, including writers for Los Angeles Times magazine
and California magazine.
   Nick D'Egidio, new accounts manager at JC Penney, said his office
received 15 applications and issued cards in five cases.
   Ron Ventresca, a fraud investigator for Sears, said the company
received 19 applications and one card was issued.
</TEXT>
