<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain On Soviet Wheat Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, gaining
on news that the Soviet Union was bidding for 515,000 metric tons of
U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Rumors of a Soviet bid for U.S. wheat had circulated during
Thursday's trading session and contributed to a late rally that
carried through into the opening today.
   Market analysts said that if the Agriculture Department accepts
the bid and the Soviets buy the wheat, the USDA probably will offer
them another 1 million metric tons of wheat under the government's
Export Enhancement Program.
   Continued warm, dry weather in the nation's midsection also
supported wheat futures by adding to fears of dry-weather damage to
the winter-wheat crop.
   The possibility of a dockworkers' strike next week in Brazil, the
world's second-largest soybean producer, prompted some buying of
soybean futures this morning.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.36 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $2.78{ a bushel; oats were }
cent to 1 cent higher with May at $2.12} a bushel; soybeans were 1
cent to 2 cents higher with March at $7.65{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .58 cent higher with April at 77.65
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .45 cent higher
with March at 81.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent lower to
.23 cent higher with April at 43.65 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent lower to .05 cent higher with March at 38
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
