<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NCNBTexas-FDIC     03-10 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NCNB Texas-FDIC,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Wants NCNB Texas To Sell Troubled Assets More Quickly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Texas National Bank is resisting regulators'
pressure to dispose of about $6 billion in troubled assets the
company manages as a result of its takeover of First RepublicBank
Corp.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which owns 80 percent of
NCNB Texas, wants to sell the assets, mainly real estate, while bank
officials are contemplating holding on to the property.
   ``We would be inclined to take a longer view than they would be
inclined to take,'' NCNB Texas Chairman Francis R. Kemp said. ``We
have to be realistic to achieve the highest value for their assets.''
   That contrasts with FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman's statement
earlier this week that, ``We are not in the business of speculating
on real estate values.''
   Kemp said the bank could see some value in retaining assets,
particularly real estate, for a number of years until market prices
begin to recover.
   Acknowledging that many lenders have sustained losses from
attempting to outlast the Texas real estate slump, Kemp said he
believes disposal may be ill-advised.
   ``We are concerned that we would like to take more time with real
estate than the FDIC would like, but we're not sure we're right,''
he said. ``This is clearly a `How high is high?' question.''
   The government segregated the troubled loans and other assets
were placed into a separate pool, which NCNB Texas agreed to manage
last summer when it bought the former banks of First Republic.
   FDIC officials would not comment Thursday. In other situations,
regulators have adopted a strategy of making all assets available
for sale at market prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
