<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Bankruptcy,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allowing Eastern To Pay Working Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge is allowing
strike-crippled Eastern Airlines to pay its working employees but
has made no provision for paying workers who are honoring Machinists
picket lines.
   Eastern attorney Bruce Zirinsky said Friday the carrier was freed
to compensate its employees working outside the United States,
namely in Central and South America and the Carribbean.
   Federal Judge Burton R. Lifland signed an order late Thursday
also authorizing Eastern to provide benefits and salary and to
reimburse expenses for other currently working Eastern employees.
   Eastern filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11
of the federal Bankruptcy Code on Thursday, the sixth day of a
crippling strike by its Machinists union and walkouts by its pilots
and flight attendants.
   The bankruptcy court must approve all of the company's
expenditures and transactions.
   The filing came on what would have been payday for the
Machinists, whose final pre-strike paychecks were withheld as part
of the Chapter 11 petition.
