<FIRST>r f BC-Eastern-Railroads     03-10 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Railroads,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Decision Delayed on Railroad Sympathy Strikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who has temporarily barred
commuter railroad workers from honoring Eastern Airlines strikers'
picket lines has extended his order until he renders a final
decision.
   U.S. District Judge Robert P. Patterson Jr. extended his
self-imposed Friday midnight deadline indefinitely, until he rules
on whether it is legal for railroad workers to strike in sympathy
with airlines workers.
   Patterson gave no indication how long the temporary restraining
order would remain in effect or when he would issue a written
opinion on the complex labor dispute.
   His secretary, Kathleen Howley, said Patterson on Friday decided
to extend the deadline because the transcript of two days of
hearings he conducted was not immediately available and electrical
power in Manhattan's federal courthouse would be off for several
hours on Saturday for testing purposes.
   ``I hope to render an opinion as soon as possible,'' Patterson
told lawyers for both sides at the end of the second day of hearings
on Thursday, but gave no indication when that might be.
   Less than an hour after strikebound Eastern filed for Chapter 11
protection from creditors, Patterson heard competing legal arguments
from lawyers for four metropolitan area railroads and the unions
that represent their workers.
   The unions claim that federal law allows secondary picketing in
the railroad and airline industries.
   But the railroads maintain that the law requires their employees
to stay on the job until they go through a series of mandated
arbitration steps.
   On Sunday, at the request of the railroads, Patterson barred
workers at the Long Island Rail Road, Metro-North and New Jersey
Transit from honoring the picket lines of Eastern strikers.
   Patterson later extended the temporary restraining order to
Amtrak workers.
   Eastern machinists had said they might set up picket lines at the
railroads as part of their strike but have not done so yet.
   ``This could bring the city to an absolute standstill,'' the
judge said near the end of Wednesday's session.
   Earlier Wednesday, the unions urged a federal appeals court to
overturn Patterson's order but the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
declined to intervene until the lower court made a determination.
   In two days of lengthy hearings, Patterson heard railroad
officials testify that they would be forced to shut down if their
workers honored Eastern strikers' picket lines.
   The unions will not concede that point and maintain that they
will only ``urge and encourage'' their members to honor picket lines
_ not order them to do so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
