<HEAD>Iraqi Airways Seeks Lifting of TWA Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's state airline has asked the
government to lift a ban on flights by Trans World Airlines so that
a Baghdad-Detroit route can be opened, a senior Iraqi Airways
official said.
   Nouri El Din Safi, Iraqi Airways' director general, said Thursday
he hoped the ban on TWA flights under an Arab boycott of firms that
do business with Israel soon would be lifted.
   He said that Iraqi and United States civil aviation authorities
reached agreement last year on starting flights between the
countries, but the accord was never implemented because of the TWA
ban.
   The U.S. government does not permit a foreign airline to operate
in the United States if an American airline is banned from operating
in that country.
   Safi said the planned flight would link Baghdad and Detroit,
which has a large Iraqi community, with a stop in Paris.
