<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Brazil     03-10 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Minister Says Debt Crisis Will Bring `Messiahs' to Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The finance minister says that if
wealthy countries don't do something about reducing Latin America's
debt, populists and demagogues will gain political power in the
region.
   The minister, Mailson da Nobrega, said: ``People will believe in
messiahs. Radical groups will replace moderate ones'' now grappling
with Latin America's $400 billion foreign debt.
   Recent riots in Venezeula, which left more than 250 people dead,
were a ``clear alert'' that the current debt situation is ``socially
and politically unbearable,'' da Nobrega said.
   ``Latin American debt is being paid at the cost of low salaries
for Latin Americans. The industrialized countries don't understand
this,'' he said.
   Brazil, owing $115 billion, mostly to big U.S banks, is the Third
World's biggest debtor.
   Brazil, which in 1985 returned to civilian government after 21
years of military rule, is preparing for presidential elections on
Nov. 15, the first such popular vote in Brazil since 1960.
   Political parties still must hold conventions to choose
candidates, but media polls show leftist leaders are very popular.
   Da Nobrega said news reports that the Bush administration is
preparing new policies for dealing with Third World debt are ``very
positive.''
   ``This seems to be the maturing of an idea that there must be
something more than just the debtors and the banks in the resolution
of the debt: the involvement of governments of industrialized
countries and of international financial institutions,'' he said.
   Latin American governments now in power ``realize that
confrontation is not the answer,'' da Nobrega said.
   But he added that these current administrations need
``corresponding measures'' from the developed world ``to reduce the
amount of Latin American debt and provide a flow of new financial
resources to Latin America.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
