<SECOND>BC-Chrysler Profit Sharing,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iacocca Hands Out Four Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca dropped
by the company's stamping plant in this northern Detroit suburb
Friday to hand out profit-sharing checks to four workers.
   Iacocca presented the checks while standing in front of a
stamping press being tested for operation in July. He congratulated
the workers and they thanked him during the five-minute ceremony.
   The chairman of the nation's third-largest automaker then was
hustled past reporters and photographers for a brief tour through
some of the 630,000 square feet of manufacturing space. Before he
left, Iacocca was serenaded in the plant's executive garage by six
Chrysler workers singing a tune called ``Committed to be the Best.''
   The company handed out more than $59.9 million in profit-sharing
checks to about 82,000 workers, or about $725 each. Ford Motor Co.
distributed profit-sharing checks Tuesday averaging about $2,800
apiece, and next Tuesday General Motors Corp. will mail checks of
slightly more than $250 per employee.
   The checks, called for in labor agreements among the Big Three
and the United Auto Workers union, are based on the companies'
financial performance in North America. It's the first time that
workers for all of the companies have received the payments in the
same year.
