<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Cocoa     03-10 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Cocoa,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Consumers Expected to Call For Levy Suspension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consuming countries are expected to call for the
suspension of the current levy on traded cocoa at International
Cocoa Organization talks opening here Monday, delegates said Friday.
   They are expected to argue a formal suspension is warranted
because key cocoa producers have unilaterally stopped paying their
share.
   The levy of $30 a metric ton is collected by producers when they
sell to cocoa organization consumers, and by consumers when they buy
from non-members.
   The money is supposed to be forwarded to the cocoa organization,
headquartered in London, to meet operational costs and to finance
possible market-intervention measures.
   The organization lacks the money to implement a proposed
stockpiling scheme to stabilize prices in the current oversupplied
market because of producer arrears totaling more than $80 million.
   Producer debts, the bulk owed by the Ivory Coast and Brazil, have
created a feeling of injustice among consuming countries, delegates
said, requesting anonymity.
   Consumers were disappointed when producers at the last meeting of
the 41-nation cocoa organization here in January rejected a proposal
to suspend the levy.
   Traders said that they did not expect the talks to produce any
market-moving developments.
   ``International action to support prices looks likely to remain
paralyzed for the foreseeable future,'' said one.
   All leading consuming countries except the United States are
members of the cocoa organization. The only key producers that do
not belong are Malaysia and Indonesia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
