<FIRST>u f BC-BritainStocks 1stLd-Writethru   03-10 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0043,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher Ahead Of Budget Presentation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher Friday, shaking off the
depressing influence of early losses on Wall Street, as buying
interest emerged at the beginning of a new trading account during
which Britain's fiscal 1990 budget is to be presented.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 9.3
points, or 0.4 percent, higher at 2,085.2.
   The index gained as much as 14.5 points at midday but later fell
back to its lowest level, up 3.4 points, shortly after New York
opened for business.
   For the week, the index gained 26 points. It also was up 65.7
points over the course of the two-week trading account that ended
Friday. London's Stock Exchange divides trading into two-week and
three-week trading periods for accounting purposes.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 10.8 points at 1,724.9.
The Financial Times 500-share index rose 5.95 points to close at
1,190.44.
   Volume was a relatively brisk 655 million shares, its best level
for the past month, and up from 483.9 million shares on Thursday.
   Several dealers voiced surprise at the market's resilience in the
face of subsequent losses on Wall Street.
   But other dealers said the London market was ignoring external
factors, at least until Tuesday's budget speech by Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson is safely out of the way.
   Most private economists expect Lawson to present a conservative
budget, with relatively small tax cuts, to prevent the economy from
overheating.
</TEXT>
