<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingWiring     03-10 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Wiring,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>59 Wiring and Plumbing Problems in Boeing Jets Reported Since 1981</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Aviation Administration officials say they
have received 59 reports of miswiring or faulty plumbing in
cargo-hold and engine fire-suppression systems of commercial jets
made by the Boeing Co. since 1981.
   The first problem was reported in 1983 and the latest on Thursday.
   FAA officials said 32 of the problems were found by airlines
before Jan. 31, when the agency issued an airworthiness directive
for checks of 741 jets in the United States, while the other 27 were
found afterward. The FAA also has heard from many foreign carriers
flying some of the other 836 Boeing jets that were built in the same
period.
   Boeing is in the process of redesigning some parts and
overhauling test procedures to try to prevent future errors.
   Meanwhile, the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported today that a
letter dated Jan. 26 from Leroy Keith, local manager of the FAA's
Aircraft Certification Service, to Boeing officials renewed concerns
about delays in reporting safety problems to the federal agency.
   Boeing learned of crossed wires in a 757 cargo compared
fire-suppression system last August but reported the problem four
months later, Keith noted.
   ``Until now, I had been encouraged that there were definite
improvements,'' his letter said. ``The 757 issue, however, indicates
that more needs to be done.''
   The newspaper also said an internal FAA briefing paper cited
several factors in the plumbing and wiring mistakes.
   Fire-extinguishing system connectors were identical in size,
making it easier to misconnect them, and Boeing's functional test
procedure did not include the completed systems to insure that the
proper connector was attached to the corresponding plug on fire
bottles.
   ``Results of this FAA inspection have identified several areas of
concern within the Boeing quality control system,'' the briefing
paper said.
</TEXT>
