<FIRST>r f PM-GAOReport     03-10 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAO Report,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report Says Land Sold for Pennies on the Dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has sold to private
interests thousands of acres in the West worth a thousand times the
land's selling price, according to a published report.
   The Arizona Republic reported in today's editions that the
transactions, described in a report by the General Accounting
Office, are allowed under a 117-year-old law designed to promote
miing in the West.
   According to the GAO report, the Republic said, at least three
Phoenix-area tracts are involved, including a 19-acre site that sold
in 1987 for $47 and now is estimated to be worth $376,000 to $3.8
million. That site was bought by Melluzzo and Nichols granite
operation, the Republic said.
   Other Phoenix deals reported by the Republic include the 1985
sale of 15 acres for $38 but estimated to be worth $272,000. It was
bought by Phoenix Sand &amp; Rock. The Republic also cited sale of 40
acres near Mesa in 1983 to another sand and gravel operation,
Johnson &amp; Johnson, for $100 but estimated to be worth $400,000.
   The GAO said that since 1970, the federal government has
collected $4,500 for land valued in 1988 at $14 million to $48
million, the newspaper reported.
   The land was sold under the patent provisions of the Mining Law
of 1872, which says a patent holder owns the land and the minerals
contained in it.
   To acquire a patent, a person must meet certain minimal
requirements intended to show mining activity, but critics say the
requirements are lax and meaningless.
   The report urged that the law be changed to prohibit land sales
under the loophole.
   Among the federal land sold was an inactive 160-acre mining claim
near the Keystone, Colo., ski resort that was patented in 1983 for
$2.50 an acre. Last year, 44 acres of that tract were offered for
sale at $11,000 an acre.
   ``This is outrageous,'' said Rep. Nick Joe Rahall, D-W.Va., who
heads the Interior subcommittee on mining and natural resources,
where the report was released Wednesday.
   ``At $2.50 an acre, these valuable federal lands are being
transferred out of public ownership for fast-food-hamburger
prices,'' a statement released by Rahall said.
   ``The intent of the mining law is to facilitate mineral
extraction, not serve as a vehicle for land speculation and
profiteering at the public's expense,'' he added.
   Keith Knoblock, vice president of the 450-member American Mining
Congress, said the report was misleading and contained factual
errors. He added that changing the law would hurt the struggling
mining industry.
   He said the GAO ``decided what conclusions it wanted to reach and
then presented information to justify those conclusions.''
   Since passage of the Mining Law, the federal government has sold
about 3.2 million acres, an area about the size of Connecticut.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr., told Rahall's subcommittee
Wednesday that he supports legislation increasing patent fees from
the current $2.50 and $5 an acre.
</TEXT>
