<FIRST>r f AM-US-Mexico     03-10 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mexico,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conable Proposes Debt Relief for Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Third World Debt Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the World Bank called Friday for
special relief to Mexico from its debt burden of more than $100
billion.
   ``Mexico has indicated a willingness to engage in major
reforms,'' said Barber Conable. ``It has substantial prospects. It
also has substantial debt, and it has lived up to its obligations.''
   ``The international financial community should offer Mexico a
wider than traditional range of options to finance its requirements
over the next few years,'' Conable said.
   His first suggestion was that there should be a signficant
reduction in Mexico's debt, the largest in the Third World after
Brazil's. Current loans to Mexico should be exchanged at a discount
for long-term bonds, he said. This would be a form of debt
forgiveness by the commercial banks to which the bulk of Mexico's
debt is owed.
   Mexico would have less to repay when the bonds came due, and
interest paid in the interval would also be reduced.
   The World Bank, owned by 151 governments, is the major source of
aid to Third World countries. Under a plan proposed by then-Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III in 1985, it is in charge of helping
debtor countries map new policies to put them in a better position
to carry their debt burden.
   Conable also suggested:
   _``Exit bonds,'' to be taken by creditor banks at a discount from
the sums now owed them, enabling some banks to get out of lending to
Mexico. This would also reduce the principal and interest Mexico has
to pay.
   _A ``debt-equity swap program,'' which would allow banks to use
the dollars they have lent to Mexico to buy shares in Mexican
businesses
   _Strong support from international bodies like his own bank and
its sister organization, the International Monetary Fund, to support
Mexico's austerity policies. Though Conable did not specify, this
support would presumably include additional loans on more favorable
terms than those offered by commerical banks.
   _New tax, trade and banking regulations by creditor countries to
encourage private investment from abroad that will help Mexico's
income to grow.
   ``New money will be needed in Mexico's case even after
significant debt reduction,'' Conable added.
   He said that his bank and other international bodies cannot
furnish the needed money alone, implying that new loans from
commercial banks will also be needed.
</TEXT>
