<DOCNO> AP890310-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-UsedPlanes     03-10 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Used Planes,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delays Boost Jet Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delays in shipping Boeing's new 747-400 jumbo jet
have pushed up prices for used 747s and made them nearly as scarce
as the new models, industry officials say.
   ``It's a seller's market, and there just aren't any planes out
there right now,'' said Bill Avery, editor of Cargo Facts, an
industry newsletter published in Seattle.
   The first 747-400 was to have been delivered in December. But to
date, just one 747-400 has been delivered, to Northwest Airlines,
although a number of the planes are close to completion. Boeing
hopes to deliver 57 of the planes by the end of the year.
   Twenty-two customers have ordered 192 of the advanced planes,
which can carry 412 passengers more than 8,000 miles.
   Boeing has cited late deliveries by suppliers, complex new
avionics, an inexperienced work force and a decision to win
simultaneous certification for several versions of the new plane as
reasons for the delays.
   Because of the delays, airlines are holding on to their older
planes. As a result, just eight of the more than 700 older 747s are
for sale worldwide, and most of those are spoken for, says Avmark, a
Virginia-based aircraft appraisal company.
   Higher demand also has meant higher used-plane prices, says
Avmark's Paul Turk.
   ``Boeing 747-200s that used to sell for about $27.5 million now
are commanding up to $32 million,'' Turk said. ``Some even have gone
as high as $38 million.''
   The 747 went into service in January 1970, and the
larger-capacity 747-200 in November 1971. Many 747-200s sold for
less than $30 million new.
   Newer used planes, when available, sell for much more, such as
$40 million for a 747-200 model that can be used for passengers and
cargo, and $75 million for a used 747-300, a model that went into
service in February 1983.
   The eight planes now on the market aren't going to be available
until next year because their owners, KLM Dutch Airlines and
Singapore Airlines, have had their 747-400s delayed by Boeing, Turk
said.
</TEXT>
