<FIRST>u f PM-ThriftHearing 1stLd-Writethru   03-10 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thrift Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Banking Committee Chairman Calls For Resignation of Federal
Regulators</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs next to last graf to CORRECT numbers of thrifts taken over
this year to 118 nationally and 36 in Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the U.S. House banking
committee called today for the resignation of federal savings and
loan regulators after hearing a government report that the thrift
crisis could have been handled more efficiently.
   U.S. Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, chairman of the House Banking,
Finance, and Urban Affairs Committee, which is conducting a field
hearing on thrift problems, has been critical of M. Danny Wall, the
chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   Gonzalez' comments seeking the resignation came after testimony
by Frederick D. Wolf, assistant comptroller geneneral of the General
Accounting Office, who said that the handling of the savings and
loan problems could have been handled in a less-costly manner.
   Wolf said the deficit for the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corp. had at least quadrupled between 1987 and 1988 when it began
takeover of insolvent thrifts.
   ``Those deals were terribly expensive and our thinking is that
there could have been more ways you could have done it less
costly,'' he said.
   ``We are still in the process of doing the audit and the number
may be higher than lower,'' Wolf said.
   Gonzalez interrupted Wolf's testimony to say that the new figures
contradict testimony by Wall and others before the committee earlier
this year.
   ``I just feel under these circumstances, the Congress, and
therefore the public, have been disgracefully misinformed. The
persons responsible should step aside at this time,'' Gonzalez said,
reiterating his criticism of Wall.
   Federal and state officials are scheduled to testify in the
two-day hearing looking into the savings and loan crisis. Wall is
not among the witnesses scheduled to testify.
   So far this year, 118 savings and loan institutions have been
taken over by federal regulators, including 36 in Texas.
   Wolf said that he believed the administration's projection to
spend $100 billion to rectify the thrift crisis was adequate.
</TEXT>
