<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-US-Japan-Trade Bjt   03-10 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Not Worried That U.S. Will Set Tougher Trade Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan does not fear a tougher trade policy will
emerge from Washington because the United States would be unlikely
to further restrict trade with Japan while it promotes a free-trade
policy with the rest of the world, officials say.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills has established a task
force that is considering ``managed trade'' as part of a review of
how to reduce the United States' $52 billion trade deficit with
Japan.
   A policy of managed trade could include specific targets for
increased Japanese purchases of U.S. products and reductions in the
trade imbalance.
   But Japanese officials do not appear worried that such changes
will be implemented.
   ``I think Mrs. Hills has reservations about managed trade and her
basic stance is still toward free trade,'' said Shin Yasunobe, an
official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI).
   ``The United States would have a difficult time promoting its
basic commitment to multilateral free trade and at the same time
moving toward managed trade with Japan,'' added Yasunobe, deputy
director of the Americas and Oceanic division at MITI.
   Other ministry officials see recent criticisms of Japan by Mrs.
Hills as politically motivated. It is necessary for her to display a
tough attitude toward Japan, they say, to win approval for the team
she wants in the new administration.
   They concede, however, that she may turn out to be tough.
   MITI officials see a trade policy vacuum right now in the U.S.
government. With few U.S. officials concerned with formulating
economic and trade policy in place, they believe Mrs. Hills has
little support currently for setting new policies.
   Ministry officials say they don't expect anything concrete to
emerge in trade policy from the United States until mid-May, after
Mrs. Hills' deputies are confirmed and have been briefed.
   When that happens, the two sides can have a meaningful exchange
of views, they say.
   ``We do not support managed trade,'' said Yoshio Nakamura, head
of U.S.-Japan economic relations at Keidanren, Japan's powerful
Federation of Economic Organizations.
   But, he added, Japan already has ``managed trade'' with the
United States in automobiles, steel and semiconductors. Japan has
adhered to voluntary restraint agreements for steel and auto exports
to the United States for several years. It agreed in 1986 to
encourage foreign semiconductor sales in Japan.
   While the United States complains that Japanese markets are
closed to its products, Japanese government officials and business
leaders believe there is little correlation between market access
and the trade imbalance.
   ``Since 1980 we have, in response to U.S. pressure, enhanced
access to Japanese markets,'' Nakamura said. ``But while Japanese
markets have become more open, the trade imbalance has worsened.''
   ``It is almost nonsense to measure the openness of the market by
looking only at the trade imbalance,'' said Yasunobe, the MITI
official. ``Even Mrs. Hills admits the imbalance is the outcome of
macroeconomic policies and structures.''
   Greater coordination of these policies is needed, the officials
say, along with a reduction in the U.S. budget deficit, reduced
consumer demand in the United States, and greater stimulation of
Japan's domestic economy.
   Nakamura said what happens in the trade relationship between the
two countries will likely depend on trade statistics in the coming
months.
   ``If they worsen, the frustration level will be higher in the
U.S. Congress and administration, and Japan will be in a bad
position. Hills may have to take strong action against Japan,''
Nakamura said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
