<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated today, faced with news
of continuing strong growth in employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 14.11 points to
2,277.32 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 481 up, 884 down and
514 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported that the civilian unemployment rate
fell to 5.1 percent, a 15-year low, in February from 5.4 percent the
month before.
   The report also showed an increase of 289,000 in nonfarm payroll
employment, topping most advance estimates.
   Wall Street had been anxiously awaiting the report all week,
hoping for new evidence that economic growth was slowing, taking
upward pressure off inflation and interest rates.
   So the figures were poorly received in both the bond and stock
markets. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, fell about $5 for each
$1,000 in face value.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down | at 118; General Electric, down | at 44~; General
Motors, down { at 85, and American Express, down } at 29~.
   Upjohn dropped ] to 29 after losing 2\ points Thursday.
Responding to an analyst's report, the company said it was too soon
to gauge the effect of new prescription procedures in New York State
on sales of two Upjohn tranquilizers.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.81 to 164.55. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .76 at 328.60.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.34 million shares with two
hours to go.
