<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MicrosoftSuit     03-10 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Microsoft Suit,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microsoft Shareholder Sues Company Over Big Stock Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Microsoft Corp. shareholder has filed a federal
class-action lawsuit alleging the computer software publisher and
two of its officers violated U.S. securities laws by misleading
stockholders about the company's financial outlook.
   Microsoft shareholders were damaged when the price of the stock
plummeted 13.7 percent Tuesday after Microsoft announced it faced
lower-than-expected third-quarter sales and profits, according to
allegations in the suit filed in U.S. District Court in Seattle by
Bruce Adelstein.
   The suit says Microsoft gave no indication in the weeks before
the announcement that it was facing any problems. It seeks
undetermined compensatory and punitive damages.
   ``We are reviewing the plaintiff's claims and we believe them to
be entirely without merit,'' William H. Neukom, Microsoft vice
president of law and corporate affairs, said in a news release
Friday. ``Microsoft intends to defend the case vigorously. The case
is now before the courts and Microsoft will not offer comment
outside of this statement.''
   In addition to Microsoft, the suit names as plaintiffs Jon A.
Shirley, Microsoft president and chief operating officer, and
Francis J. Gaudette, the company's vice president, treasurer and
chief financial officer. Microsoft co-founder and chairman Bill
Gates is not listed as a defendant.
   Microsoft's stock, traded over the counter, dropped by $8.50 a
share to $53.50 Tuesday after the company announced it expected
lower profits and sales for its third quarter ending March 31st. It
would be the first time quarterly profits declined since the company
went public three years ago.
   Microsoft blamed the lower forecast on delays in shipping new
versions of its word-processing software, Microsoft Word, and
overstocking by key distributors.
   Microsoft predicted third-quarter sales at $180 million to $200
million, down from the $200 million to $215 million expected by many
market analysts.
   The company had sales of $161.8 million and profits of $37.3
million in the third quarter of last year. It said it expected
profits for the current quarter ``to be somewhat less than a year
ago.''
   Adelstein's Seattle attorney, Steven Berman, said the suit
alleges that in a quarterly report filed Feb. 10 with the Securities
and Exchange Commission and in conferences with investors and
analysts that month, Microsoft and its executives gave no indication
of the inventory problems or that shipments of the new Word versions
would be delayed.
   The suit says that ``as a direct result of the company's belated
disclosures'' of the problems Tuesday, ``the market's response to
Microsoft's announcement was swift and severe.''
   It alleges the Microsoft officers misled stockholders to protect
their jobs, enhance the value of their Microsoft stock and holdings,
``and cover up their own prior misconduct and mismangement of
Microsoft and avoid being held responsible.''
   The class named in the suit covers investors who bought Microsoft
stock between Jan. 19 and March 6. Berman said he didn't know how
many people that covered, although 19 million shares of Microsoft
were traded during that period.
   Adelstein bought 1,400 shares of Microsoft on Feb. 10, when the
stock closed at $63 a share, Berman said.
   ``He bought on the upswing because he read the news and so forth
and was pretty unhappy at what happened,'' Berman said.
   With the $8.50-a-share drop, Adelstein's stock would have lost
$11,900 in value on Tuesday. In contrast, Shirley, listed in the
suit as owning 638,400 shares, faced an on-paper loss of $5.4
million, while Gaudette, listed as having 33,334 shares, saw his
stock drop by $283,339.
   Gates, with over 20 million shares, took a paper loss of about
$174 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
