<FIRST>r f BC-GrainProduction     03-10 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Grain Production,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Season Wheat Output Could Reach Record Level</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recovery in world wheat production to possibly a
record 540 million metric tons in the 1989-90 season was tentatively
forecast Friday by the International Wheat Council.
   The council _ one of the world's leading wheat forecasting bodies
_ revised its 1988-89 world wheat crop estimate to 504 million from
502 million in January.
   This compares with 512 million produced in 1987-88 and the record
538 million in 1986-87.
   The estimate for the season running from June 1989 to July 1990
is based on an expected increase in planting and good growing
conditions, the council said.
   ``It must be stressed that the final outcome will depend on the
weather and crop developments over the next few months,'' the
council said, noting that sowing in some parts of the world has not
yet begun.
   Production forecasts for 1989-90 include the Soviet Union 90.0
million tons (84.5 million estimated for 1988-89), China 89.0
million (87.0 million), the European Economic Community 86.2 million
(86.1 million), the United States 65.0 million (49.3 million), India
49.0 million (44.5 million), Canada 26.0 million (15.5 million),
Turkey 19.0 million (18.5 million), Australia 14.0 million (14.3
million), Argentina 8.2 million (8.0 million) and Brazil 5.0 million
(5.9 million).
   For the 1988-89 season, output of coarse grains _ principally
corn _ is now estimated at 725 million tons this season (800 million
tons in 1987-88).
   World wheat trade in 1988-89 is estimated to fall to 98 million
tons from a record 106 million in 1987-88 because of lower Soviet
and Indian imports.
   Soviet wheat imports are put at 14.0 million (22.0 million last
season) and Indian imports at 2.1 million (3.0 million).
   The council expects China to overtake the Soviet Union as the
world's biggest wheat importer in 1988-89, buying a record 16.6
million tons compared with 15.3 million in 1987-88.
   World coarse grain trade in 1988-89 is put at 97.0 million tons,
against 86.0 million last season.
   Soviet imports of coarse grains in 1988-89 are estimated at 21.0
million tons (9.0 million in 1987-88).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
