<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-EEC-USTrade 1stLd-Writethru   03-10 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-US Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-EEC Officials Meet to Discuss Trade Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs with talks beginning; picks up 15th graf
pvs, The Common ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top American trade negotiators met
Friday with officials of the European Economic Community for a
series of talks focusing on the troublesome issue of farm subsidies.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and Trade Representative
Carla Hills met for about two hours with the Common Market's top
foreign affairs official, Frans Andriessen, and its agriculture
chief, Ray MacSharry.
   Nico Wegter, spokesman for the 12-nation trading bloc, said the
discussions were held in a ``constructive atmosphere'' but provided
no details.
   The officials were having dinner together Friday night and
continuing their talks Saturday morning. Yeutter and Mrs. Hills were
scheduled to leave Brussels later Saturday.
   The officials are trying to find ways to ease a conflict between
the United States and the community over government subsidies to
farmers before the resumption of international trade talks April 5
in Geneva. The dispute has stalled the Uruguay Round negotiations,
held under the auspices of the 96-nation General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   The United States wants the Common Market to end import barriers
and export and domestic farm subsidies that it says distort trade.
It initially demanded the subsidies be eliminated by the year 2000.
   An American proposal offered last month to the Europeans seeks to
gradually lower farm subsidies. A U.S. statement said the plan
``does not use language strongly opposed by the (community) that
specifically calls for elimination of trade-distorting subsidies by
a certain date.''
   The community has refused to agree on a date for withdrawing all
supports and wants the United States to include short-term reform
measures in the debate.
   The Common Market provides hefty subsidies to its 18 million
farmers through guaranteed prices for many of their crops. It also
gives exporters help so costlier European farm products can compete
with lower world prices.
   The United States complains the export subsidies have helped the
community increase its share of the world market. It has responded
by setting up its own Export Enhancement Program.
   A year ago, European leaders began the politically sensitive task
of curbing farm payments. They agreed to limit the maximum annual
amount of expenditure on price guarantees over five years. U.S.
officials say the measures were not enough to fix a fundamentally
flawed policy.
   Europeans argue they cannot leave the bulk of their farmers to
compete without help in the world market. Their farms, they say, are
on average smaller than in the United States and need extra aid.
   The four officials held a round of get-acquainted talks in
Feburary in Washington during which they agreed to set up a task
force to try to resolve a dispute over a European ban on imports of
hormone-treated meat from the United States. The task force has
until early May to complete its findings.
   The Common Market imposed on Jan. 1 a ban on imports of meat from
cattle treated with growth hormones. The United States refused to
comply and instead slapped stiff duties on a variety of European
products.
   The Europeans have threatened to impose their own retaliatory
measures _ tough tariffs on American walnuts and dried fruit _ if
the conflict isn't resolved.
   The hormone ban was imposed because of European concerns the
stimulants pose a health risk to consumers, a claim the United
States disputes.
   The ban is expected to block imports of about $100 million worth
of beef and beef byproducts from the United States. The trading
partners totaled about $165 billion worth of trade in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890310-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-RJRDebt     03-10 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR Debt,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;P Lowers Rating on RJR Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. announced Friday it has
lowered its rating on $5 billion of RJR Nabisco Inc. debt because of
the $24.53 billion leveraged buyout of the food and tobacco company
by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Standard &amp; Poor's, a credit rating service, said it was lowering
RJR Nabisco's A rating to BB.
   Preferred stock and convertible debentures to be issued in
connection with the buyout are expected to receive a B plus rating,
Standard &amp; Poor's said.
   Standard &amp; Poor's announced it was reassessing RJR Nabisco's debt
rating last fall, after the company's managers said they were
considering a leveraged buyout of the firm. Management lost a
bidding war to Kohlberg Kravis, which is in the process of carrying
out its own LBO.
   A leveraged buyout _ which is accomplished with largely borrowed
funds _ sharply increases the debt load of a company and can raise
questions about its ability to repay its loans.
   An A rating _ the third-highest in the Standard &amp; Poor's rankings
_ is given to debt that ``has a strong capacity to pay interest and
repay principal although it is somewhat more susceptible to the
adverse effects of changes in circumstances and economic conditions
than debt in higher rated categories.''
   The highest Standard &amp; Poor rating is AAA.
   A rating of BB is fifth on the Standard &amp; Poor's list, and is the
highest of five grades assigned to debt on which there is
speculation about the issuer's ability to pay interest and repay
principal. It is followed by B.
   ``While such debt will likely have some quality and protective
characteristics, these are outweighed by large uncertainties or
major risk exposures to adverse conditions,'' Standard &amp; Poor's said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
