<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge; Nuclear Mishap, Volcano Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower Friday
on the Chicago Board of Trade after whipsawing late in the session
on reports of a nuclear mishap in West Germany and a volcano in
Guatemala.
   ``Ooh, boy, it was wild,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Grain futures finished mixed.
   The markets started out mixed, then rallied at midday following
wire-service reports of a nuclear reactor breakdown in Wiesbaden,
West Germany.
   Traders, recalling the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear accident,
frantically bought futures contracts on fears of European crop
contamination. But the buyers quickly became sellers on follow-up
reports that no radiation had leaked from the reactor.
   Two out of four emergency cooling systems at the Biblis nuclear
power plant problems temporarily broke down, the Hesse state
government said.
   Selling accelerated shortly thereafter on reports of a volcano
eruption in Guatemala. Lespinasse said a private meteorologist had
said last week that a volcano eruption would reduce the likelihood
of a U.S. drought this summer because an increased number of
particles in the air could encourage rainfall.
   The Pacayo Volcano spewed lava, ash and sand on Friday,
destroying coffee plantations in the path of the molten rock,
seismologists said. They said the eruption was not dangerous.
   At the close, wheat was } cent lower to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.35 a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to 2\ cents higher with March at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were {
cent lower to } cent higher with March at $2.07 a bushel; soybeans
were 4 cents to 11 cents lower with March at $7.57 a bushel.
