<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 2302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TimeWarner-Neuharth     03-10 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time Warner-Neuharth,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gannett Chairman: Discussed Possibility of Merger with Time in 1985</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of Gannett Co. Inc. and Time Inc.
discussed the possibility of a merger in 1985 but disagreed on
whether the company should be run with co-chief executives, Gannett
Chairman Allen Neuharth said Friday.
   Neuharth made his remarks in a column published in Gannett's USA
Today newspaper, commenting on Time's agreement to merge with Warner
Communications Inc. The deal calls for co-chief executives to run
the company initially.
   The Gannett chairman wrote that he and J. Richard Munro, Time's
chief executive, ``were of one mind on the merits of a merger of
Gannett and Time.''
   ``But we had two very diverse views about creating a two-headed
monster,'' Neuharth wrote.
   He said after he and Munro had several discusssions, Munro sent
Sol Linowitz, a former Time director, to ``try to sell me on the
co-CEO idea.''
   ``I didn't buy it, because I knew it wouldn't work. I'd had
experience before in 50-50 partnerships, large and small. Nothing
happens,'' Neuharth said.
   Neuharth said Munro also had ``preached that philosophy'' about
co-CEOs to Thomas Wyman, who was chief executive of CBS Inc. in
1985. He did not say what Wyman's reaction was. Wyman was forced out
by the CBS board in November 1986.
   In their merger agreement, Time and Warner said the new company
to be called Time Warner Inc. initially would be headed by co-chief
executives _ Munro from Time and Steven J. Ross from Warner.
   But the longer-term plan is for N.J. Nicholas, Time's president,
to succeed Munro as co-chief executive in two years and eventually
become sole chief executive.
   Time spokesman Louis Slovinsky said Friday his company had no
comment on Neuharth's assertions and that Munro was unavailable. A
call was placed to a spokesman for CBS but it was not immediately
returned.
   A Gannett spokeswoman said she had nothing to add and that
Neuharth was unavailable.
   There were published reports in the summer of 1985 that Gannett
had made advances to both CBS and Time, although a Gannett spokesman
at the time refused to confirm or deny them.
   Time, a leading book and magazine publisher with interests in
cable programming and cable TV systems, announced last Saturday that
it had agreed to a merger with Warner, the film and record giant.
   Time Warner would have an estimated $10 billion in revenue,
making it the world's largest communications concern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
