<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Ticketholders Bjt   03-10 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Ticketholders, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Bankruptcy Filing Grounds Many Ticketholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warwick, R.I., job counselor Robert MacDonald
knew about Eastern Airlines' labor problems when he booked a flight
to Dothan, Ala., on the carrier two months ago, but he couldn't
resist the low ticket price.
   Now he's paying for it _ several hundred dollars to be precise.
   When Eastern filed for federal bankruptcy law protection this
past week in the midst of a crippling strike, MacDonald had to find
a last-minute, costlier flight on another airline.
   He's one of the luckier ones.
   Many more Eastern ticketholders have been grounded, forced to
cancel travel plans because a number of other booked carriers aren't
honoring their tickets and they can't afford to make other
arrangements, travel agents said Friday.
   Worse, a few others that flew one way before the Eastern strike
began a week ago have been stranded, the agents said. Some booked on
package deals linked with Eastern have faced other problems, they
said.
   One man who surprised his wife for their anniversary by whisking
her away for a five-day stay in Florida found a Key West hotel
wouldn't honor the room voucher that came as part of the Eastern
package, said Maija Groden, manager of Church Travel in Warwick, R.I.
   ``Fortunately he was able to stay at the condo of a friend
there,'' Groden said.
   In Miami, Eastern ticketholder Mary Jennings complained to a
local television station, ``We don't know if we're going to be
life-time Floridians, or if we get to go back home.''
   Jennings had a cruise deal that included roundtrip tickets on
Eastern to the busy Port of Miami.
   ``Eastern has told us that our tickets are nonrefundable. On our
cruise line we learned later that Continental (Airlines) would honor
them, but they can't even guarantee that,'' Jennings said.
   ``It's all very confusing right now,'' said Marsha Thompson, a
travel agent with DMS Travel in New York. ``Nobody's quite sure what
to do.''
   She said her company, like other travel firms, had been steering
clients away from Eastern when its labor problems intensified
several weeks ago. But a few that already booked Eastern flights are
now forced to change their plans.
   Thompson said one woman, who had planned to fly on Eastern as
part of a $2,000 eight-day Florida cruise package, will have to pay
about $500 more for roundtrip tickets on another airline or scrap
her plans.
   ``It was a Disney-beach-cruise deal. Her daughter will be real
disappointed if they don't go,'' Thompson said.
   Many cruise lines, however, have arranged for flights on other
airlines for passengers booked on package deals linked to Eastern at
no extra cost, said Tim Gallagher, a spokesman for Carnival Cruise
Lines in Miami.
   ``It hasn't been easy, but we're getting them all protected,'' he
said.
   Miami-based Eastern _ the nation's seventh-largest airline with
1,000 flights a day before the strike _ said $200 million worth of
tickets were in the hands of passengers and other airlines when it
filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the Federal
Bankruptcy Act on Thursday.
   In the eyes of the bankruptcy court, ticketholders are unsecured
creditors, trailing secured creditors in priority. That means it may
be some time before they can get refunds, if ever.
   Those who paid for tickets on a major credit card, however, may
have an easier time, since a federal law protects consumers who make
credit-card purchases but fail to receive goods or services.
   Eastern has promised to get as many planes airborne as possible
as it reorganizes under bankruptcy protection and make good on old
tickets.
   Nonetheless, travel agents said they're not optimistic.
   ``We haven't been selling Eastern wholeheartedly in the last
eight months ... I don't know if we will ever again,'' said Jack
Bloch, owner of JB's World Travel in New York.
   Others say it may take some time for strike-burdened passengers
to forgive and forget.
   Among those are MacDonald, owner of an employee-assistance
company in Rhode Island, who in January bought a restricted $280.50
Eastern roundtrip ticket to Dothan, Ala., as a gift for his
daughter, Nancy. He had to shell out $320.50 more for tickets on
another airline after the strike.
   ``I now have another set of tickets lost in limbo,'' MacDonald
said, although he admits he was partly to blame. ``I bought these
tickets even though they were talking about a strike because they
were the cheapest around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
