<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-10 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar wound up the week on a strong note
Friday, finishing higher against most major currencies amid buying
inspired by the government's report of a decline in unemployment.
   Gold prices slipped in domestic dealings after rising overseas.
At 4 p.m. EST, Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of
$393.50 for a troy ounce of gold, 30 cents lower than Thursday's
late bid.
   As currency trading got under way in the United States, the Labor
Department reported the February unemployment rate fell to a 15-year
low of 5.1 percent from 5.4 percent in January. Payroll growth was
strong, with 289,000 new non-farm jobs created during the month, the
report from Washington said.
   Foreign exchange dealers interprepted the figures as evidence of
robust economic activity. The view touched off a rally in the
dollar, which pushed the U.S. currency to 1.8660 West German marks
in London trading.
   ``The reaction to the unemployment report was logical,'' said
Jesse Torres, Bank of Boston's chief dealer in New York.
   Stephen Leach, a currency analyst at Chemical Bank, said
broad-based dollar buying steadily continued for much of the session
until close to the end.
   He said the rally ran out of steam as activity slackened toward
the end of New York's session, which normally happens ahead of a
weekend. The loss in the rally's momentum also occurred because
dealers decided to collect profits.
   There were unconfirmed rumors that the Federal Reserve Board had
intervened, selling dollars to slow the advance. But dealers said
there was no proof that the central bank had come into the market.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.35 yen to a closing 128.88 yen.
   The dollar headed higher as trading centers opened in other
cities around the globe. In London, it was quoted at 129.46 yen, and
late in New York's business day it was quoted at 129.40, up from
128.80 on Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7159 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7183 late Thursday. By the
time dealing was done for the day in New York, sterling fetched
$1.7177 compared to Thursday's $1.7220.
   Other later dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates, included: 1.86175 West German marks, up from 1.85625;
1.58975 Swiss francs, up from 1.58555; 1.1987 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.19925; 6.314 French francs, up from 6.2975; and 1,366.75
Italian lire, up from 1,363.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
levels included: 1.8629 West German marks, up from 1.8600; 1.5918
Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 6.3185 French francs, up from 6.3125;
2.1020 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1000; 1,366.00 Italian lire,
unchanged; and, 1.1987 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2000.
   Gold prices finished mixed and silver prices rose.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $394.30 a troy ounce, down from $395.10 Thursday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $393.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $391.55 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold rose to close at a bid $393.50 from $391.75 bid
late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.58 to close at a bid $396.08.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $5.88. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery settled at $6.068 a troy ounce, up from Thursday's
settlement of $6.008.
</TEXT>
