<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     03-10 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goverment bond prices tumbled Friday in response
to news of strong employment growth in February.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond skidded } point, or about
$7.50 per $1,000 in face amount, while its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from its price, jumped to 9.14 percent from 9.06
percent late Thursday.
   A new Labor Department report said the nation's unemployment rate
in February fell to 5.1 percent, the lowest point in 15 years, as
employers created 289,000 new jobs. The report also boosted the
estimate of January job growth to 415,000 from 408,000 previously
reported.
   The growth in non-farm payrolls suggested efforts to slow
economic activity to reduce upward pressures on prices have not had
much effect.
   Kevin Flanagan, a money market economist at Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., said the report indicated ``new job creation hasn't been
slowed at all.''
   ``It has gotten some people nervous about what the Fed might do
next,'' he said.
   The Federal Reserve has taken steps in recent weeks to encourage
higher interest rates in a bid to slow the economy and reduce
inflationary pressures. Bond prices deteriorate when interest rates
go up, but bond values are also eroded by inflation.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments were off by between \ point and ] point,
intermediate maturities lost { point and long-term issues fell as
much as ~ point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial information
service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, dropped 5.31 to 1,118.83.
   Corporate bonds moved modestly lower. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate
bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.80 to 298.12.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3-16 point to 9019-32. The average yield
to maturity rose to 7.72 percent from 7.70 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 9.05 percent as the
discount rose 8 basis points to 8.74 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 9.30 percent as the discount rose 14 basis points to
8.78 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.54 percent as the
discount rose 12 basis points to 8.79 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 9} percent, down from 913-16 percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
