<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Machinists Bjt   03-10 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Machinists, Bjt,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Machinists Say Chapter 11 Won't Kill Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines Machinists said Friday
they would file their own plan to rescue the carrier from bankruptcy
and they denounced management for threatening to split the union by
replacing unskilled members.
   Bolstered by crucial support on the picket lines they've received
from Eastern's pilots, the Machinists said they'll continue striking
together in the face of what they call the company's
``divide-and-conquer'' strategy.
   ``We went out on strike together, we'll go back together,'' Roy
Anderson, a Machinists general chairman in Miami, said Friday. ``The
idea of a union is everyone's together.''
   He insisted that Eastern's petition for protection from creditors
under the bankruptcy laws, filed Thursday in a New York court,
hasn't daunted the Machinists' spirit.
   ``There is no incentive for people to go back,'' Anderson said.
   The Machinist strategists said they plan to fight in bankruptcy
court any company attempts to split the union.
   They said they'll also seek an emergency court order against
sales of Eastern assets, notably the plan to sell its profitable
Northeast shuttle service to developer Donald Trump.
   In addition, they said they'll try to bring Eastern's parent
Texas Air Corp. and sister carrier Continental Airlines into the
bankruptcy proceedings; and to change the court location of the
proceedings from New York to Miami.
   The Machinists plan to present an alternative reorganization plan
to the court that calls for the sale of Eastern intact to an outside
party, according to sources close to the union.
   The union is seeking such a sale ``so we've got a live asset to
move,'' said a source, who requested anonymity.
   Financier Carl Icahn, chairman of Eastern rival Trans World
Airlines, publicly expressed interest several months ago in
acquiring Eastern. Icahn reportedly has been asked in recent days by
Eastern union representatives to consider a buyout.
   The Chapter 11 filing would still allow a takeover but would
force approval by the bankruptcy court as well as by Eastern unions
and creditors.
   When Eastern officials announced the filing Thursday, they
addressed the two factions within the Machinists union separately.
The 8,500 members of the International Association of Machinists at
Eastern are divided into two categories: aircraft mechanics and ramp
service workers.
   The mechanics, the more skilled of the two groups, earn a top
wage of $18.83 an hour at Eastern. The less skilled ramp workers,
who fuel planes, handle baggage and drive motorized equipment on
airport runways, make top pay of $15.60 an hour.
   If Eastern's pilots could be induced to return to work, ``much of
the (ground) work will be contracted out,'' Eastern President Phil
Bakes told a news conference. ``If our mechanics come back to work,
they will get paid.
   ``The Machinists chose to leave their jobs. The majority of the
Machinists union are not mechanics. The majority are cleaners,
baggage handlers, stock clerks, janitors.''
   Eastern has arranged for those types of work to be done ``with
outside vendors, some that are serving other airlines,'' Bakes said.
   Bakes apparently was holding out a carrot to the skilled
mechanics, which Eastern needs almost as much as the pilots, and a
stick to the ramp workers, who could be replaced relatively easily.
   That approach might not get a warm reception from the bankruptcy
judge, a legal expert suggested.
   ``What (a judge) would be looking to do is to bring the parties
together,'' said William Ury, associate director of the program on
negotiation at Harvard Law School.
   The Machinists could be successful in court in blocking efforts
to split the union, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
