<FIRST>u f AM-ThriftHearing     03-10 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thrift Hearing,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gonzalez: Tax Increase For Thrift Crisis Would Save $138 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raising taxes to solve the savings and loan
crisis could save taxpayers $138 billion over the next 30 years, a
congressman critical of federal regulators' handling of the crisis
said Friday.
   Congress and Americans were misinformed about the costs of saving
the troubled thrift industry, said U.S. Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, who
also suggested top thrift regulators step aside after he heard that
the deficit of the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. had
quadrupled from $14 billion in 1987 to at least $56 billion in 1988.
   Gonzalez, a Democrat from San Antonio who is chairman of the
House Banking, Finance and Urban Affairs Committee, is conducting a
two-day field hearing on the S&amp;L crisis.
   Gonzalez was highly critical of M. Danny Wall, chairman of the
Home Loan Bank Board, which administers the FSLIC.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
said the agency's figure for the 1988 FSLIC deficit is closer to $45
billion and complained that the General Accounting Office ``arrived
at their number without the benefit of having talked to us.''
   Hoyle said Wall has testified before the House Banking Committee
that the size of the S&amp;L problem was $75 billion to $80 billion. He
said that could not be directly compared with the FSLIC deficit.
   ``Clearly Mr. Gonzalez is mixing up apples and oranges,'' Hoyle
said.
   Frederick Wolf, assistant comptroller general of the General
Accounting Office, fueled the criticism of Wall after telling the
committee the Southwest Plan to bail out insolvent thrifts was too
costly.
   ``The deals were terribly expensive and we think there could have
been more ways you could have done it less costly,'' Wolf told the
committee.
   ``We are still in the process of doing the audit, so the numbers
may be higher than lower,'' he said about the FSLIC deficit.
   Wolf said solving the crisis would cost at least $140 billion _
$60 billion for the deals already made, $50 billion for the current
insolvents and another $30 billion for the future insolvencies.
   He also said the cost would not have been as great if the
government had taken steps to solve the problem three years ago.
   ``Even using accounting numbers we believe you could have known
that the problem was bigger than what (Wall) was saying. We've had
other hearings where we've both been there and we've disagreed about
the numbers,'' Wolf told reporters after his testimony.
   Gonzalez, meanwhile, suggested that raising taxes, instead of
borrowing, could save taxpayers' money even if it meant not
complying with the Gramm-Rudmann budget balancing law.
   ``I don't see why we should pay $138 billion, just to make Gramm
look good,'' he said.
   Gonzalez said Wall as late as January had not told the committee
about the FSLIC's deficit.
   ``These statistics refute the testimony we've had,'' Gonzalez
said. ``I just feel under these circumstances the Congress and the
American public was so disgracefully misinformed.
   ``The persons responsible should step aside at this time,'' he
said while criticizing Wall.
   ``There is something wrong somewhere. How can we allow a
quasi-independent agency to in effect authorize and appropriate
without going through those regular procedures that even the
president can't do. The president wouldn't be able on his own do
what Danny Wall did last December,'' Gonzalez said.
   Wolf, meanwhile, said that he would not be surprised if half the
tax dollars spent on solving the S&amp;L crisis were spent in Texas.
   So far this year, 118 savings and loan institutions have been
taken over by federal regulators, including 36 in Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
