<FIRST>u f AM-WesternUnion-TelecomUSA     03-10 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Western Union-Telecom USA,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Union Sells Network Services Business To Telecom USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telecom USA has agreed to acquire Western
Union Corp.'s private line and switched long-distance voice
business, the companies announced Friday.
   The services, which have been provided by Western Union's Network
Services unit, produced revenue of about $72 million in 1988,
according to a written statement jointly issued by the companies.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   The acquisition is structured as a cash purchase of customer
accounts and is contingent upon regulatory approvals, the companies
said.
   ``Acquisition will continue to be an important aspect of Telecom
USA's growth strategy,'' said Telecom USA Chairman O. Gene Gabbard.
``It is our goal to increase our revenue by 25 percent through
internal marketing efforts and an additional 25 percent through the
Western Union transaction and other acquisitions.''
   Telecom USA advertises itself as the nation's fourth largest
long-distance carrier and is the holding company for regional
long-distance carriers Southern-Net USA and Teleconnect USA. It owns
and operates an all-digital fiber optic network with 14 digital
switching centers and provides national service through its
membership in the National Telecommunications Network.
   Western Union, based in Upper Saddle River, provides messaging
and financial services, both national and internationally.
   The company underwent a major restructuring late in 1987 because
of financial problems that pushed it to the brink of bankruptcy. The
reorganization included the merger of Western Union and its Western
Union Telegraph Co. subsidiary, the purchase of ITT Corp.'s
international telex service an exchange of its debt for stock in the
restructured company.
   Western Union last week reported a $244 million loss in
fourth-quarter 1988 earnings, which it attributed to restructuring
charges.
</TEXT>
