<SECOND>AM-Channel One,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Channel One Plans Live Broadcast of Space Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Channel One, the new service that is beaming
daily news shows with commercials into six schools, said Friday it
plans to produce its first live broadcast on Monday with coverage of
the space shuttle launch.
   The special broadcast, which will contain no commercials, will be
sent to the six schools participating in the test of the new service
for use at their discretion, the programs creators said.
   Channel One is a service of Whittle Communications LP, a
Knoxville, Tenn.-based media concern that has given about $50,000 in
televisions, video equipment and satellite dishes to each of the six
test schools to receive its daily 12-minute news show. Each show
contains up to two minutes of paid ads.
   Some educators have denounced the project, which debuted Monday,
for permitting advertisers to intrude into the classrooms.
   The space launch coverage will be separate from the daily news
show. It will feature live video supplied by NASA via satellite
along with commentary from the Los Angeles studio by the regular
Channel One news anchors and a space travel expert.
   The Discovery launch is tentatively scheduled for Monday morning.
   William S. Rukeyser, editor-in-chief of Whittle Communications,
said the plans for a live broadcast provide ``an exciting example of
what Channel One can do.''
   The six schools involved in the test are Eisenhower Middle School
in Kansas City, Kan.; Withrow High School in Cincinnati; Mumford
High School in Detroit; Central High School in Knoxville, Tenn.;
Billerica Memorial High School near Boston and Gahr High School in
Cerritos, Calif.
</TEXT>
