<FIRST>b f AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru   03-10 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists To Fight In Court For Their Pay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, Lifland's orders ..., to CORRECT that Machinists
lawyer criticized Eastern's action, sted judge's order.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Eastern Airlines Machinists said
Friday they will mount a legal battle to get wages owed to striking
union members and repeated accusations that the crippled carrier
timed its bankruptcy filing to make sure workers went unpaid.
   Machinists who expected to be paid Thursday instead had their
final pre-strike paychecks withheld by Eastern as part of its
petition for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal Bankruptcy Code.
   All of Eastern's expenditures and business transactions now must
be approved by the bankruptcy court.
   Robert Clayman, a Washington-based attorney for the Machinists,
said he would file papers soon in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan
to ``correct the pay situation ``and make sure these employees get
paid as quickly as possible.''
   Sources estimate the 8,500 Machinists are owed about $7.5 million
for the week.
   The Machinists are particularly irked because a federal judge
overseeing the bankruptcy has signed orders allowing Eastern to
compensate other employees who have continued working instead of
joining the strike.
   Federal Judge Burton R. Lifland on Thursday authorized the
carrier to pay its employees working outside the United States _ in
Central and South America and the Caribbean _ provide benefits and
salary and reimburse expenses for other currently working Eastern
employees.
   Eastern's timing of its Bankruptcy Court petition ``really
rankled the people,'' Clayman said.
   ``It seems not coincidental that the timing of the bankruptcy was
intended to deny these employees the wages for the work they
performed,'' he said. Clayman said he will stress that issue when he
files court documents.
   A number of union officials voiced similar complaints on
Thursday, after Eastern made its filing.
   Attorneys for Eastern, however, were upbeat about the court
action. Eastern attorney Bruce Zirinsky said the signing of the
orders represented ``a fair amount of movement'' in what is certain
to be a lengthly court proceeding.
   While no further hearings have been scheduled, Zirinsky said a
meeting would be held within the next two weeks to organize an
official creditors committee. The panel ultimately will have a say
in Eastern's reorganization plan for emerging from Chapter 11.
   Zirinisky also said Eastern's creditors ``already are beginning
to communicate with us as well as the company and with each other.''
He said creditors were requesting information on the affects of the
bankruptcy filing and ``are indicating that they are interested in
assisting Eastern.''
   Nearly 20 attorneys are working on the case for Eastern and its
parent, Texas Air Corp. ``Things are moving very smoothly,''
Zirinsky said.
   Meanwhile, spokesman David Jimenez, a spokesman for Seattle-based
Boeing Co., said the company is not worried about the $54 million it
is owed by Eastern. ``We're confident we're going to be paid,'' he
said.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo and other Eastern executives
have vowed all creditors will be paid and shareholders will receive
``fair value.''
   At the Bank of New York, trustee for about $150 million unsecured
bonds held by nearly 4,000 bondholders, spokesman Owen Brady said
the bank was ``consulting with its counsel to determine what actions
would be appropriate for us to take in terms of our responsibilities
to the bondholders.''
   Trustees often are either invited or seek to serve on creditors
committees in order to represent the interests of the bondholders.
</TEXT>
