<FIRST>u f AM-BankAmericaLawsuit     03-10 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BankAmerica Lawsuit,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Shareholders Sue Over Loan Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two shareholders of BankAmerica Corp. have sued
company officers over a student-loan fiasco that could cost a group
of banks $450 million to $650 million, their law firm announced
Friday.
   BankAmerica announced Wednesday it was boosting its first-quarter
reserves to cover its part in losses that resulted from an unusually
high default rate on student vocational loans for which it acted as
trustee.
   The holding company for San Francisco-based Bank of America said
the addition to its reserves would not have a material effect on its
1989 earnings.
   Greenfield &amp; Chimicles, a Haverford, Pa.-based law firm, said it
was representing two shareholders in the suit, filed in the Court of
Chancery in Wilmington, Del.
   A news release from the law firm did not name the shareholder
plaintiffs or say what they were seeking. Richard D. Greenfield, the
lead attorney, did not return a phone call late Friday seeking
clarification.
   The student loan problems came to the surface when the Department
of Education decided to withdraw a federal guarantee on the loans,
triggering the prospect that the huge defaults would be borne by
banks that backed the loans with letters of credit.
   The letters of credit were issued by Citicorp and several
Japanese institutions, including Mitsubishi Bank Ltd.
</TEXT>
